u20131985: Party Secretary, [[Zhengding County]]\n}}\n----\n<center>'''[[Paramount leader|Paramount Leader of<br>the People's Republic of China]]'''<br>\n{{flatlist|\n* {{big|'''\u2190'''}} [[Hu Jintao]]\n* (''Current holder'')\n}}\n</center>\n| honorific_prefix = \n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n| pic = Xi Jinping (Chinese characters).svg\n| piccap = \"Xi Jinping\" in Simplified (top) and Traditional (bottom) Chinese characters\n| picupright = 0.495\n| s = \u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\n| t = \u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\n| p = X\u00ed J\u00ecnp\u00edng\n| bpmf = \u3112\u3127\u02ca \u3110\u3127\u3123\u02cb \u3106\u3127\u3125\u02ca\n| gr = Shyi Jinnpyng\n| w = Hsi<sup>2</sup> Chin<sup>4</sup>-p\u1ffeing<sup>2</sup>\n| tp = S\u00ed J\u00ecnp\u00edng\n| wyr = Sy\u00ed J\u00ecnp\u00edng\n| mps = Sh\u00ed J\u00ecn-p\u00edng\n| mi = {{IPAc-cmn|x|i|2|-|j|in|4|.|p|ing|2}}\n| h = Sip<sup>6</sup> Kiun<sup>4</sup> Pin<sup>2</sup><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.hkilang.org/NEW_WEB/page/dictionary |title = Association for Conversation of Hong Kong Indigenous Languages Online Dictionary |date=1 July 2015 |website=hkilang.org |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150701164520/http://www.hkilang.org/NEW_WEB/page/dictionary|archive-date=1 July 2015 |access-date=12 September 2019 }}</ref>\n| phfs = Si\u030dp Khiun-ph\u00ecn\n| y = Jaahp Gahn-p\u00echng\n| ci = {{IPAc-yue|z|aap|6|-|g|an|6|.|p|ing|4}}\n| j = Zaap6 Gan6-ping4\n| poj = Si\u030dp K\u012bn-p\u00eeng\n| tl = Si\u030dp K\u012bn-p\u00eeng\n| bp = S\u00edp G\u00een-b\u00edng\n| buc = S\u012dk G\u00ea\u0324\u1e73ng-ping\n| suz = Z\u00edh J\u00een-b\u01d0n\n| order = st\n}}\n{{Xi Jinping sidebar}}\n\n'''Xi Jinping'''{{efn Chinese name|[[Xi (surname)|X\u00ed]] ({{lang|zh-Hans|\u4e60|italic=no}})|reftype=NoteTag}} ({{IPAc-en|\u0283|i\u02d0|_|d\u0292|\u026a|n|\u02c8|p|\u026a|\u014b}}; {{zh|s={{linktext|\u4e60|\u8fd1|\u5e73}}|c=|t=|p=}}; {{small|[[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]] pronunciation}}: {{IPAc-cmn|x|i|2|-|j|in|4|.|p|ing|2|audio=\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73.ogg}}; born 15 June 1953) is a Chinese politician serving as the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]] of the [[Communist Party of China]] (CPC), [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]] of the [[China|People's Republic of China]] (PRC), and [[Chairman of the Central Military Commission|Chairman]] of the [[Central Military Commission (China)|Central Military Commission]] (CMC). Xi has been the [[paramount leader]], the [[Orders of precedence in China|highest-ranking]] official in China, since 2012 and he officially received the title of \"[[leadership core]]\" from the CPC in 2016. Xi has also been a member of the 17th, 18th, 19th [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|CPC Politburo Standing Committee]] since 2007.\n\nThe son of Chinese Communist veteran [[Xi Zhongxun]], he was exiled to rural [[Yanchuan County]] as a teenager following his father's purge during the [[Cultural Revolution]], and lived in a cave in the village of Liangjiahe, where he worked as the party secretary. After studying [[chemical engineering]] at the [[Tsinghua University]] as a \"[[Worker-Peasant-Soldier student]]\", Xi rose through the ranks politically in China's coastal provinces. Xi was governor of [[Fujian]] from 1999 to 2002. He was also governor, then [[Party Committee Secretary|party secretary]] of neighbouring [[Zhejiang]] from 2002 to 2007. Following the dismissal of the party secretary of Shanghai [[Chen Liangyu]], Xi was transferred to replace him for a brief period in 2007. He joined the [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|Politburo Standing Committee]] and [[Secretariat of the Communist Party of China Central Committee|central secretariat]] in October 2007, spending the next five years as Chinese paramount leader [[Hu Jintao|Hu Jintao's]] presumed [[Succession of power in the People's Republic of China|successor]]. Xi was [[Vice President of the People's Republic of China|vice president]] from 2008 to 2013 and [[Vice Chairman of the Central Military Commission]] from 2010 to 2012.\n\nXi is the first [[List of general secretaries and chairmen of the Communist Party of China|general secretary]] born after the [[Proclamation of the People's Republic of China|establishment]] of the People's Republic of China. Since assuming power, Xi has introduced far-ranging measures to enforce party discipline and to impose internal unity. His [[Anti-corruption campaign under Xi Jinping|anti-corruption campaign]] has led to the downfall of prominent incumbent and retired Communist Party officials, including members of the Politburo Standing Committee. He has also enacted or promoted more assertive foreign policy, particularly with regard to [[China\u2013Japan relations]], [[Territorial disputes in the South China Sea|China's claims]] in the [[South China Sea Islands|South China Sea]], and its advocacy for [[free trade]] and [[globalization]]. He has sought to expand China's African and Eurasian influence through the [[Belt and Road Initiative]].\n\nAs the central figure of the [[Generations of Chinese leadership|fifth generation of leadership]] of the People's Republic,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217211144/http://www.giga-hamburg.de/dl/download.php?d=%2Fcontent%2Fias%2Farchiv%2Fcds%2Fcds_0905.pdf|title=Journal of Current Chinese Affairs|last=|first=|date=May 2009|website=giga-hamburg.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archivedate=17 February 2012|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref> Xi has significantly centralised institutional power by taking on a wide range of leadership positions, including chairing the newly formed [[National Security Commission of the Communist Party of China|National Security Commission]], as well as new steering committees on economic and social reforms, military restructuring and modernization, and the Internet. Xi's [[Xi Jinping Thought|political thoughts]] have been written into the [[Constitution of the Communist Party of China|party]] and [[Constitution of the People's Republic of China|state constitutions]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/policies-politics/article/2111746/xi-jinpings-political-thought-will-be-added-chinas|title=Xi Jinping's political thought will be added to Chinese Communist Party constitution, but will his name be next to it?|last=Choi|first=Chi-yuk|date=18 September 2017|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=22 September 2017|last2=Jun|first2=Mai}}</ref> and a [[Xi Jinping's cult of personality|cult of personality]] has developed around him.<ref name=\"EconomistCultPersonality\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/china/21618882-cult-personality-growing-around-chinas-president-what-will-he-do-his-political|title=The power of Xi Jinping|last=|first=|date=18 September 2014|work=[[The Economist]]|access-date=20 September 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107055514/https://www.economist.com/news/china/21618882-cult-personality-growing-around-chinas-president-what-will-he-do-his-political|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"ForeignPolicyCultPersonality\">{{Cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/03/08/the-personality-cult-of-xi-jinping-china-leader-communist-party/|title=Behind the Personality Cult of Xi Jinping|last=Jiayang|first=Fan|last2=Taisu|first2=Zhang|date=8 March 2016|newspaper=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726173241/https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/03/08/the-personality-cult-of-xi-jinping-china-leader-communist-party/|archive-date=26 July 2019|access-date=26 July 2019|last3=Ying|first3=Zhu}}</ref> Xi has been labelled a \"[[dictator]]\" by some political observers citing an increase of [[Censorship in China|censorship]] and [[Mass surveillance in China|mass surveillance]], deterioration in [[Human rights in China|human rights]] and the removal of [[term limits]] for the [[President for life|President]] under his tenure.{{efn|Sources calling Xi Jinping a \"dictator\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/feb/26/xi-jinping-china-presidential-limit-scrap-dictator-for-life|title='Dictator for life': Xi Jinping's power grab condemned as step towards tyranny|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=26 February 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=12 August 2019|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/cb2c8578-adb4-11e7-aab9-abaa44b1e130|title=Under Xi Jinping, China is turning back to dictatorship|last=Anderlini|first=Jamil|date=11 October 2017|work=[[Financial Times]]|access-date=12 August 2019|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/made-by-history/wp/2018/03/05/dictatorship-nearly-destroyed-china-once-will-it-do-so-again/?noredirect=on|title=Dictatorship nearly destroyed China once. Will it do so again?|last=Radchenko|first=Sergey|date=5 March 2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=12 August 2019|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eastasiaforum.org/2018/04/02/a-deepening-dictatorship-promises-a-grim-future-for-china/|title=A deepening dictatorship promises a grim future for China|last=Carrico|first=Kevin|date=2 April 2018|work=[[East Asia Forum]]|access-date=12 August 2019|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/emasculate-america-the-dictators-plan-for-world-domination-l0t232nfx|title=Emasculate America: The dictator\u2019s plan for world domination|last=Stelzer|first=Irwin|date=4 March 2018|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=12 August 2019|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/asia/2019/06/21/kim-jong-un-entertains-xi-jinping-at-home|title=Kim Jong Un entertains Xi Jinping at home|date=21 June 2019|work=The Economist|access-date=17 August 2019|issn=0013-0613|quote=It was Mr Xi\u2019s first visit to North Korea since he and Mr Kim took the helm of their respective countries... It is not known what precisely the two dictators discussed once they retired to a guest house for talks.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/china-xi-jinping-ban-823823|title=China's war on words show Xi Jinping is a dictator for life {{!}} Opinion|last=Mair|first=Victor H.|date=28 February 2018|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=17 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/opinion-xi-jinping-todays-chairman-tomorrows-dictator/a-42747054|title=Opinion: Xi Jinping \u2013 Today's chairman, tomorrow's dictator?|last=Hein|first=Matthias|date=26 February 2018|website=Deutsche Welle|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/blog/china-likely-enter-another-long-period-severe-dictatorship|title=China Is Likely to Enter Another Long Period of Severe Dictatorship|last=Cohen|first=Jerome A.|date=28 February 2018|website=Council on Foreign Relations|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/donald-trump-xi-jinping-bad-leadership-by-chris-patten-2019-07|title=Great Countries, Bad Leaders|last=Patten|first=Chris|date=30 July 2019|website=Project Syndicate|language=en|access-date=17 August 2019|quote=Moreover, Xi is deploying cutting-edge technology to reinforce his dictatorship.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2018-02-26/china-and-xi-jinping-toss-aside-their-experiment-with-stability|title=China Now Faces the Downsides of Dictatorship|last=Feldman|first=Noah|date=27 February 2018|work=Bloomberg|access-date=17 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/nov/23/chinese-export-repression-xi-jinping-mao-china-hong-kong|title=The Chinese export we really should be worried about: repression|last=Tisdall|first=Simon|date=23 November 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=17 August 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|quote=What is different, and underappreciated in the west, is the way Xi is inexorably and single-mindedly expanding draconian systems of social control centred on the Communist party and the de facto dictatorship of one man: himself.}}</ref>}} \n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\n[[File:Xi Jinping, Xi Yuanping and Xi Zhongxun in 1958.jpg|left|thumb|Five-year-old Xi Jinping (left) with younger brother [[Xi Yuanping]] (center) and father [[Xi Zhongxun]] (right) in 1958]]\n\nXi Jinping was born in Beijing on 15 June 1953, the second son of [[Xi Zhongxun]] and his wife [[Qi Xin]]. After the [[Proclamation of the People's Republic of China|founding]] of the People's Republic of China in 1949 by [[Mao Zedong]], Xi's father held a series of posts, including [[Propaganda Department of the Communist Party of China|Party propaganda]] chief, [[Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China|vice-premier]], and [[Vice Chairperson of the National People's Congress]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/china-profile-xi-jinping/24764283.html|title=Profile: Chinese Vice President Xi Jinping|last=|first=|date=7 November 2012|work=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]|access-date=26 August 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019083336/http://www.rferl.org/content/china-profile-xi-jinping/24764283.html|archive-date=19 October 2013}}</ref> Xi had two older sisters, [[Qi Qiaoqiao|Qiaoqiao]] ({{zh|c=\u6865\u6865}}), born in 1949 and An'an ({{zh|c=\u5b89\u5b89}}), born in 1952.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://news.xinhuanet.com/book/2009-04/28/content_11270872.htm |script-title=zh:\u8207\u4e08\u592b\u7fd2\u4ef2\u52db\u76f8\u4f3458\u5e74 \u9f4a\u5fc3\uff1a\u9019\u8f29\u5b50\u7121\u6bd4\u5e78\u798f |date=28 April 2009 |newspaper=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |language=zh-Hant|trans-title=With her husband Xi Zhongxun for 58 years: very happy in this life|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128102212/http://news.xinhuanet.com/book/2009-04/28/content_11270872.htm|archive-date=28 January 2013|access-date=18 March 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"laoren2\">{{cite web|url=http://book.people.com.cn/BIG5/n/2013/0527/c69360-21628126.html |last=Xu|first=Xinyi|date=27 May 2013|website=[[People's Daily]]|language=zh-Hant|script-title=zh:\u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\"\u5bb6\u98a8\"\u63ed\u79d8 \u9f4a\u5fc3\u81ea\u8ff0\u8207\u7fd2\u4ef2\u52db\u5a5a\u59fb\u5f80\u4e8b|trans-title=Xi Jinping's \"family traditions\" are unmasked: Qi Xin's autobiographical account of her marriage to Xi Zhongxun|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428053410/http://book.people.com.cn/BIG5/n/2013/0527/c69360-21628126.html|archive-date=28 April 2017|access-date=27 April 2017}}</ref> Xi's father was from [[Fuping County, Shaanxi|Fuping County]], Shaanxi, and Xi could further trace his [[patrilineal]] descent from Xiying in [[Dengzhou]], Henan.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://hn.wenweipo.com/news/zhuanti/2012-11-16/23713.html |script-title=zh:\u672c\u5831\u7368\u5bb6\u63a2\u8a2a\u6cb3\u5357\u9127\u5dde\u7fd2\u71df\u6751|last=Fangqin|first=Sun|date=16 November 2012|work=[[Wen Wei Po]]|accessdate=15 November 2012|language=zh-Hant|trans-title=This Newspaper's Exclusive Visit To Xiying Village, Dengzhou County, Henan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123040758/http://hn.wenweipo.com/news/zhuanti/2012-11-16/23713.html|archive-date=23 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nXi went to the [[Beijing 101 Middle School]] in the 1960s. There, he developed a close friendship with [[Liu He (politician)|Liu He]], who later became China's vice-premier and a close advisor to Xi after he became China's paramount leader.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/29/power-behind-the-thrones-10-movers-and-shakers-for-2020|title=The power behind the thrones: 10 political movers and shakers who will shape 2020|last=Tisdall|first=Simon|date=29 December 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=16 January 2020|url-status=live|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712|author-link=Simon Tisdall}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/blessed-by-xi-jinping-the-new-captain-of-chinas-economy-1519688592|title=Who Is 'Uncle He?' The Man in Charge of China's Economy|last=Wei|first=Lingling|date=27 February 2018|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=16 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1963, when he was age 10, his father was purged from the Party and sent to work in a factory in [[Luoyang]], Henan.{{sfn|Bou\u00e9e|2010|p=93}} In May 1966, the [[Cultural Revolution]] cut short Xi's secondary education when all secondary classes were halted for students to criticise and fight their teachers. Student militants ransacked the Xi family home and one of Xi's sisters, Xi Heping, was killed.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite news |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/25/world/asia/xi-jinping-china-cultural-revolution.html |title=Cultural Revolution Shaped Xi Jinping, From Schoolboy to Survivor |last1=Buckley|first1=Chris |last2=Tatlow|first2=Didi Kirsten|date=24 September 2015 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=6 March 2018|url-status=live |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180305150638/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/25/world/asia/xi-jinping-china-cultural-revolution.html |archive-date=5 March 2018 |url-access=limited }}</ref> Later, his mother was forced to publicly denounce his father, as he was paraded before a crowd as an enemy of the revolution. His father was later thrown into prison in 1968 when Xi was aged 15. Without the protection of his father, Xi was sent to work in Liangjiahe Village, Wen'anyi Town, [[Yanchuan County]], Yan'an, Shaanxi, in 1969 in Mao Zedong's [[Down to the Countryside Movement]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://v.youku.com/v_show/id_XMzM2NTc1MjAwOA==.html |script-title=zh:\u4e0d\u5fd8\u521d\u5fc3\uff1a\u662f\u4ec0\u4e48\u9020\u5c31\u4e86\u4eca\u5929\u7684\u4e60\u4e3b\u5e2d\uff1f|date=30 January 2018|website=[[Youku]]|language=zh-Hans |trans-title=What Were His Original Intentions? The President Xi of Today |url-status=live |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180130204306/http://v.youku.com/v_show/id_XMzM2NTc1MjAwOA==.html |archive-date=30 January 2018 |access-date=30 January 2018}}</ref> He worked as the [[Party Committee Secretary|party secretary]] of Liangjiahe, where he lived in a cave.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/11/09/164684418/for-chinas-rising-leader-a-cave-was-once-home?t=1578589261050|title=For China's Rising Leader, A Cave Was Once Home|last=Lim|first=Louisa|date=9 November 2012|work=[[NPR]]|access-date=27 October 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616053635/https://www.npr.org/2012/11/09/164684418/for-chinas-rising-leader-a-cave-was-once-home|archive-date=16 June 2018}}</ref> After a few months, unable to stand rural life, he ran away to Beijing. He was arrested during a crackdown on deserters from the countryside and sent to a work camp to dig ditches.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2012/02/14/chinas_political_star_xi_jinping_is_a_study_in_contrasts.html |title=China's political star Xi Jinping is a study in contrasts |last1=Demick|first1=Barbara|last2=Pierson|first2=David |date=14 February 2012|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=24 October 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171013225355/https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2012/02/14/chinas_political_star_xi_jinping_is_a_study_in_contrasts.html |archive-date=13 October 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter being rejected seven times, Xi joined the [[Communist Youth League of China]] in 1971 by befriending a local official.<ref name=\"newyorker2\" /> He reunited with his father in 1972, because of a family reunion ordered by [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]] [[Zhou Enlai]].<ref name=\":10\" /> From 1973, he applied to join the [[Communist Party of China]] ten times and was finally accepted on his tenth attempt in 1974.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/radio/thecurrent/the-current-for-february-28-2018-1.4555132/wednesday-february-28-2018-full-text-transcript-1.4556381#segment3|title=\"The Current\" - Wednesday February 28, 2018 Full Text Transcript|last=|first=|date=28 February 2018|newspaper=[[CBC Radio]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324194159/http://www.cbc.ca/radio/thecurrent/the-current-for-february-28-2018-1.4555132/wednesday-february-28-2018-full-text-transcript-1.4556381#segment3|archive-date=24 March 2018|access-date=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url = https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Zy479_jx11YJ:www.aerospaceindia.org/Issue%2520Briefs/2010/25%2520October%25202010%2520-%2520CHINA%25E2%2580%2599S%2520NEXT%2520CHAIRMAN%25E2%2580%2594XI%2520JINPING.pdf+&hl=en&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjpQjUAtfkdEgw0cxv3UMunFfoLBcy0_po2aPN4xvPoQ-K9lFpIdgtf7PAw5ebYoTd8NwaRSswzfWmws278UPehKckL3Zb0TXlci2R0HsZGceCYRpBiD6EfBrspdjUh8CZzwcMg&sig=AHIEtbRjgFp8BCiHybWUtaP2uVF8BVuVZA |title=China's Next Chairman \u2013 Xi Jinping |last=Ranade|first=Jayadva|date=25 October 2010|newspaper=Centre for Air Power Studies|access-date=27 May 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130724125447/https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache%3AZy479_jx11YJ%3Awww.aerospaceindia.org%2FIssue%2520Briefs%2F2010%2F25%2520October%25202010%2520-%2520CHINA%25E2%2580%2599S%2520NEXT%2520CHAIRMAN%25E2%2580%2594XI%2520JINPING.pdf+&hl=en&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjpQjUAtfkdEgw0cxv3UMunFfoLBcy0_po2aPN4xvPoQ-K9lFpIdgtf7PAw5ebYoTd8NwaRSswzfWmws278UPehKckL3Zb0TXlci2R0HsZGceCYRpBiD6EfBrspdjUh8CZzwcMg&sig=AHIEtbRjgFp8BCiHybWUtaP2uVF8BVuVZA |archive-date=24 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1975 to 1979, Xi studied [[chemical engineering]] at Beijing's [[Tsinghua University]] as a \"[[Worker-Peasant-Soldier student]]\". The engineering majors there spent about 15 percent of their time studying [[Marxism\u2013Leninism\u2013Mao Zedong thought]] and 5 percent of their time doing farm work and \"learning from the People's Liberation Army\".{{sfn|Simon|Cong|p=28\u201329|2009}}\n\n==Rise to power==\nFrom 1979 to 1982, Xi served as secretary for his father's former subordinate [[Geng Biao]], the then [[Vice Premier of the State Council of the People's Republic of China|vice premier]] and secretary-general of the [[Central Military Commission (China)|Central Military Commission]]. This gained Xi some military background.<ref name=\"newyorker2\" /> In 1985, as part of a Chinese delegation to study U.S. agriculture, he stayed in the home of an American family in the town of [[Muscatine, Iowa]]. This trip, and his two-week stay with a U.S. family, is said to have had a lasting impression upon him and his views on the United States.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.thestreet.com/story/13300612/1/president-xi-slept-here-how-a-trip-to-iowa-in-1985-changed-u-s-china-relations.html |title=President Xi Slept Here: How a Trip to Iowa in 1985 Changed U.S.-China Relations |last=Dvorchak|first=Gary|date=24 September 2015|work=[[TheStreet.com|The Street]]|access-date=7 September 2019 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160418172931/http://www.thestreet.com/story/13300612/1/president-xi-slept-here-how-a-trip-to-iowa-in-1985-changed-u-s-china-relations.html |archive-date=18 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, he was sent to [[Zhengding County]] in Hebei as deputy party secretary of Zhengding County. He was promoted in 1983 to secretary, becoming the top official of the county.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/china/xi-jinping.htm|title=Xi Jinping|last=|first=|date=|website=[[GlobalSecurity.org]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111205052644/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/china/xi-jinping.htm|archive-date=5 December 2011|access-date=27 May 2012}}</ref> Xi subsequently served in four provinces during his regional political career: Hebei (1982\u20131985), [[Fujian]] (1985\u20132002), [[Zhejiang]] (2002\u20132007), and Shanghai (2007).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/xi-jinping-from-graft-fighting-governor-to-chinas-most-powerful-leader-since-mao|title=Xi Jinping: From graft-fighting governor to China's most powerful leader since Mao Zedong|last=|first=|date=11 March 2018|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818052957/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/xi-jinping-from-graft-fighting-governor-to-chinas-most-powerful-leader-since-mao|archive-date=18 August 2019|access-date=18 August 2019}}</ref> Xi held posts in the [[Fuzhou]] Municipal Party Committee and became the president of the Party School in Fuzhou in 1990. In 1997, he was named an alternate member of the [[15th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]]. However, of the 151 alternate members of the Central Committee elected at the 15th Party Congress, Xi received the lowest number of votes in favour, placing him last in the rankings of members, ostensibly due to his status as a [[Princelings|princeling]].{{NoteTag|[[Liu Yandong]], [[Wang Qishan]], and [[Deng Pufang]] (Deng Xiaoping's son) all placed among the bottom of the alternate member list. Like Xi, all three were seen as \"princelings\". [[Bo Xilai]] was not elected to the Central Committee at all; that is, Bo placed lower in the vote count than Xi.}}<ref name=\"canyu2\">{{cite news |url = http://www.canyu.org/n24349c6.aspx |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u5171\u5341\u4e94\u5927\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u4f4d\u5217\u5019\u8865\u59d4\u5458\u6700\u540e\u4e00\u540d\u4e3a\u4f55 |date=22 April 2011|website=Canyu.org|access-date=7 September 2019|language=zh-Hans|trans-title=Why Is Xi Jinping, At the 15th CCP National Congress, Being Waited On To Fill The Last Committee Member Position?|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141334/http://www.canyu.org/n24349c6.aspx|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1998 to 2002, Xi studied Marxist theory and ideological education in Tsinghua University,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.people.cn/90001/90776/6288506.html|title=Xi Jinping -- Politburo Standing Committee member of CPC Central Committee |date=22 October 2007|website=[[People's Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630190420/http://en.people.cn/90001/90776/6288506.html|archive-date=30 June 2015|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> graduating from there with a doctorate in law and ideology in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/oct/26/china.uknews4|title=Most corrupt officials are from poor families but Chinese royals have a spirit that is not dominated by money|last=Watts|first=Jonathan|date=26 October 2007|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=11 June 2008|location=London, England|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901014357/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/oct/26/china.uknews4|archive-date=1 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1999, he was promoted to the office of Vice Governor of Fujian, then he became governor a year later. In Fujian, Xi made efforts to attract investment from Taiwan and to strengthen the private sector of the provincial economy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thediplomat.com/2014/11/from-fujian-chinas-xi-offers-economic-olive-branch-to-taiwan/|title=From Fujian, China's Xi Offers Economic Olive Branch to Taiwan|last=Tiezzi|first=Shannon|date=4 November 2014|newspaper=[[The Diplomat]]|language=en-US|url-access=limited|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610145941/http://thediplomat.com/2014/11/from-fujian-chinas-xi-offers-economic-olive-branch-to-taiwan/|archive-date=10 June 2016|access-date=17 March 2016}}</ref> In February 2000, he and then-provincial Party Secretary [[Chen Mingyi]] were called before the top members of the Party Central [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China]]&nbsp;\u2013 General Secretary [[Jiang Zemin]], Premier [[Zhu Rongji]], Vice-President [[Hu Jintao]] and [[Central Commission for Discipline Inspection|Discipline Inspection]] Secretary [[Wei Jianxing]]&nbsp;\u2013 to explain aspects of the [[Yuanhua scandal]].<ref name=\"scmpxiao2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/article/308424/fujian-leaders-face-beijing-top-brass|title=Fujian leaders face Beijing top brass|last=Yu|first=Xiao|date=18 February 2000|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029030831/https://www.scmp.com/article/308424/fujian-leaders-face-beijing-top-brass|archive-date=29 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Xi left Fujian and took up leading political positions in neighbouring Zhejiang. He eventually took over as provincial [[Party Committee Secretary]] after several months as acting governor, occupying a top provincial office for the first time in his career. In 2002, he was elected a full member of the [[16th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|16th Central Committee]], marking his ascension to the national stage. While in Zhejiang, Xi presided over reported growth rates averaging 14% per year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1068825/chinas-leadership-transition-xi-jinpings-time-zhejiang|title=Xi Jinping's time in Zhejiang: doing the business|last=Ho|first=Louise|date=25 October 2012|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429160349/http://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1068825/chinas-leadership-transition-xi-jinpings-time-zhejiang|archive-date=29 April 2016|access-date=9 December 2019}}</ref> His career in Zhejiang was marked by a tough and straightforward stance against corrupt officials. This earned him a name in the national media and drew the attention of China's top leaders.<ref name=\"wanglei2\">{{cite news|url=http://opinion.dwnews.com/news/2014-12-25/59626005.html |script-title=zh:\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u4e3a\u5b98\u4e4b\u9053 \u62ce\u7740\u4e4c\u7eb1\u5e3d\u5e72\u4e8b|last1=Wang|first1=Lei|date=25 December 2014|work=[[Duowei News]]|access-date=7 September 2019|language=zh-hans|trans-title=Xi Jinping's Governmental Path - Carries Official Administrative Posts|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203225014/http://opinion.dwnews.com/news/2014-12-25/59626005.html|archive-date=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the dismissal of Shanghai Party secretary [[Chen Liangyu]] in September 2006 due to a [[Shanghai pension scandal|social security fund scandal]], Xi was transferred to Shanghai in March 2007 where he was the party secretary there for seven months.<ref name=\"shanghai2\">{{cite news|url=http://news.sohu.com/20070324/n248946143.shtml|script-title=zh:\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u4efb\u4e0a\u6d77\u5e02\u59d4\u4e66\u8bb0 \u97e9\u6b63\u4e0d\u518d\u4ee3\u7406\u5e02\u59d4\u4e66\u8bb0|last=|first=|date=24 March 2007|work=[[Sohu]]|access-date=7 September 2019|language=zh-Hans|trans-title=Xi Jinping is Secretary of Shanghai Municipal Party Committee - Han Zheng is No Longer Acting Party Secretary|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016061557/http://news.sohu.com/20070324/n248946143.shtml|archive-date=16 October 2007|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-20322288|title=China new leaders: Xi Jinping heads line-up for politburo|last=|first=|date=15 November 2012|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=25 August 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190909102154/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-20322288|archive-date=9 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> In Shanghai, Xi avoided controversy and was known for strictly observing party discipline. For example, Shanghai administrators attempted to earn favour with him by arranging a special train to shuttle him between Shanghai and [[Hangzhou]] for him to complete handing off his work to his successor as Zhejiang party secretary [[Zhao Hongzhu]]. However, Xi reportedly refused to take the train, citing a loosely enforced party regulation which stipulated that special trains can only be reserved for \"national leaders\".<ref name=\"ming2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.boxun.com/news/gb/china/2013/07/201307110449.shtml#.VTxXVvnF_tU|script-title=zh:\u4ece\u4e0a\u6d77\u5230\u5317\u4eac \u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u8d34\u8eab\u79d8\u4e66\u53ea\u6709\u949f\u7ecd\u519b|last=|first=|date=11 July 2013|work=[[Mingjing News]]|access-date=12 September 2019|language=zh-hans|trans-title=From Shanghai to Beijing, Zhong Shaojun Has Been Xi Jinping\u2019s Only Personal Secretary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141343/http://www.boxun.com/news/gb/china/2013/07/201307110449.shtml#.VTxXVvnF_tU|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> While in Shanghai, he worked on preserving unity of the local party organisation. He pledged there would be no 'purges' during his administration, despite the fact many local officials were thought to have been implicated in the Chen Liangyu corruption scandal.{{sfn|Lam|2015|p=56}} On most issues Xi largely echoed the line of the central leadership.<ref name=\"newin2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.caijing.com.cn/2007-10-22/100034588.html |script-title=zh:\u65b0\u664b\u653f\u6cbb\u5c40\u5e38\u59d4\uff1a\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73|last=|first=|date=22 October 2007|work=[[Caijing]]|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222175301/http://www.caijing.com.cn/2007-10-22/100034588.html|archive-date=22 December 2015|language=zh-hans|trans-title=Newly Appointed Member of Politburo Standing Committee: Xi Jinping}}</ref>\n\n==Politburo Standing Committee member==\n[[File:President George W. Bush with Vice President Xi Jinping.jpg|thumb|Xi Jinping greeting U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] in August 2008]]\n[[File:Dmitry Medvedev in China 28 September 2010-6.jpeg|thumb|Xi Jinping with Russian President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] on 28 September 2010]]\n\nXi was appointed to the nine-man Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China at the [[17th National Congress of the Communist Party of China|17th Party Congress]] in October 2007. He was ranked above [[Li Keqiang]], an indication that he was going to succeed Hu Jintao as China's [[Succession of power in the People's Republic of China|next leader]]. In addition, Xi also held the top-ranking membership of the Communist Party's [[Secretariat of the Communist Party of China Central Committee|Central Secretariat]]. This assessment was further supported at the [[11th National People's Congress]] in March 2008, when Xi was elected as [[Vice-President of the People's Republic of China|vice-president]] of the People's Republic of China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2008npc/2008-03/15/content_6539302.htm|title=Hu Jintao reelected Chinese president|last=|first=|date=15 March 2008|newspaper=[[China Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055352/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2008npc/2008-03/15/content_6539302.htm|archive-date=4 March 2016|access-date=8 September 2019}}</ref> Following his elevation, Xi has held a broad range of portfolios. He was put in charge of the comprehensive preparations for the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in Beijing, as well as being the central government's leading figure in Hong Kong and Macau affairs. In addition, he also became the new president of the [[Central Party School of the Communist Party of China]], the cadre-training and ideological education wing of the Communist Party. In the wake of the [[2008 Sichuan earthquake]], Xi visited disaster areas in [[Shaanxi]] and [[Gansu]]. He made his first foreign trip as vice president to North Korea, Mongolia, Saudi Arabia, Qatar and Yemen from 17 to 25 June 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.mfa.gov.cn/eng/wjdt/wsrc/t462294.htm |title=Vice-President Xi Jinping to Visit DPRK, Mongolia, Saudi Arabia, Qatar and Yemen|date=5 June 2008|website=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]]|access-date=20 October 2010 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110723214209/http://www.mfa.gov.cn/eng/wjdt/wsrc/t462294.htm|archive-date=23 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> After the Olympics, Xi was assigned the post of committee chair for the preparations of the [[60th Anniversary of the People's Republic of China|60th Anniversary Celebrations]] of the founding of the People's Republic of China. He was also reportedly at the helm of a top-level Communist Party committee dubbed the [[6521 Project]], which was charged with ensuring social stability during a series of politically sensitive anniversaries in 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/10/world/asia/10china.html|title=China's Leaders See a Calendar Full of Anniversaries, and Trouble|last=Wines|first=Michael|date=9 March 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=8 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721045913/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/10/world/asia/10china.html|archive-date=21 July 2016|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nXi's position as the apparent successor to become the paramount leader was threatened with the rapid rise of [[Bo Xilai]], the party secretary of [[Chongqing]] at the time. Bo was expected to join the Politburo Standing Committee at the [[18th National Congress of the Communist Party of China|18th Party Congress]], with the possibility of creating a counterweight to Xi, or even replacing him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d67b90f0-d140-11e1-8957-00144feabdc0|title=Bo Xilai: power, death and politics|last=Anderlini|first=Jamil|date=20 July 2012|work=[[Financial Times]]|access-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Bo's policies in Chongqing inspired imitations throughout China and received praise from Xi himself during Xi's visit to Chongqing in 2010. Records of praises from Xi were later erased after he became paramount leader. Xi's position as successor was secured with Bo's downfall due to the [[Wang Lijun incident]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/10/19/the-resistible-rise-of-xi-jinping/|title=The Resistible Rise of Xi Jinping|last=Palmer|first=James|date=19 October 2017|work=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]]|access-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nXi is considered one of the most successful members of the [[Crown Prince Party]], a quasi-clique of politicians who are descendants of early Chinese Communist revolutionaries. Former prime minister of Singapore, [[Lee Kuan Yew]], when asked about Xi, said he felt he was \"a thoughtful man who has gone through many trials and tribulations\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/xi-jinping-chinas-new-boss-and-l-word-95021|title=Xi Jinping: China's New Boss And The 'L' Word|last=Ansfield|first=Jonathan|date=22 December 2007|work=[[Newsweek]]|access-date=20 October 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330064319/http://www.newsweek.com/id/81558|archive-date=30 March 2010}}</ref> Lee also commented: \"I would put him in the [[Nelson Mandela]] class of persons. A person with enormous emotional stability who does not allow his personal misfortunes or sufferings affect his judgment. In other words, he is impressive\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://china.blogs.time.com/2007/11/19/chinas_nelson_mandela/|title=China's Nelson Mandela|last=Elegant|first=Simon|date=19 November 2007|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=8 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090728171010/http://china.blogs.time.com/2007/11/19/chinas_nelson_mandela/|archive-date=28 July 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Former U.S. Treasury Secretary [[Henry Paulson]] described Xi as \"the kind of guy who knows how to get things over the goal line\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aDpLoVnlKn6E&refer=home|title=China Appoints Xi Vice President, Heir Apparent to Hu|last=Elegant|first=Simon|date=15 March 2008|newspaper=[[Bloomberg News]]|url-access=limited|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 October 2010}}</ref> Australian Prime Minister [[Kevin Rudd]] said that Xi \"has sufficient reformist, party and military background to be very much his own man\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/rudd-seeks-to-pre-empt-pms-china-white-paper-with-his-own-version/story-fn59niix-1226488505695|title=Rudd seeks to pre-empt PM's China white paper with his own version|last=Uren|first=David|date=5 October 2012|work=[[The Australian]]|access-date=8 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121122083821/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/rudd-seeks-to-pre-empt-pms-china-white-paper-with-his-own-version/story-fn59niix-1226488505695|archive-date=22 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Trips as Vice President and Mexico commentary incident===\nIn February 2009, in his capacity as vice-president, Xi Jinping embarked on a tour of Latin America, visiting Mexico,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.people.cn/90001/90776/90883/6589461.html|title=Chinese vice president arrives in Mexico for official visit|last=|first=|date=10 February 2009|work=[[People's Daily]]|access-date=11 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Jamaica,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cctv.com/english/20090213/101253.shtml|title=China, Jamaica vow to enhance friendly partnership |date=13 February 2009|newspaper=[[China Central Television]]|access-date=8 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028093629/http://www.cctv.com/english/20090213/101253.shtml|archive-date=28 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Colombia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.people.cn/90001/90776/90883/6594636.html|title=Chinese vice president continues visit in Colombia|last=|first=|date=17 February 2009|website=[[People's Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 September 2019}}</ref> Venezuela,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.cn/english/2009-02/18/content_1235145.htm|title=Chinese VP praises friendly cooperation with Venezuela, Latin America|last=Zhang|first=Xiang|date=18 February 2009|website=[[Government of China]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 September 2019}}</ref> and Brazil<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.china.org.cn/international/2009-02/20/content_17311463.htm|title=Xi Jinping\u00a0proposes efforts to boost cooperation with Brazil |date=20 February 2009|website=[[China Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206063031/http://china.org.cn/international/2009-02/20/content_17311463.htm|archive-date=6 February 2011|access-date=11 September 2019}}</ref> to promote Chinese ties in the region and boost the country's reputation in the wake of the [[Great Recession|global financial crisis]]. He also visited [[Valletta]], Malta, before returning to China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/chinese-vice-president-begins-official-visit.245968|title=Chinese vice president begins official visit|last=|first=|date=22 February 2009|newspaper=[[Times of Malta]]|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 February, while visiting Mexico, Xi spoke in front of a group of [[overseas Chinese]] and explained China's contributions to the financial crisis, saying that it was \"the greatest contribution towards the whole of human race, made by China, to prevent its 1.3&nbsp;billion people from hunger\".{{NoteTag|Original {{zh|s=\u5728\u56fd\u9645\u91d1\u878d\u98ce\u66b4\u4e2d\uff0c\u4e2d\u56fd\u80fd\u57fa\u672c\u89e3\u51b313\u4ebf\u4eba\u53e3\u5403\u996d\u7684\u95ee\u9898\uff0c\u5df2\u7ecf\u662f\u5bf9\u5168\u4eba\u7c7b\u6700\u4f1f\u5927\u7684\u8d21\u732e|t=\u5728\u570b\u969b\u91d1\u878d\u98a8\u66b4\u4e2d\uff0c\u4e2d\u570b\u80fd\u57fa\u672c\u89e3\u6c7a13\u5104\u4eba\u53e3\u5403\u98ef\u7684\u554f\u984c\uff0c\u5df2\u7d93\u662f\u5c0d\u5168\u4eba\u985e\u6700\u5049\u5927\u7684\u8ca2\u737b}}|}} He went on to remark: \"There are some bored foreigners, with full stomachs, who have nothing better to do than point fingers at us. First, China doesn't export revolution; second, China doesn't export hunger and poverty; third, China doesn't come and cause you headaches.  What more is there to be said?\"{{NoteTag|Original: {{zh|s=\u6709\u4e9b\u5403\u9971\u6ca1\u4e8b\u5e72\u7684\u5916\u56fd\u4eba\uff0c\u5bf9\u6211\u4eec\u7684\u4e8b\u60c5\u6307\u624b\u753b\u811a\u3002\u4e2d\u56fd\u4e00\u4e0d\u8f93\u51fa\u9769\u547d\uff0c\u4e8c\u4e0d\u8f93\u51fa\u9965\u997f\u548c\u8d2b\u56f0\uff0c\u4e09\u4e0d\u6298\u817e\u4f60\u4eec\uff0c\u8fd8\u6709\u4ec0\u4e48\u597d\u8bf4\u7684\uff1f|t=\u6709\u4e9b\u5403\u98fd\u6c92\u4e8b\u5e72\u7684\u5916\u570b\u4eba\uff0c\u5c0d\u6211\u5011\u7684\u4e8b\u60c5\u6307\u624b\u756b\u8173\u3002\u4e2d\u570b\u4e00\u4e0d\u8f38\u51fa\u9769\u547d\uff0c\u4e8c\u4e0d\u8f38\u51fa\u98e2\u9913\u548c\u8ca7\u56f0\uff0c\u4e09\u4e0d\u6298\u9a30\u4f60\u5011\uff0c\u9084\u6709\u4ec0\u9ebd\u597d\u8aaa\u7684\uff1f}}}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/the%2BStraits%2BTimes/Story/A1Story20090214-121872.html|title=Chinese VP blasts meddlesome foreigners|last=Sim|first=Chi Yin|date=14 February 2009|newspaper=[[AsiaOne]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711171035/http://news.asiaone.com/News/the%2BStraits%2BTimes/Story/A1Story20090214-121872.html|archive-date=11 July 2011|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref> The story was reported on some local television stations. The news led to a flood of discussions on Chinese Internet forums and it was reported that the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs was caught off-guard by Xi's remarks, as the actual video was shot by some accompanying Hong Kong reporters and broadcast on Hong Kong TV, which then turned up on various Internet video websites.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://udn.com/NEWS/MAINLAND/MAI1/4742366.shtml |script-title=zh:\u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\u51fa\u8a2a\u7f75\u8001\u5916 \u5916\u4ea4\u90e8\u634f\u51b7\u6c57|last1=Lai|first1=Jinhong|date=18 February 2009|newspaper=[[United Daily News]]|accessdate=27 February 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221023838/http://udn.com/NEWS/MAINLAND/MAI1/4742366.shtml|archive-date=21 February 2009|language=zh-hans|trans-title=Xi Jinping Goes and Scolds at Foreigners, Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Cold Sweat}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[European Union]], Xi visited Belgium, Germany, Bulgaria, Hungary and Romania from 7 to 21 October 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.china-un.ch/eng/xwdt/t622138.htm|title=A Journey of Friendship, Cooperation and Culture \u2013 Vice Foreign Minister Zhang Zhijun Sums Up Chinese Vice President Xi Jinping's Trip to 5 European Countries|last=|first=|date=21 October 2009|website=[[Permanent Representative of China to the United Nations]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 September 2019}}</ref> He visited Japan, South Korea, Cambodia, and Myanmar on his Asian trip from 14 to 22 December 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/papers36/paper3566.html|title=China's Cousin-Cousin Relations with Myanmar|last=Raman|first=B.|date=25 December 2009|website=[[South Asia Analysis Group]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317074826/http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/papers36/paper3566.html|archivedate=17 March 2010|accessdate=14 February 2012}}</ref> He later visited the United States, Ireland and Turkey in February 2012. This visit included meeting with then U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] at the White House<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/01/24/us-usa-china-xi-idUSTRE80N06E20120124|title=China leader-in-waiting Xi to visit White House next month|last=Bull|first=Alister|date=24 January 2012|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|access-date=28 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029201614/https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/01/24/us-usa-china-xi-idUSTRE80N06E20120124|archive-date=29 October 2013|last2=Buckley|first2=Chris}}</ref> and then Vice President [[Joe Biden]]; and stops in California and [[Iowa]], where he met with the family which previously hosted him during his 1985 tour as a [[Hebei]] provincial official.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/16/world/asia/xi-jinping-of-china-makes-a-return-trip-to-iowa.html|title=Xi Jinping of China Makes a Return Trip to Iowa|last=Johnson|first=Kirk|date=15 February 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=12 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621114147/https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/16/world/asia/xi-jinping-of-china-makes-a-return-trip-to-iowa.html|archive-date=21 June 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n===Disappearance===\nA few months before his ascendancy to the party leadership, Xi disappeared from official media coverage for several weeks beginning on 1 September 2012. On 4 September, he cancelled a meeting with U.S. Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]], and later also cancelled meetings with Singapore's Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]] and a top Russian official. It was said that Xi effectively \"went on strike\" in preparation for the power transition in order to install political allies in key roles.<ref name=\"newyorker2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/04/06/born-red|title=Born Red|last1=Osnos|first1=Evan|date=30 March 2015|work=[[The New Yorker]]|access-date=11 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004153259/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/04/06/born-red|archive-date=4 October 2019|author-link=Evan Osnos}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported from a single source that Xi may have been injured in an altercation during a meeting of the \"[[Princelings|red second generation]]\" which turned violent.<ref name=\"wpost2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2012/11/01/the-secret-story-behind-xi-jinpings-disappearance-finally-revealed/|title=The secret story behind Xi Jinping's disappearance, finally revealed?|last1=Fisher|first1=Max|date=1 November 2012|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=11 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028225746/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2012/11/01/the-secret-story-behind-xi-jinpings-disappearance-finally-revealed/|archive-date=28 October 2018|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n==Leadership==\n===Accession to top posts===\n{{See also|Generations of Chinese leadership|Succession of power in China}}\nOn 15 November 2012, Xi was elected to the posts of [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|general secretary of the Communist Party]] and [[Chairman of the Central Military Commission|chairman of the CPC Central Military Commission]] by the [[18th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]]. This made him, informally, the [[paramount leader]] and the first to be born after the founding of the People's Republic of China. The following day Xi led the new line-up of the [[Politburo Standing Committee]] onto the stage in their first public appearance.<ref name=\"BBCconfirm2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-20322288|title=China Confirms Leadership Change|last=|first=|date=17 November 2012|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=15 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729201558/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-20322288|archive-date=29 July 2016}}</ref> The new Standing Committee reduced its number of seats from nine to seven, with only Xi himself and [[Li Keqiang]] retaining their seats from the previous Standing Committee; the remaining members were new.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/world/xi-jinping-china-s-princeling-new-leader/story-uKjI60ipqpRSEew3Zi7jzL.html|title=Xi Jinping: China's 'princeling' new leader|last=|first=|date=15 November 2012|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181028230023/https://www.hindustantimes.com/world/xi-jinping-china-s-princeling-new-leader/story-uKjI60ipqpRSEew3Zi7jzL.html|archive-date=28 October 2018|access-date=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/15/world/asia/communists-conclude-party-congress-in-china.html?ref=asia&_r=0|title=Ending Congress, China Presents New Leadership Headed by Xi Jinping|last1=Wong|first1=Edward|date=14 November 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=16 November 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121208103006/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/15/world/asia/communists-conclude-party-congress-in-china.html?ref=asia&_r=0|archive-date=8 December 2012|author-link=Edward Wong|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/11/14/world/asia/china-leadership-transition/index.html|title=After months of mystery, China unveils new top leaders|last1=FlorCruz|first1=Jaime A|last2=Mullen|first2=Jethro|date=16 November 2012|newspaper=[[CNN]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115195006/http://edition.cnn.com/2012/11/14/world/asia/china-leadership-transition/index.html|archive-date=15 November 2012|accessdate=16 November 2012}}</ref> In a marked departure from the common practice of Chinese leaders, Xi's first speech as general secretary was plainly worded and did not include any political slogans or mention of his predecessors.<ref name=\"nytimes22\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/16/world/asia/new-chinese-leader-offers-few-hints-of-a-shift-in-direction.html?pagewanted=all|title=A Promise to Tackle China's Problems, but Few Hints of a Shift in Path|last1=Johnson|first1=Ian|date=15 November 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=16 July 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726121506/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/16/world/asia/new-chinese-leader-offers-few-hints-of-a-shift-in-direction.html?pagewanted=all|archive-date=26 July 2014|url-access=limited}}</ref> Xi mentioned the aspirations of the average person, remarking, \"Our people ... expect better education, more stable jobs, better income, more reliable social security, medical care of a higher standard, more comfortable living conditions, and a more beautiful environment.\" Xi also vowed to tackle corruption at the highest levels, alluding that it would threaten the Party's survival; he was reticent about far-reaching economic reforms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-20338586|title=Full text: China's new party chief Xi Jinping's speech|last=|first=|date=15 November 2012|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914232334/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-20338586|archive-date=14 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, Xi visited [[Guangdong]] in his first trip outside Beijing since taking the Party leadership. The overarching theme of the trip was to call for further economic reform and a strengthened military. Xi visited the statue of [[Deng Xiaoping]] and his trip was described as following in the footsteps of [[Deng Xiaoping#Resignation and 1992 southern tour|Deng's own southern trip in 1992]], which provided the impetus for further economic reforms in China after conservative party leaders stalled many of Deng's reforms in the aftermath of the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]]. On his trip, Xi consistently alluded to his signature slogan the \"[[Chinese Dream]]\". \"This dream can be said to be the dream of a strong nation. And for the military, it is a dream of a strong military\", Xi told sailors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324128504578348774040546346|title=New Beijing Leader's 'China Dream'|last=Page|first=Jeremy|date=13 March 2013|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191011195356/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324128504578348774040546346|archive-date=11 October 2019|access-date=8 September 2019}}</ref> Xi's trip was significant in that he departed from the established convention of Chinese leaders' travel routines in multiple ways. Rather than dining out, Xi and his entourage ate regular hotel buffet. He travelled in a large van with his colleagues rather than a fleet of limousines, and did not restrict traffic on the parts of the highway he travelled.<ref name=\"bbc2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-20662947|title=The symbolism of Xi Jinping's trip south|last1=Chen|first1=Zhuang|date=10 December 2012|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=22 July 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140708094339/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-20662947|archive-date=8 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nXi was elected [[President of the People's Republic of China]] on 14 March 2013, in a confirmation vote by the [[12th National People's Congress]] in Beijing. He received 2,952 for, one vote against, and three abstentions.<ref name=\"BBCconfirm2\" /> He replaced [[Hu Jintao]], who retired after serving two terms.<ref name=\"Demick2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/world/worldnow/la-fg-wn-china-xi-presidency-20130313,0,1240600.story|title=China's Xi Jinping formally assumes title of president|last=Demick|first=Barbara|date=3 March 2013|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=16 March 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316021753/http://www.latimes.com/news/world/worldnow/la-fg-wn-china-xi-presidency-20130313,0,1240600.story|archive-date=16 March 2013|author-link=Barbara Demick}}</ref> In his new capacity as president, on 16 March 2013 Xi expressed support for non-interference in [[China\u2013Sri Lanka relations]] amid a [[United Nations Security Council]] vote to condemn that country over government abuses during the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/world/china-s-xi-jinping-hints-at-backing-sri-lanka-against-un-resolution-343378|title=China's Xi Jinping hints at backing Sri Lanka against UN resolution|date=16 March 2013|accessdate=16 March 2013|newspaper=[[Press Trust of India]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316222016/http://www.ndtv.com/article/world/china-s-xi-jinping-hints-at-backing-sri-lanka-against-un-resolution-343378|archive-date=16 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 March, Xi and his new ministers arranged a meeting with the [[Leung Chun-ying as Chief Executive of Hong Kong|chief executive of Hong Kong]], [[CY Leung]], confirming his support for Leung.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1192587/cy-leung-meet-xi-jinping-beijing-and-explain-cross-border-policies|title=CY Leung to meet Xi Jinping in Beijing and explain cross-border policies|last=Cheung|first=Tony|date=17 March 2013|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=16 March 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130318073700/http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1192587/cy-leung-meet-xi-jinping-beijing-and-explain-cross-border-policies|archive-date=18 March 2013|last2=Ho|first2=Jolie}}</ref> Within hours of his election, Xi discussed [[cyber security]] and North Korea with U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] over the phone. Obama announced the visits of treasury and state secretaries [[Jacob Lew]] and [[John F. Kerry]] to China the following week.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/373967/china-names-xi-jinping-as-new-president|title=China names Xi Jinping as new president|date=15 March 2013|accessdate=16 March 2013|newspaper=[[Agence France-Presse]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317020402/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/373967/china-names-xi-jinping-as-new-president|archive-date=17 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Announcing reforms===\nIn November 2013, at the conclusion of the Third Plenum of the 18th Central Committee, the Communist Party delivered a far-reaching reform agenda that alluded to changes in both economic and social policy. Xi signaled at the plenum that he was consolidating control of the massive internal security organization that was formerly the domain of [[Zhou Yongkang]].<ref name=\"brook2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.brookings.edu/research/opinions/2013/11/17-xi-jinping-economic-agenda-kroeber|title=Xi Jinping's Ambitious Agenda for Economic Reform in China|last1=Kroeber|first1=Arthur R.|date=17 November 2013|accessdate=21 July 2014|newspaper=[[Brookings Institution]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727211348/http://www.brookings.edu/research/opinions/2013/11/17-xi-jinping-economic-agenda-kroeber|archive-date=27 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> A new [[National Security Commission of the Communist Party of China|National Security Commission]] was formed with Xi at its helm. The [[Central Leading Group for Comprehensively Deepening Reforms]]\u2014another ad-hoc policy coordination body led by Xi\u2014was also formed to oversee the implementation of the reform agenda.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/19thcpcnationalcongress/2017-10/17/content_33352410.htm|title=Leading Group's focus is to deepen reform|last=Zhang|first=Yunbi|date=17 October 2017|newspaper=[[China Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818053001/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/19thcpcnationalcongress/2017-10/17/content_33352410.htm|archive-date=18 August 2019|access-date=18 August 2019}}</ref> Termed \"comprehensive deepening reforms\" ({{zh|labels=no|s=\u5168\u9762\u6df1\u5316\u6539\u9769|p=qu\u00e1nmi\u00e0n sh\u0113nhu\u00e0 g\u01ceig\u00e9}}), they were said to be the most significant since Deng Xiaoping's 1992 \"Southern Tour\". In the economic realm, the plenum announced that \"market forces\" would begin to play a \"decisive\" role in allocating resources.<ref name=\"brook2\" /> This meant that the state would gradually reduce its involvement in the distribution of capital, and restructure [[state-owned enterprise]]s to allow further competition, potentially by attracting foreign and private sector players in industries that were previously highly regulated. This policy aimed to address the bloated state sector that had unduly profited from an earlier round of re-structuring by purchasing assets at below-market prices, assets which were no longer being used productively. The plenum also resolved to abolish the ''[[laogai]]'' system of \"[[Re-education through labor|re-education through labour]]\" which was largely seen as a blot on China's human rights record. The system has faced significant criticism for years from domestic critics and foreign observers.<ref name=\"brook2\" /> The [[one-child policy]] was also abolished, resulting in a shift to a [[Two-child policy#China|two-child policy]] from 1 January 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/china-formally-abolishes-decades-old-one-child-policy-1535006|title=China formally abolishes decades-old one-child policy|last=Sridahan|first=Vasudevan|date=27 December 2015|newspaper=[[International Business Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828224908/https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/china-formally-abolishes-decades-old-one-child-policy-1535006|archive-date=28 August 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Anti-corruption campaign===\n{{main|Anti-corruption campaign under Xi Jinping}}\nXi vowed to crack down on corruption almost immediately after he ascended to power at the 18th Party Congress. In his inaugural speech as general secretary, Xi mentioned that fighting corruption was one of the toughest challenges for the party.<ref name=\"inaug2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-20338586|title=Xi Jinping's inaugural Speech|last=|first=|date=15 November 2012|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914232334/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-20338586|archive-date=14 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A few months into his term, Xi outlined the \"eight-point guide\", listing rules intended to curb corruption and waste during official party business; it aimed at stricter discipline on the conduct of party officials. Xi also vowed to root out \"tigers and flies\", that is, high-ranking officials and ordinary party functionaries.<ref name=\"elite2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/28/world/asia/xi-jinping-imposes-austerity-measures-on-chinas-elite.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Elite in China Face Austerity Under Xi's Rule|last=Jacobs|first=Andrew|date=27 March 2013|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=7 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181130054920/https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/28/world/asia/xi-jinping-imposes-austerity-measures-on-chinas-elite.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|archive-date=30 November 2018|author-link=Andrew Jacobs (journalist)}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first two years of Xi's term, he initiated cases against former Central Military Commission vice-chairman [[Xu Caihou]], former Politburo Standing Committee member and security chief [[Zhou Yongkang]] and former Hu Jintao chief aide [[Ling Jihua]].<ref name=\"bloom2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-03-03/china-s-xi-broadens-graft-crackdown-to-boost-influence.html|title=President Xi's Anti-Corruption Campaign Biggest Since Mao|last=Oster|first=Shai|date=4 March 2014|newspaper=[[Bloomberg News]]|access-date=7 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209164917/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-03-03/china-s-xi-broadens-graft-crackdown-to-boost-influence.html|archive-date=9 December 2014|author-link=Shai Oster}}</ref> Along with new disciplinary chief [[Wang Qishan]], Xi's [[Xi\u2013Li Administration|administration]] spearheaded the formation of \"centrally-dispatched inspection teams\" ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4e2d\u592e\u5de1\u89c6\u7ec4}}). These were essentially cross-jurisdictional squads of officials whose main task was to gain more in-depth understanding of the operations of provincial and local party organizations, and in the process, also enforce party discipline mandated by Beijing. Many of the work teams also had the effect of identifying and initiating investigations of high-ranking officials. Over one hundred provincial-ministerial level officials were implicated during a massive nationwide anti-corruption campaign. These included former and current regional officials ([[Su Rong]], [[Bai Enpei]], [[Wan Qingliang]]), leading figures of state-owned enterprises and central government organs ([[Song Lin]], [[Liu Tienan]]), and highly ranked generals in the military ([[Gu Junshan]]). In June 2014, the [[Shanxi]] provincial political establishment was decimated, with four officials dismissed within a week from the provincial party organization's top ranks. Within the first two years of the campaign alone, over 200,000 low-ranking officials received warnings, fines, and demotions.{{sfn|Heilmann|2017|p=62\u201375}}\n\nThe campaign has led to the downfall of prominent incumbent and retired Communist Party officials, including members of the [[Politburo Standing Committee]].<ref name=\"lam20142\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jamestown.org/programs/chinabrief/single/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=43160&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=25&cHash=d5d24d2f82c5981963c0180d300e62cd#.VOOBN_nF9uM|title=China's Soft-Power Deficit Widens as Xi Tightens Screws Over Ideology|last=|first=|date=5 December 2014|access-date=7 September 2019|newspaper=[[Brookings Institution]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041925/http://www.jamestown.org/programs/chinabrief/single/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=43160&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=25&cHash=d5d24d2f82c5981963c0180d300e62cd#.VOOBN_nF9uM|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Xi's anti-corruption campaign is seen by critics as a political purge on a scale not seen since Chairman Mao, with the aim of removing potential opponents and consolidating power. Xi's establishment of a new anti-corruption agency, the National Supervision Commission, that is ranked higher than the supreme court, has been described by [[Amnesty International]]'s East Asia director as a \"systemic threat to human rights\" which \"places tens of millions of people at the mercy of a secretive and virtually unaccountable system that is above the law\".<ref>{{cite news |title=China's former military chief of staff jailed for life for corruption |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/feb/20/chinas-former-military-chief-of-staff-jailed-for-life-for-corruption |accessdate=13 September 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=20 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191010131232/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/feb/20/chinas-former-military-chief-of-staff-jailed-for-life-for-corruption |archive-date=10 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-43453769|title=China's anti-corruption campaign expands with new agency|last=|first=|date=20 March 2018|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=13 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924060145/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-43453769|archive-date=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Censorship ===\n{{see also|Censorship in China|Internet censorship in China}}\"[[Document Number Nine|Document No. 9]]\" is a [[Internal media of China|confidential internal document]] widely circulated within the Communist Party of China in 2013 by the [[General Office of the Communist Party of China|party's General Office]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hndj.gov.cn/html/jgdj/gzkx/2013/5168269.html|script-title=zh:\u7701\u50a8\u5907\u5c40\u8ba4\u771f\u5b66\u4e60\u8d2f\u5f7b\u843d\u5b9e\u300a\u5173\u4e8e\u5f53\u524d\u610f\u8bc6\u5f62\u6001\u9886\u57df\u60c5\u51b5\u7684\u901a\u62a5\u300b\uff0c\u6e56\u5357\u673a\u5173\u515a\u5efa|last=Li|first=Bing|date=16 May 2013|website=hndj.gov.cn|trans-title=The Provincial Reserve Bureau Has Carefully Studied and Implemented the \"Notice on the Current Situation of Ideology\"|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615122048/http://www.hndj.gov.cn/html/jgdj/gzkx/2013/5168269.html|archive-date=15 June 2013|access-date=16 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vtibet.cn/zhuanti/2013-05/09/cms340592article.shtml|script-title=zh:\u897f\u85cf\u5e7f\u7535\u5c40\u53ec\u5f00\u4f20\u8fbe\u5b66\u4e60\u6709\u5173\u6587\u4ef6\u7cbe\u795e\u4f1a\u8bae\uff0c\u4e2d\u56fd\u897f\u85cf\u4e4b\u58f0\u7f51|last=Liang|first=Liming|date=9 May 2013|website=vtibet.cn|trans-title=Tibet Radio and Television Bureau Holds Vigorous Discussion To Study Documents in Concern|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615105337/http://www.vtibet.cn/zhuanti/2013-05/09/cms340592article.shtml|archive-date=15 June 2013|access-date=16 October 2013}}</ref> It was first published in July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theory.people.com.cn/n/2012/0703/c83855-18430666.html|script-title=zh:\u5f53\u524d\u6211\u56fd\u610f\u8bc6\u5f62\u6001\u5efa\u8bbe\u9762\u4e34\u7684\u516d\u5927\u6311\u6218--\u7406\u8bba--\u4eba\u6c11\u7f51|last=Ren|first=Jie|date=3 July 2012|work=[[People's Daily]]|language=zh-hans|trans-title=Six Major Challenges Facing China's Ideological Construction|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901000000/http://theory.people.com.cn/n/2012/0703/c83855-18430666.html|archive-date=1 September 2012|access-date=8 September 2019}}</ref> The document warns of seven dangerous Western values: [[constitutional democracy]], [[universal values]], [[civil society]], pro-market [[neo-liberalism]], [[media independence]], historical [[nihilism]] (criticisms of past errors) and questioning the nature of [[Socialism with Chinese characteristics|Chinese style socialism]].<ref name=\"NYT819132\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/20/world/asia/chinas-new-leadership-takes-hard-line-in-secret-memo.html?ref=global-home|title=China's New Leadership Takes Hard Line in Secret Memo|last=Buckley|first=Christopher|date=19 August 2013|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=8 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721050121/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/20/world/asia/chinas-new-leadership-takes-hard-line-in-secret-memo.html?ref=global-home|archive-date=21 July 2016|url-access=limited}}</ref> Coverage of these topics in educational materials is forbidden.<ref name=\"SCMP829132\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1234453/seven-subjects-limits-teaching-chinese-universities-told|title=Seven subjects off limits for teaching, Chinese universities told|last=Li|first=Raymond|date=29 August 2013|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=19 September 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022211500/http://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1234453/seven-subjects-limits-teaching-chinese-universities-told|archive-date=22 October 2013}}</ref> The specific ideas posed as dangerous within the tenets of Western Constitutional Democracy included the separation of powers, multi-party systems, general elections, and an independent judiciary.{{sfn|Bougon|p=154|2018}} The threat from 'universal values' is the notion, contrary to Maoist doctrine, that the Western value system transcends nation in class, and applies to China.{{sfn|Bougon|p=155-56|2018}}{{sfn|Goodman|p=51|2015}} 'Civil society' is the notion that individual rights are paramount, rather than the collective rights established by the Party. Neoliberalism refers to libertarian economic values and globalization.{{sfn|Bougon|p=156-57|2018}} Xi was especially hostile to Western ideas of journalism, and notions of a press that could criticize government and Party policies. The release of this internal document, which has introduced new topics that were previously not \"off-limits\", was seen as Xi's recognition of the \"sacrosanct\" nature of Communist Party rule over China.<ref name=\"NYT819132\" /> \nSince Xi became the General Secretary of the CPC, [[Censorship in China|censorship]] has been significantly stepped up.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/chinas-communist-party-unveils-new-leadership-with-no-obvious-successor-to-xi-jinping/2017/10/25/efe67876-b8fc-11e7-9b93-b97043e57a22_story.html|title=China's Xi Jinping unveils his top party leaders, with no successor in sight|last=Denyer|first=Simon|date=25 October 2017|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=25 October 2017|quote=Censorship has been significantly stepped up in China since Xi took power.|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813203127/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/chinas-communist-party-unveils-new-leadership-with-no-obvious-successor-to-xi-jinping/2017/10/25/efe67876-b8fc-11e7-9b93-b97043e57a22_story.html|archive-date=13 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/jun/29/the-great-firewall-of-china-xi-jinpings-internet-shutdown|title=The great firewall of China: Xi Jinping's internet shutdown|last=Economy|first=Elizabeth|author-link=Elizabeth Economy|date=29 June 2018|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191010172129/https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/jun/29/the-great-firewall-of-china-xi-jinpings-internet-shutdown|archive-date=10 October 2019|accessdate=4 November 2019|quote=Before Xi Jinping, the internet was becoming a more vibrant political space for Chinese citizens. But today the country has the largest and most sophisticated online censorship operation in the world.}}</ref> Chairing the 2018 China Cyberspace Governance Conference on 20 and 21 April 2018, Xi committed to \"fiercely crack down on criminal offenses including hacking, telecom fraud, and violation of citizens' privacy\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-04/21/c_137127374.htm|title=Xi outlines blueprint to develop China's strength in cyberspace|date=21 April 2018|newspaper=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|accessdate=22 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421162040/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-04/21/c_137127374.htm|archive-date=21 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> His administration has also overseen more Internet restrictions imposed in China, and is described as being \"stricter across the board\" on speech than previous administrations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/06/03/tiananmen-censorship-reflects-crackdown-under-xi-jinping|title=Tiananmen Censorship Reflects Crackdown Under Xi Jinping|last=Risen|first=Tom|date=3 June 2014|work=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|access-date=8 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411190520/https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/06/03/tiananmen-censorship-reflects-crackdown-under-xi-jinping|archive-date=11 April 2019}}</ref> The situation for users of [[Sina Weibo|Weibo]] has been described as a change from fearing that individual posts would be deleted, or at worst one's account, to fear of arrest.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/aug/06/china-xi-jinping-crackdown-liberal-academics-minor-cultural-revolution|title='It's getting worse': China's liberal academics fear growing censorship|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=6 August 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=8 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918070042/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/aug/06/china-xi-jinping-crackdown-liberal-academics-minor-cultural-revolution|archive-date=18 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A law enacted in September 2013 authorized a three-year prison term for bloggers who shared more than 500 times any content considered \"defamatory\".<ref name=\"Grigg2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.afr.com/technology/social-media/how-china-stopped-its-bloggers-20150701-gi34za|title=How China stopped its bloggers|last=Grigg|first=Angus|date=4 July 2015|newspaper=[[The Australian Financial Review]]|access-date=8 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626001441/https://www.afr.com/technology/social-media/how-china-stopped-its-bloggers-20150701-gi34za|archive-date=26 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The State Internet Information Department summoned a group of influential bloggers to a seminar instructing them to avoid writing about politics, the Communist Party, or making statements contradicting official narratives. Many bloggers stopped writing about controversial topics, and Weibo went into decline, with much of its readership shifting to [[WeChat]] users speaking to very limited social circles.<ref name=\"Grigg2\" />\n\nIn July 2017, the character [[Winnie the Pooh (Disney character)|Winnie the Pooh]] was blocked on Chinese social media sites following the spread of an [[internet meme]] in which photographs of Xi and other individuals were compared to Winnie the Pooh and other characters from the works of [[A. A. Milne]]<ref name=\"cbs winnie2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/winnie-the-pooh-censored-china-president-xi-jinping-comparisons/|title=Winnie the Pooh censored in China after President Xi Jinping comparisons|last=Martinez|first=Peter|date=17 July 2017|work=[[CBS News]]|accessdate=27 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171224214026/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/winnie-the-pooh-censored-china-president-xi-jinping-comparisons/|archive-date=24 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and in 2018, the Winnie the Pooh film ''[[Christopher Robin (film)|Christopher Robin]]'' was denied a Chinese release.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-45083944|title=Winnie the Pooh film denied release in China|last=|first=|date=6 August 2018|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927153333/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-45083944|archive-date=27 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> This followed an incident where Chinese authorities censored a nine-year-old for comments about Xi's weight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2014/12/18/not-as-skinny-as-obama-like-putin-is-ok-china-censors-schoolboys-suggestion-that-xi-lose-weight/|title='Not as skinny as Obama, like Putin is okay.' China censors schoolboy's suggestion that Xi lose weight|last=Denyer|first=Simon|date=18 December 2014|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=19 June 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619063324/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2014/12/18/not-as-skinny-as-obama-like-putin-is-ok-china-censors-schoolboys-suggestion-that-xi-lose-weight/|archive-date=19 June 2018|issn=0190-8286|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nXi has taken a very strong stand to control internet usage inside China, including [[Google]] and [[Facebook]],{{sfn|Bougon|p=157-65|2018}} advocating Internet censorship in China as the concept of \"[[Network sovereignty|internet sovereignty]]\".<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/06/chinas-sovereign-internet/|title=China's 'Sovereign Internet'|last=Tiezzi|first=Shannon|date=24 June 2014|work=[[The Diplomat]]|access-date=4 August 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804053110/http://thediplomat.com/2014/06/chinas-sovereign-internet/|archive-date=4 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Asia-Pacific/2015/1218/On-Internet-freedoms-China-tells-the-world-leave-us-alone|title=On Internet freedoms, China tells the world, 'leave us alone'|last=Ford|first=Peter|date=18 December 2015|work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]|access-date=4 August 2017|ISSN=0882-7729|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804055927/https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Asia-Pacific/2015/1218/On-Internet-freedoms-China-tells-the-world-leave-us-alone|archive-date=4 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[censorship of Wikipedia]] has also been stringent; as of April 2019, all versions of Wikipedia have been blocked in China.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-48269608|title=Wikipedia blocked in China in all languages|last=|first=|date=14 May 2019|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=15 May 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515001341/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-48269608|archive-date=15 May 2019|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, telecommunications carriers in China were instructed by the government to block individuals' use of [[Virtual Private Network]]s (VPNs) by February 2018.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-07-10/china-is-said-to-order-carriers-to-bar-personal-vpns-by-february China Tells Carries to Block Access to Personal VPNs by February]. Bloomberg. 2017-07-10</ref>\n\n===Consolidation of power===\n[[File:\u6297\u6218\u80dc\u522970\u5468\u5e74\u9605\u5175\u6f14\u7ec3.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Xi in Beijing, September 2015]]\nPolitical observers have called Xi the most powerful Chinese leader since Chairman Mao Zedong, especially since the ending of presidential two-term limits in 2018.<ref name=\"PhillipsGuardian2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/24/xi-jinping-mao-thought-on-socialism-china-constitution|title=Xi Jinping becomes most powerful leader since Mao with China's change to constitution|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=24 October 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=24 October 2017|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024053607/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/24/xi-jinping-mao-thought-on-socialism-china-constitution|archive-date=24 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/china-congress-xi-jinping-1.4368588|title=China elevates Xi to most powerful leader in decades|last=|first=|date=24 October 2017|work=[[CBC News]]|accessdate=22 June 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501062515/http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/china-congress-xi-jinping-1.4368588|archive-date=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/world-news/china-elevates-xi-jinpings-status-making-him-the-most-powerful-leader-since-mao-36256294.html|title=China elevates Xi Jinping's status, making him the most powerful leader since Mao|last=|first=|date=24 October 2017|work=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=22 June 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622220327/https://www.independent.ie/world-news/china-elevates-xi-jinpings-status-making-him-the-most-powerful-leader-since-mao-36256294.html|archive-date=22 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2017/11/08/politics/president-donald-trump-xi-jinping-china/index.html|title=Xi's up, Trump is down, but it may not matter|last1=Collins|first1=Stephen|date=9 November 2017|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623004701/https://edition.cnn.com/2017/11/08/politics/president-donald-trump-xi-jinping-china/index.html|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Xi has notably departed from the [[collective leadership]] practices of his post-Mao predecessors. He has centralised his power and created working groups with himself at the head to subvert government bureaucracy, making himself become the unmistakable central figure of the new administration.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Asia-Pacific/2018/0228/Xi-for-life-China-turns-its-back-on-collective-leadership|title=Xi for life? China turns its back on collective leadership.|last1=Holtz|first1=Michael|date=28 February 2018|work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]|accessdate=23 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624035940/https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Asia-Pacific/2018/0228/Xi-for-life-China-turns-its-back-on-collective-leadership|archive-date=24 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Beginning in 2013, the party under Xi has created a series of new \"Central Leading Groups\"; supra-ministerial steering committees, designed to bypass existing institutions when making decisions, and ostensibly make policy-making a more efficient process. The most notable new body is the Central Leading Group for Comprehensively Deepening Reforms. It has broad jurisdiction over economic restructuring and social reforms, and is said to have displaced some of the power previously held by the State Council and its premier.<ref name=\"keck2\">{{cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/01/is-li-keqiang-being-marginalized/|title=Is Li Keqiang Being Marginalized?|last1=Keck|first1=Zachary|date=7 January 2014|work=[[The Diplomat]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029152046/https://thediplomat.com/2014/01/is-li-keqiang-being-marginalized/|archive-date=29 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Xi also became the leader of the [[Central Leading Group for Internet Security and Informatization]], in charge of cyber-security and Internet policy. The Third Plenum held in 2013 also saw the creation of the [[National Security Commission of the Communist Party of China]], another body chaired by Xi which commentators have said would help Xi consolidate over national security affairs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/06/30/chinas-much-heralded-national-security-council-has-disappeared-nsc-xi-jinping/|title=China's Much-Heralded NSC Has Disappeared|last=Wuthnow|first=Joel|date=30 June 2016|newspaper=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825180323/https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/06/30/chinas-much-heralded-national-security-council-has-disappeared-nsc-xi-jinping/|archive-date=25 August 2019|access-date=25 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lampton|first=David M.|date=3 September 2015|title=Xi Jinping and the National Security Commission: policy coordination and political power|journal=Journal of Contemporary China|volume=24|issue=95|pages=759\u2013777|doi=10.1080/10670564.2015.1013366|issn=1067-0564}}</ref>\n\n====Cult of personality====\n[[File:\u4e2d\u56fd\u8857\u5934\u51fa\u552e\u7684\u9762\u5b54\u53ef\u4ee5\u53d8\u6362\u7684\u6bdb\u6cfd\u4e1c\u548c\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u50cf.png|thumb|Portraits of [[Mao Zedong]] and Xi Jinping in a shop in China]]\n{{Main|Xi Jinping's cult of personality}}\nXi has had a [[cult of personality]] constructed around himself since entering office<ref name=\"EconomistCultPersonality\" /><ref name=\"ForeignPolicyCultPersonality\" /> with books, cartoons, pop songs and dance routines honouring his rule.<ref name=\"PhilGuard12\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/19/xi-jinping-does-china-truly-love-big-daddy-xi-or-fear-him|title=Xi Jinping: Does China truly love 'Big Daddy Xi' \u2013 or fear him?|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=19 September 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=31 August 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427001038/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/19/xi-jinping-does-china-truly-love-big-daddy-xi-or-fear-him|archive-date=27 April 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Following Xi's ascension to the [[leadership core]] of the CPC, he has been referred to as ''Xi Dada'' (Uncle or Papa Xi).<ref name=\"PhilGuard12\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-politics-xi-idUSKCN12S0AA|title=All hail the mighty uncle - Chinese welcome Xi as the 'core'|last1=Blanchard|first1=Ben|date=28 October 2016|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=23 June 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624010629/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-politics-xi-idUSKCN12S0AA|archive-date=24 June 2018}}</ref> The village of Liangjiahe, where Xi was sent to work, has become a \"modern-day shrine\" decorated with Communist propaganda and murals extolling the formative years of his life.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/03/19/asia/china-xi-jinping-village-intl/index.html|title=This entire Chinese village is a shrine to Xi Jinping|last1=Rivers|first1=Matt|date=19 March 2018|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=23 June 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624010733/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/03/19/asia/china-xi-jinping-village-intl/index.html|archive-date=24 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Politburo of the Communist Party of China|party's Politburo]] named Xi Jinping ''[[Lingxiu (disambiguation)|lingxiu]]'' ({{zh|s={{linktext|\u9886\u8896}}|labels=no}}), a reverent term for \"leader\" and a title previously only given to [[Chiang Kai-shek]], [[Mao Zedong]] and his immediate successor [[Hua Guofeng]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/policies-politics/article/2117421/xi-jinpings-latest-grandiose-title-aims-take|title=Why China is reviving Mao's grandiose title for Xi Jinping|last=Gan|first=Nectar|date=28 December 2017|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2018/02/17/xi-jinping-is-no-longer-any-old-leader|title=Xi Jinping is no longer any old leader|last=|first=|date=17 February 2018|work=[[The Economist]]|access-date=26 July 2019|url-status=live|issn=0013-0613}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-congress-idUSKBN1CO0AV|title=With tears and song, China welcomes Xi as great, wise leader|last=Shepherd|first=Christian|date=20 October 2017|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=26 July 2019|url-status=live|last2=Wen|first2=Philip|language=en}}</ref> He is also sometimes called the \"[[Great Helmsman (disambiguation)|Great Helmsman]]\" ({{zh|s=\u5927\u8235\u624b|labels=no}}), and in July 2018 [[Li Zhanshu]], the [[Chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress|Chairman]] of the [[Standing Committee of the National People's Congress]], referred to Xi as the \"[[Leadership core|eternal core]]\" of the party.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://supchina.com/2018/03/19/oath-tears-joy-great-hall-people/|title=An oath, and tears of joy in the Great Hall of the People|last=Goldkorn|first=Jeremy|date=19 March 2018|website=SupChina|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> On 25 December 2019, the politburo officially named Xi as \"People's Leader\" ({{zh|s=\u4eba\u6c11\u9886\u8896|labels=no|c=|t=|p=r\u00e9nm\u00edn l\u01d0ngxi\u00f9}}), a title only Mao held previously.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Editor-s-Picks/China-up-close/China-crowns-Xi-with-special-title-citing-rare-crisis|title=China crowns Xi with special title, citing rare crisis|last=Nakazawa|first=Katsuji|date=9 January 2020|work=[[Nikkei Asian Review]]|access-date=10 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Removal of term limits ====\nIn March 2018, the party-controlled National People's Congress passed a set of constitutional amendments including removal of term limits for the president and vice president, the creation of a [[National Supervisory Commission]], as well as enhancing the central role of the Communist Party.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2134791/end-term-limits-top-may-be-start-global-backlash-china|title=End to term limits at top 'may be start of global backlash for China'|last=Shi|first=Jiangtao|date=26 February 2018|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227155138/http://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2134791/end-term-limits-top-may-be-start-global-backlash-china|archive-date=27 February 2018|last2=Huang|first2=Kristin}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/04/xi-jinping-from-president-to-china-new-dictator|title=Xi Jinping's power play: from president to China's new dictator?|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=4 March 2018|website=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304005848/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/04/xi-jinping-from-president-to-china-new-dictator|archive-date=4 March 2018|access-date=4 March 2018}}</ref> On 17 March 2018, the Chinese legislature reappointed Xi as president, now without term limits; [[Wang Qishan]] was appointed vice president.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-parliament-xi/chinas-parliament-re-elects-xi-jinping-as-president-idUSKCN1GT03C|title=China's parliament re-elects Xi Jinping as president|last=Wen|first=Philip|date=17 March 2018|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=17 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317042406/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-parliament-xi/chinas-parliament-re-elects-xi-jinping-as-president-idUSKCN1GT03C|archive-date=17 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/78ea5b0646564a6eb98d9d20d5fbcbb6|title=Xi reappointed as China's president with no term limits|last1=Bodeen|first1=Christopher|date=17 March 2018|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317190611/https://apnews.com/78ea5b0646564a6eb98d9d20d5fbcbb6|archive-date=17 March 2018|accessdate=17 March 2018}}</ref> The following day, [[Li Keqiang]] was reappointed [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|premier]] and longtime allies of Xi, [[Xu Qiliang]] and [[Zhang Youxia]], were voted in as vice-chairmen of the state military commission.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/economy/article/2137707/li-keqiang-endorsed-chinas-premier-while-military-commission|title=Li Keqiang endorsed as China's premier; military leaders confirmed|last1=Zhou|first1=Xin|date=18 March 2018|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827155325/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/economy/article/2137707/li-keqiang-endorsed-chinas-premier-while-military-commission|archive-date=27 August 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> Foreign minister [[Wang Yi (politician)|Wang Yi]] was promoted to [[State councillor (China)|state councillor]] and General [[Wei Fenghe]] was named [[Ministry of National Defense of the People's Republic of China|defence minister]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2137769/china-promotes-foreign-minister-wang-yi-state|title=China's foreign minister gains power in new post as state councillor|last1=Ng|first1=Teddy|date=19 March 2018|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305121632/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2137769/china-promotes-foreign-minister-wang-yi-state|archive-date=5 March 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Financial Times]]'', Xi expressed his views of constitutional amendment at meetings with Chinese officials and foreign dignitaries. Xi explained the decision in terms of needing to align two more powerful posts\u2014General Secretary of the Communist Party and Chairman of the Central Military Commission (CMC)\u2014which have no term limits. However, Xi did not say whether he intended to serve as party general secretary, CMC chairman and state president, for three or more terms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/2b449400-413a-11e8-803a-295c97e6fd0b|title=China's Xi Jinping says he is opposed to life-long rule|last1=Mitchell|first1=Tom|date=7 September 2019|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|accessdate=17 April 2018|quote=President insists term extension is necessary to align government and party posts|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417192157/https://www.ft.com/content/2b449400-413a-11e8-803a-295c97e6fd0b|archive-date=17 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Economic policy ===\nXi has increased state control over [[Economy of China|China's economy]], voicing support for China's [[state-owned enterprise]]s (SOEs),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/economy/china-economy/article/2166261/chinese-president-xi-jinpings-show-support-state-owned-firms|title=Chinese President Xi Jinping's show of support for state-owned firms 'no surprise', analysts say|last=Wang|first=Orange|date=28 September 2018|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Leng|first2=Sidney}}</ref> while also supporting the country's private sector.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/2166108/xi-jinping-reassures-chinas-state-owned-enterprises-and-private|title=Xi says it's wrong to 'bad mouth' China's state firms... but country needs private sector as well|last=Gan|first=Nectar|date=28 September 2018|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He has increased the role of the [[Central Financial and Economic Affairs Commission]] at the expense of the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/57371736-4b69-11e6-88c5-db83e98a590a|title=Xi's China: The rise of party politics|last=Mitchell|first=Tom|date=25 July 2016|work=[[Financial Times]]|access-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> His administration made it easier for banks to issue [[Mortgage loan|mortgages]], increased foreign participation in the bond market, and increased country's currency [[Renminbi|renminbi's]] global role, helping it to join [[International Monetary Fund|IMF's]] basked of [[Special drawing rights|special drawing right]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/04/business/china-xi-jinping-economic-reform-scorecard.html|title=China and Economic Reform: Xi Jinping's Track Record|last=Bradsher|first=Keith|date=4 March 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In the 40th anniversary of the launching of [[Chinese economic reform]]s in 2018, he has promised to continue reforms but has warned that nobody \"can dictate to the Chinese people\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/658e78ce-0287-11e9-99df-6183d3002ee1|title=Xi says no one can 'dictate to the Chinese people'|last=Wildau|first=Gabriel|date=18 December 2018|work=[[Financial Times]]|access-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Since the outbreak of the [[China\u2013United States trade war|China-United States trade war]] in 2018, Xi has also revived calls for \"self-reliance\", especially on the matters of technology.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/as-china-settles-in-for-trade-war-leader-xi-emphasizesself-reliance/2018/11/01/2961b2b2-d8de-11e8-9559-712cbf726d1c_story.html|title=As China settles in for trade war, leader Xi emphasizes 'self reliance'|last=Fifield|first=Anna|date=2 November 2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Legal reforms===\nThe party under Xi announced a raft of legal reforms at the Fourth Plenum held in the fall 2014, and he called for \"Chinese socialistic rule of law\" immediately afterwards. The party aimed to reform the legal system which had been perceived as ineffective at delivering justice and affected by corruption, local government interference and lack of constitutional oversight. The plenum, while emphasizing the absolute leadership of the party, also called for a greater role of the constitution in the affairs of state and a strengthening of the role of the National People's Congress Standing Committee in interpreting the constitution.<ref name=\"scm32\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1623286/communist-party-pledges-greater-role-constitution-rights-fourth-plenum|title=Communist Party pledges greater role for constitution, rights in fourth plenum|last1=Zhou|first1=Laura|date=24 October 2014|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=7 September 2019|last2=Huang|first2=Cary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030035405/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1623286/communist-party-pledges-greater-role-constitution-rights-fourth-plenum|archive-date=30 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It also called for more transparency in legal proceedings, more involvement of ordinary citizens in the legislative process, and an overall \"professionalization\" of the legal workforce. The party also planned to institute cross-jurisdictional circuit legal tribunals as well as giving provinces consolidated administrative oversight over lower level legal resources, which is intended to reduce local government involvement in legal proceedings.<ref name=\"dww2\">{{cite news|url=https://jamestown.org/program/the-fourth-plenum-party-officials-and-local-courts/|title=The Fourth Plenum, Party Officials and Local Courts|last1=Doyon|first1=Jerome|date=20 November 2014|newspaper=[[Jamestown Foundation]]|access-date=7 September 2019|last2=Winckler|first2=Hugo}}</ref>\n\nXi has overseen significant reforms of the [[Central Commission for Discipline Inspection]] (CCDI), CPC's highest [[internal control]] institution.<ref name=\"xinj\">{{cite news|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/politics/2014-06/13/c_126612534.htm|title=31\u4e2a\u7701\u7ea7\u7eaa\u59d4\u6539\u9769\u65b9\u6848\u83b7\u6279\u590d 12\u7701\u5df2\u5b8c\u6210\u7eaa\u59d4\"\u91cd\u5efa\"|last=|first=|date=13 June 2014|work=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|access-date=7 January 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703204141/http://news.xinhuanet.com/politics/2014-06/13/c_126612534.htm|archive-date=3 July 2014|trans-title=31 Provincial Commission for Discipline Inspection Reform Plans Approved 12 Provinces Have Completed \"Reconstruction\"}}</ref> He and CCDI Secretary [[Wang Qishan]] further institutionalised CCDI's independence from the day-to-day operations of the CPC, improving its ability to function as a ''bona fide'' control body.<ref name=\"xinj\" />\n\n=== Military reforms ===\n{{see also|Modernization of the People's Liberation Army|2015 People's Republic of China military reform}}Since taking power in 2012, Xi has started a massive overhaul of the [[People's Liberation Army]].<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/china-army-xi/|title=How China is replacing America as Asia's military titan|last=Lague|first=David|date=23 April 2019|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=10 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Lim|first2=Benjamin Kang}}</ref> Xi has been active in his participation in military affairs, taking a direct hands-on approach to military reform. In addition to being the Chairman of the Central Military Commission, and the leader of the [[Central Leading Group for Military Reform]] founded in 2014 to oversee comprehensive military reforms, Xi has delivered numerous high-profile pronouncements vowing to clean up malfeasance and complacency in the military, aiming to build a more effective fighting force. In addition, Xi held the \"New Gutian Conference\" in 2014, gathering China's top military officers, re-emphasizing the principle of \"the party has absolute control over the army\" first established by Mao at the 1929 [[Gutian Conference]].<ref name=\"meng2\">{{cite news|url=http://china.dwnews.com/news/2014-11-04/59616798.html|last1=Meng|first1=Chuan|date=4 November 2014|work=[[Duowei News]]|access-date=8 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121184703/http://china.dwnews.com/news/2014-11-04/59616798.html|archive-date=21 January 2015|language=zh-hans|script-title=zh:\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u519b\u4e2d\"\u4eae\u5251\" \u65b0\u53e4\u7530\u4f1a\u8bae\u4e00\u7bad\u591a\u96d5|trans-title=Xi Jinping And Central Army's New \"Bright Sword\" Conferrence In Gutian Killed Many Birds With Only A Single Stone}}</ref>\n\nXi has warned against the depoliticization of the PLA from the Communist Party, warning that it would lead to a collapse similar to that of the [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|Soviet Union]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinas-communist-party-has-one-more-reason-to-celebrate--a-year-longer-in-power-than-the-soviet-union/2019/09/28/993bb832-dfc0-11e9-be7f-4cc85017c36f_story.html|title=China's Communist Party has one more reason to celebrate \u2014 a year longer in power than the U.S.S.R.|last=Fifield|first=Anna|date=29 September 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live|author-link=Anna Fifield}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-21790384|title=President Xi Jinping: A man with a dream|last=Grammaticas|first=Damian|date=14 March 2013|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref> He said that \"in the USSR, where the military was depoliticized, separated from the party and nationalized, the party was disarmed. When the Soviet Union came to crisis point, a big party was gone just like that. Proportionally, the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Soviet Communist Party]] had more members than we do, but nobody was man enough to stand up and resist.\"<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nXi announced a reduction of 300,000 troops from the PLA in 2015, bringing its size to 2 million troops. Xi described this as a gesture of peace, while analysts have said that the cut was done to reduce costs as well as part of PLA's modernization.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/03/world/asia/beijing-turns-into-ghost-town-as-it-gears-up-for-military-parade.html|title=China Announces Cuts of 300,000 Troops at Military Parade Showing Its Might|last=Wong|first=Edward|date=2015-09-02|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2020-01-10|url-status=live|last2=Perlez|first2=Jane|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Buckley|first3=Chris}}</ref> On 2016, he reduced the number of [[Theater commands of the People's Liberation Army|theater commands of the PLA]] from seven to five.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thediplomat.com/2016/02/its-official-chinas-military-has-5-new-theater-commands/|title=It's Official: China's Military Has 5 New Theater Commands|last=Tiezzi|first=Shannon|date=2 February 2016|work=[[The Diplomat]]|access-date=10 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He has also abolished the four autonomous [[People's Liberation Army General Political Department|general departments]] of the PLA, replacing them with 15 agencies directly reporting to the Central Military Commission.<ref name=\":8\" /> Two new branches of the PLA were created under his reforms, the [[People's Liberation Army Strategic Support Force|Strategic Support Force]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thediplomat.com/2017/02/chinas-strategic-support-force-a-force-for-innovation/|title=China's Strategic Support Force: A Force for Innovation?|last=Kania|first=Elsa|date=18 February 2017|work=[[The Diplomat]]|access-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the Joint Logistics Support Force.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-defence-idUSKCN11K05F|title=China sets up new logistics force as part of military reforms|last=Blanchard|first=Ben|date=14 September 2016|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 April 2016 Xi was named [[Supreme Military Command of the People's Republic of China|commander-in-chief]] of the country's new Joint Operations Command Center of the [[People's Liberation Army]] by [[Xinhua News Agency]] and the broadcaster [[China Central Television]].<ref name=\"Guardian21Apr162\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/21/xi-jinping-named-commander-in-chief-chinese-state-media|title=Xi Jinping named as 'commander in chief' by Chinese state media|date=21 April 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=25 April 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425012825/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/21/xi-jinping-named-commander-in-chief-chinese-state-media|archive-date=25 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Independent21Apr162\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/chinese-president-xi-jinping-commander-in-chief-military-armed-forces-a6997396.html|title=Chinese President Xi Jinping named as military's 'commander-in-chief'|last1=Kayleigh|first1=Lewis|date=23 April 2016|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=25 April 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427091000/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/chinese-president-xi-jinping-commander-in-chief-military-armed-forces-a6997396.html|archive-date=27 April 2016}}</ref> Some analysts interpreted this move as an attempt to display strength and strong leadership and as being more \"political than military\".<ref name=\"ChinaTopix22Apr162\">{{cite news|url=http://www.chinatopix.com/articles/84000/20160422/president-xi-jinping-is-new-commander-in-chief-of-the-military.htm|title=President Xi Jinping is New Commander-in-Chief of the Military|last1=Sison|first1=Desiree|date=22 April 2016|work=China Topix|accessdate=25 April 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423120421/http://www.chinatopix.com/articles/84000/20160422/president-xi-jinping-is-new-commander-in-chief-of-the-military.htm|archive-date=23 April 2016}}</ref> According to Ni Lexiong, a military affairs expert, Xi \"not only controls the military but also does it in an absolute manner, and that in wartime, he is ready to command personally\".<ref name=\"ColuDaily24Apr20162\">{{cite news|url=http://www.columbiatribune.com/news/perspectives/china-s-xi-moves-to-take-more-direct-command-over/article_b5e96afb-97e6-533e-b33e-db5beab72bf3.html|title=China's Xi moves to take more direct command over military|date=24 April 2016|work=[[Columbia Daily Tribune]]|accessdate=25 April 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425105101/http://www.columbiatribune.com/news/perspectives/china-s-xi-moves-to-take-more-direct-command-over/article_b5e96afb-97e6-533e-b33e-db5beab72bf3.html|archive-date=25 April 2016}}</ref> According to a [[University of California, San Diego]] expert on Chinese military, Xi \"has been able to take political control of the military to an extent that exceeds what Mao and Deng have done\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/11/world/asia/xi-jinping-military-china-purge.html|title=Xi Jinping Presses Military Overhaul, and Two Generals Disappear|last1=Buckley|first1=Chris|date=11 October 2017|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=26 October 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025083913/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/11/world/asia/xi-jinping-military-china-purge.html|archive-date=25 October 2017|publisher=|last2=Myers|first2=Steven Lee}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\n{{main|Foreign policy of Xi Jinping}}\n[[File:Xi Jinping in USA.jpg|thumb|Xi giving a speech at the U.S. Department of State in 2012, with then Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]] and then Vice-President [[Joe Biden]] in the background. Seated in the front row is former Secretary of State [[Henry Kissinger]].]]\nA [[Chinese nationalism|Chinese nationalist]],<ref name=\"kuhn2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/1254093/xi-jinping-nationalist-and-reformer|title=Xi Jinping, a nationalist and a reformer|last=Kuhn|first=Robert Lawrence|date=6 June 2013|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805130812/https://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/1254093/xi-jinping-nationalist-and-reformer|archive-date=5 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Xi has reportedly taken a hard-line on security issues as well as foreign affairs, projecting a more nationalistic and assertive China on the world stage.<ref name=\"kuhn2\" /> His political program calls for a China more united and confident of its own value system and political structure.<ref name=\"scmp32\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1586307/xi-jinping-rules-out-western-style-political-reform-china?page=all|title=Xi Jinping rules out Western-style political reform for China|last1=Meng|first1=Angela|date=6 September 2014|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818085415/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1586307/xi-jinping-rules-out-western-style-political-reform-china?page=all|archive-date=18 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nUnder Xi China has also taken a more critical stance on North Korea, while improving [[China\u2013South Korea relations|relationships with South Korea]].<ref name=\"chengli2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.brookings.edu/research/interviews/2014/09/26-new-type-power-relationship-li|title=A New Type of Major Power Relationship?|last1=Li|first1=Cheng|date=26 September 2014|newspaper=[[Brookings Institution]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708161643/http://www.brookings.edu/research/interviews/2014/09/26-new-type-power-relationship-li|archive-date=8 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> China\u2013Japan relations have soured under Xi's [[Xi\u2013Li Administration|administration]]; the most thorny issue between the two countries remains the dispute over the [[Senkaku islands]], which China calls Diaoyu. In response to Japan's continued robust stance on the issue, China declared an [[Air Defense Identification Zone (East China Sea)|Air Defense Identification Zone]] in November 2013.<ref name=\"osawa2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.brookings.edu/research/opinions/2013/12/17-china-air-defense-identification-zone-osawa|title=China's ADIZ over the East China Sea: A \"Great Wall in the Sky\"?|last1=Osawa|first1=Jun|date=17 December 2013|newspaper=[[Brookings Institution]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714181744/http://www.brookings.edu/research/opinions/2013/12/17-china-air-defense-identification-zone-osawa|archive-date=14 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nXi has called [[China\u2013United States relations]] in the contemporary world a \"new type of great-power relations\", a phrase the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] had been reluctant to embrace.<ref name=\"nikkei2\">{{cite news|url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/International-Relations/A-new-kind-of-great-power-relationship-No-thanks-Obama-subtly-tells-China|title=A new kind of 'great power relationship'? No thanks, Obama subtly tells China|last1=Hiroyuki|first1=Akita|date=22 July 2014|access-date=11 November 2014|newspaper=[[Nikkei Asian Review]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111181321/http://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/International-Relations/A-new-kind-of-great-power-relationship-No-thanks-Obama-subtly-tells-China|archive-date=11 November 2014}}</ref> Under his administration the [[Strategic and Economic Dialogue]] that began under Hu Jintao has continued. On China\u2013U.S. relations, Xi said, \"If [China and the United States] are in confrontation, it would surely spell disaster for both countries\".<ref name=\"scmp22\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1550184/confrontation-us-would-be-disaster-says-president-xi-jinping?page=all|title=President Xi Jinping warns of disaster if Sino-US relations sour|last1=Ng|first1=Teddy|date=9 July 2014|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=7 September 2019|last2=Kwong|first2=Man-ki|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828224320/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1550184/confrontation-us-would-be-disaster-says-president-xi-jinping?page=all|archive-date=28 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  The U.S. has been critical of Chinese actions in the [[South China Sea]].<ref name=\"nikkei2\" /> In 2014, [[Cyberwarfare in China|Chinese hackers]] compromised the computer system of the [[United States Office of Personnel Management|U.S. Office of Personnel Management]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/08/24/politics/fbi-arrests-chinese-national-in-opm-data-breach/index.html|last1=Perez|first1=Evan|title=FBI arrests Chinese national connected to malware used in OPM data breach|date=24 August 2017|newspaper=CNN|access-date=29 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011015443/https://www.cnn.com/2017/08/24/politics/fbi-arrests-chinese-national-in-opm-data-breach/index.html|archive-date=11 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> resulting in the [[Office of Personnel Management data breach|theft]] of approximately 22 million personnel records handled by the office.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/federal-eye/wp/2015/07/09/hack-of-security-clearance-system-affected-21-5-million-people-federal-authorities-say/|title=Hacks of OPM databases compromised 22.1 million people, federal authorities say|last=Nakashima|first=Ellen|date=9 July 2015|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=29 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726051157/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/federal-eye/wp/2015/07/09/hack-of-security-clearance-system-affected-21-5-million-people-federal-authorities-say/|archive-date=26 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nXi has cultivated [[China\u2013Russia relations|stronger relations with Russia]], particularly in the wake of the [[2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine|Ukraine crisis]] of 2014. He seems to have developed a strong personal relationship with President Vladimir Putin. Both are viewed as strong leaders with a nationalist orientation who are not afraid to assert themselves against Western interests.<ref name=\"russia22\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/09/world/vladimir-putin-xi-jinping-form-closer-ties.html|title=As Russia Draws Closer to China, U.S. Faces a New Challenge|last1=Baker|first1=Peter|date=8 November 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828224309/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/09/world/vladimir-putin-xi-jinping-form-closer-ties.html|archive-date=28 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Xi attended the opening ceremonies of the 2014 Winter Olympics in Sochi. Under Xi, China signed a $400&nbsp;billion [[Natural gas in Russia|gas deal with Russia]]; China has also become Russia's largest trading partner.<ref name=\"russia22\" />[[File:BRICS heads of state and government hold hands ahead of the 2014 G-20 summit in Brisbane, Australia (Agencia Brasil).jpg|left|thumb|[[BRICS]] leaders [[Vladimir Putin]], [[Narendra Modi]], [[Dilma Rousseff]], Xi  Jinping and [[Jacob Zuma]] at the [[2014 G-20 Brisbane summit|G20 summit]] in [[Brisbane]], Australia, 15 November 2014]]\nXi has also indirectly spoken out critically on the U.S. \"strategic pivot\" to Asia.<ref name=\"blan2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/03/us-china-diplomacy-idUSKBN0F82GX20140703|title=With one eye on Washington, China plots its own Asia 'pivot'|last=Blanchard|first=Ben|date=3 July 2014|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006010842/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/03/us-china-diplomacy-idUSKBN0F82GX20140703|archive-date=6 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Addressing a [[Conference on Interaction and Confidence-Building Measures in Asia|regional conference]] in Shanghai on 21 May 2014, he called on Asian countries to unite and forge a way together, rather than get involved with third party powers, seen as a reference to the United States. \"Matters in Asia ultimately must be taken care of by Asians. Asia's problems ultimately must be resolved by Asians and Asia's security ultimately must be protected by Asians\", he told the conference.<ref name=\"TerritorialDisputes2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.chinanationalnews.com/index.php/sid/222207019/scat/9366300fc9319e9b/ht/Asian-nations-should-avoid-military-ties-with-third-party-powers-says-Chinas-Xi|title=Asian nations should avoid military ties with third party powers, says China's Xi|last=|first=|date=21 May 2014|newspaper=China National News|accessdate=21 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522071827/http://www.chinanationalnews.com/index.php/sid/222207019/scat/9366300fc9319e9b/ht/Asian-nations-should-avoid-military-ties-with-third-party-powers-says-Chinas-Xi|archive-date=22 May 2014}}</ref> In November 2014, in a major policy address, Xi called for a decrease in the use of force, preferring dialogue and consultation to solve the current issues plaguing the relationship between China and its South East Asian neighbors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/102225589#.|title=China's Xi tones down foreign policy rhetoric|last1=Miller|first1=Matthew|date=7 September 2019|newspaper=[[CNBC]]|accessdate=30 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206183128/http://www.cnbc.com/id/102225589#.|archive-date=6 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>[[File:\u041f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u044c 70-\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u041f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0434\u044b - 26.jpg|thumb|Xi with the first lady during the [[2015 Moscow Victory Day Parade|Moscow Victory Day Parade on 9 May 2015]]]]In April 2015, new satellite imagery revealed that China was rapidly constructing an airfield on [[Fiery Cross Reef]] in the [[Spratly Islands]] of the South China Sea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-32331964|title=China building runway in disputed South China Sea island|last=|first=|date=17 April 2015|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190909135656/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-32331964|archive-date=9 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> In May 2015, U.S. Secretary of Defense [[Ash Carter]] warned the government of Xi Jinping to halt its rapid [[Great Wall of Sand|island-building]] in disputed territory in the South China Sea.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2015/05/27/defense-secretarys-warning-to-china-u-s-military-wont-change-operations/|title=Defense secretary's warning to China: U.S. military won't change operations|last=Whitlock|first=Craig|date=27 May 2015|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=29 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030131220/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2015/05/27/defense-secretarys-warning-to-china-u-s-military-wont-change-operations/|archive-date=30 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\nIn spite of what seemed to be a tumultuous start to Xi Jinping's leadership vis-\u00e0-vis the United-States, on 13 May 2017 Xi said at the ''[[Belt and Road Forum]]'' in Beijing: \"We should foster a new type of international relations featuring 'win-win cooperation', and we should forge a partnership of dialogue with no confrontation, and a partnership of friendship rather than alliance. All countries should respect each other's sovereignty, dignity and territorial integrity; respect each other's development path and its social systems, and respect each other's core interests and major concerns... What we hope to create is a big family of harmonious coexistence.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=izR0EOgrKU0#t=438.705923|title=President Xi: Build the B&R into a road for peace, prosperity and connectivity|last=|first=|date=13 May 2017|website=[[CGTN]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029211503/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=izR0EOgrKU0#t=438.705923|archive-date=29 October 2018|access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref>[[File:Ali Khamenei receives Xi Jinping in his house (7).jpg|thumb|Xi with Iran's Supreme Leader [[Ali Khamenei]], 23 January 2016]]Starting in 2017, China's relationship with South Korea soured over the [[THAAD]] purchase of the latter<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/opinion/article/2083166/opinion-why-chinas-shadow-boycott-south-korea-self-defeating|title=Why China's economic jabs at South Korea are self-defeating|last=Huang|first=Cary|date=2 April 2017|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729174351/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/opinion/article/2083166/opinion-why-chinas-shadow-boycott-south-korea-self-defeating|archive-date=29 July 2019|url-status=live|access-date=29 July 2019}}</ref> while [[China\u2013North Korea relations|China's relations with North Korea]] increased because of [[Kim\u2013Xi meetings|meetings between Xi and North Korean leader Kim Jong-un.]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2139178/rumours-china-and-north-korea-were-no-longer-allies-put|title=Kim's visit evidence China, North Korea remain allies, analysts say|last=Shi|first=Jiangtao|last2=Chan|first2=Minnie|date=27 March 2018|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725192608/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2139178/rumours-china-and-north-korea-were-no-longer-allies-put|archive-date=25 July 2019|url-status=live|access-date=26 August 2019|last3=Zheng|first3=Sarah}}</ref> At the [[2019 G20 Osaka summit|G20 meeting in Japan]], Xi called for a \"timely easing\" of [[Sanctions against North Korea|sanctions imposed on North Korea]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3016981/beijing-reaffirms-support-gradual-easing-north-korea-sanctions|title=Xi calls for 'timely' easing of North Korea sanctions after Trump-Kim meeting|last=Lee|first=Jeong-ho|date=2 July 2019|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823115523/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3016981/beijing-reaffirms-support-gradual-easing-north-korea-sanctions|archive-date=23 August 2019|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nRelations with the U.S. soured after [[Donald Trump]] became president in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/blogs/asia/2019/05/china-trade-war-sino-american-ties-torn-brick-brick-190512132227395.html|title=China-US trade war: Sino-American ties being torn down brick by brick|last=Brown|first=Adrian|date=12 May 2019|newspaper=[[Al Jazeera]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904140940/https://www.aljazeera.com/blogs/asia/2019/05/china-trade-war-sino-american-ties-torn-brick-brick-190512132227395.html|archive-date=4 September 2019|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref> Since 2018, U.S. and China have been engaged in an [[China\u2013United States trade war|escalating trade war]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/05/business/china-us-trade-war-trump-tariffs.html|title=Trump's Trade War With China Is Officially Underway|last=Swanson|first=Ana|date=2018-07-05|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-05-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712201844/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/05/business/china-us-trade-war-trump-tariffs.html|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 4 June 2019, Xi told the Russian news agency [[TASS]] that he was \"worried\" about the current tensions between the U.S. and Iran.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/06/xi-worried-extreme-pressure-iran-raises-tensions-190605015731670.html|title=Xi worried as 'extreme' US pressure on Iran raises tensions|last=|first=|date=5 June 2019|newspaper=[[Al Jazeera]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905161609/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/06/xi-worried-extreme-pressure-iran-raises-tensions-190605015731670.html|archive-date=5 September 2019|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref> He later told his Iranian counterpart [[Hassan Rouhani]] during an [[Shanghai Cooperation Organization|SCO]] meeting that China would promote [[China\u2013Iran relations|ties with Iran]] regardless of developments from the [[June 2019 Gulf of Oman incident|Gulf of Oman incident]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-attacks/xi-says-china-will-promote-steady-ties-with-iran-idUSKCN1TF0IH|title=Xi says China will promote steady ties with Iran|last=Martina|first=Michael|date=14 June 2019|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=14 June 2019|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912211154/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-attacks/xi-says-china-will-promote-steady-ties-with-iran-idUSKCN1TF0IH|archive-date=12 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>[[File:President Trump's Trip to Asia (37575409684).jpg|thumb|U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] arrives in China, 8 November 2017]]\n\n====Foreign trips as paramount leader====\n{{Main|List of international trips made by Xi Jinping}}\nXi made his first foreign trip as China's [[paramount leader]] to Russia on 22 March 2013, about a week after he assumed the presidency. He met with President [[Vladimir Putin]] and the two leaders discussed trade and energy issues. He then went on to Tanzania, South Africa (where he attended the [[BRICS]] summit in [[Durban]]), and the Republic of the Congo.<ref name=\"russiaafrica2\">{{cite news|url=http://en.people.cn/90883/8189481.html|title=Xi's maiden foreign tour historic, fruitful|last=Wu|first=Liming|date=1 April 2013|work=[[People's Daily]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617165730/http://en.people.cn/90883/8189481.html|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Xi visited the United States at [[Sunnylands]] Estate in California in a 'shirtsleeves summit' with U.S. President Barack Obama in June 2013, although this was not considered a formal state visit.<ref name=\"sunnylands2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.brookings.edu/blogs/up-front/posts/2013/06/10-obama-xi-sunnylands-bush|title=Obama and Xi at Sunnylands: A Good Start|last1=Bush|first1=Richard C. III|date=10 June 2013|work=[[Brookings Institution]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605213252/http://www.brookings.edu/blogs/up-front/posts/2013/06/10-obama-xi-sunnylands-bush|archive-date=5 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2013 Xi attended the [[APEC Summit]] in [[Bali]], Indonesia.\n\nIn March 2014 Xi made a trip to Western Europe visiting the Netherlands, where he attended the [[Nuclear Security Summit]] in [[The Hague]], followed by visits to France, Germany and Belgium.<ref name=\"europe2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2014xivisiteu/|title=President Xi visits Western Europe|last=|first=|date=22 March 2014|newspaper=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016132459/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2014xivisiteu/|archive-date=16 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He made a state visit to South Korea on 4 July 2014 and met with South Korean President [[Park Geun-hye]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.korea.net/NewsFocus/Society/view?articleId=120421|title=President Xi, 'Korea-China relations better than ever'|author=|first=|date=4 July 2014|website=[[Korea.net]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029232400/http://www.korea.net/NewsFocus/Society/view?articleId=120421|archive-date=29 October 2018|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> Between 14 and 23 July, Xi attended the BRICS leaders' summit in Brazil and visited Argentina, Venezuela, and Cuba.<ref name=\"latin2\">{{cite news|url=http://carnegieendowment.org/2014/09/05/xi-jinping-s-july-2014-trip-to-latin-america|title=Xi Jinping's July 2014 Trip to Latin America|last=Swaine|first=Michael D.|date=5 September 2014|work=[[Carnegie Endowment for International Peace]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029232408/http://carnegieendowment.org/2014/09/05/xi-jinping-s-july-2014-trip-to-latin-america|archive-date=29 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wsp\u00f3lne o\u015bwiadczenie w sprawie ustanowienia wszechstronnego strategicznego partnerstwa.jpg|thumb|left|Xi in an official visit to [[Warsaw]], where he and Poland's President [[Andrzej Duda]] signed a declaration on strategic partnership]]\nXi went on an official state visit to India and met with Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] in September 2014; he visited New Delhi and also went to Modi's hometown in the state of [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\"india2\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Chinese-incursion-in-Ladakh-A-little-toothache-can-paralyze-entire-body-Modi-tells-Xi-Jinping/articleshow/42940337.cms|title=Chinese incursion in Ladakh: A little toothache can paralyze entire body, Modi tells Xi Jinping|last=|first=|date=20 September 2014|work=[[The Times of India]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711075407/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Chinese-incursion-in-Ladakh-A-little-toothache-can-paralyze-entire-body-Modi-tells-Xi-Jinping/articleshow/42940337.cms|archive-date=11 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He went on a state visit to Australia and met with Prime Minister [[Tony Abbott]] in November 2014,<ref name=\"smh2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au//breaking-news-national/xi-says-time-to-lift-relations-20141119-3kn7n.html|last1=Salna|first1=Karlis|last2=Blenkin|first2=Max|title=Xi says time to lift relations|date=19 November 2014|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=20 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924102909/http://www.smh.com.au//breaking-news-national/xi-says-time-to-lift-relations-20141119-3kn7n.html|archive-date=24 September 2015}}</ref> followed by a visit to the island nation of Fiji.<ref name=\"fiji2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-11-22/chinese-president-xi-visits-fiji-to-strengthen-economic-ties/5911144|title=Chinese president Xi Jinping signs five agreements with Fiji as part of China's Pacific engagement strategy|last=Fox|first=Liam|date=22 November 2015|work=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520205458/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-11-22/chinese-president-xi-visits-fiji-to-strengthen-economic-ties/5911144|archive-date=20 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Xi [[Xi Jinping's visit to Pakistan 2015|visited Pakistan]] in April 2015, signing a series of infrastructure deals worth $45&nbsp;billion related to the [[China\u2013Pakistan Economic Corridor]]. During his visit, Pakistan's highest civilian award, the [[Nishan-e-Pakistan]], was conferred upon him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/pak-confers-highest-civilian-award-on-chinese-president-xi/article1-1339490.aspx|title=Pakistan confers Nishan-e-Pakistan on Chinese president Xi Jinping|last=|first=|date=21 April 2015|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811203441/http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/pak-confers-highest-civilian-award-on-chinese-president-xi/article1-1339490.aspx|archive-date=11 August 2015|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> He then headed to [[Jakarta]] and [[Bandung]], Indonesia, to attend the Afro-Asian Leaders Summit and the 60th Anniversary events of the [[Bandung Conference]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/20/world/asia/chinas-president-heads-to-pakistan-with-billions-in-infrastructure-aid.html|title=Xi Jinping Heads to Pakistan, Bearing Billions in Infrastructure Aid|last=Perlez|first=Jane|date=19 April 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109223101/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/20/world/asia/chinas-president-heads-to-pakistan-with-billions-in-infrastructure-aid.html|archive-date=9 November 2016|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Xi visited Russia and was the guest-of-honour of Russian President Vladimir Putin at the [[2015 Moscow Victory Day Parade]] to mark the 70th Anniversary of the victory of the allies in Europe. At the parade, Xi and his wife Peng Liyuan sat next to Putin. On the same trip Xi also visited Kazakhstan and met with that country's president [[Nursultan Nazarbayev]], and also met [[Alexander Lukashenko]] in Belarus.<ref name=\"russia3\">{{cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/05/at-russias-military-parade-putin-and-xi-cement-ties/|title=At Russia's Military Parade, Putin and Xi Cement Ties|last=Tiezzi|first=Shannon|date=9 May 2015|work=[[The Diplomat]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411125137/https://thediplomat.com/2015/05/at-russias-military-parade-putin-and-xi-cement-ties/|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Xi Jinping in British Parliament.jpg|thumb|Xi, who was on a four-day state visit to the UK, addressed both [[List of people who have addressed both Houses of the United Kingdom Parliament|Houses of Parliament]] at [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]], 21 October 2015]]\nIn September 2015, Xi made his [[2015 Xi Jinping visit to the United States|first state visit to the United States]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://multimedia.scmp.com/xi-jinping-us-visit/|title=Xi Jinping's US visit: itinerary, issues and delegation|last=Gan|first=Nectar|last2=Sam|first2=Cedric|date=30 September 2015|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904155049/http://multimedia.scmp.com/xi-jinping-us-visit/|archive-date=4 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/22/china-president-xi-jinping-first-us-visit-seattle|title=China's President Xi Jinping begins first US visit in Seattle|last=|first=|date=22 September 2015|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714065843/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/22/china-president-xi-jinping-first-us-visit-seattle|archive-date=14 July 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/projects/cp/reporters-notebook/xi-jinping-visit|title=Xi Jinping's U.S. Visit|last=Perlez|first=Jane|date=30 September 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111084720/http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/projects/cp/reporters-notebook/xi-jinping-visit|archive-date=11 November 2016|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In October 2015, he made a [[2015 Xi Jinping visit to the United Kingdom|state visit to the United Kingdom]], the first by a Chinese leader in a decade.<ref name=\"ukvisit2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/china-state-visit-programme|title=China State Visit Programme|date=20 October 2015|website=royal.uk|access-date=29 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029191739/https://www.royal.uk/china-state-visit-programme|archive-date=29 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> This followed a visit to China in March 2015 by the [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Duke of Cambridge]]. During the state visit, Xi met [[Queen Elizabeth II]], British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] and other dignitaries. Increased customs, trade and research collaborations between China and the UK were discussed, but more informal events also took place including a visit to [[Manchester City]]'s [[Association football|football]] academy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/chinese-president-xi-jinping-visit-10315388|title=Chinese president Xi Jinping visit: United fan premier to visit Manchester City's stadium|last=Williams|first=Jennifer|date=23 October 2015|newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714065912/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/chinese-president-xi-jinping-visit-10315388|archive-date=14 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Xi visited the Czech Republic on his way to United States. In [[Prague]], he met with the Czech president, prime minister and other representatives to promote relations and economic cooperation between the Czech Republic and the People's Republic of China.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-czech-china-idUSKCN0WU01J|title=Czech courtship pays off with landmark visit from Chinese leader|last=Muller|first=Robert|date=28 March 2016|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=28 March 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025050433/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-czech-china-idUSKCN0WU01J|archivedate=25 October 2016|last2=Lopatka|first2=Jan}}</ref> His visit was met by a considerable number of protests by Czechs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/protests-chinas-xi-arrives-prague-173355899.html|title=Protests as China's Xi arrives in Prague|last=Marchal|first=Jan|date=28 March 2016|newspaper=[[Agence France-Presse]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408223306/https://www.yahoo.com/news/protests-chinas-xi-arrives-prague-173355899.html|archivedate=8 April 2016|accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:2017 G20 Hamburg summit leaders group photo.jpg|thumb|World leaders assemble for 'family photo' at [[2017 G20 Hamburg summit|G20 summit]] in Hamburg]]\nIn January 2017, Xi became the first Chinese paramount leader to plan to attend the [[World Economic Forum]] in [[Davos]].<ref name=\":1\">de la Merced, Michael J., and Russell Goldman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/14/world/europe/world-economic-forum-davos-explainer-global-elite-parties.html \"How Davos Brings the Global Elite Together\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115201351/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/14/world/europe/world-economic-forum-davos-explainer-global-elite-parties.html |date=15 January 2017 }}, ''New York Times'', 14 January 2017. Retrieved 15 January 2017</ref> On 17 January, Xi addressed the forum in a high-profile keynote, addressing [[globalization]], the global trade agenda, and China's rising place in the world's economy and international governance; he made a series of pledges about China's defense of \"economic globalization\" and climate change accords.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cn.nytimes.com/china/20170111/davos-china-xi-jinping-trump/|script-title=zh:\u7784\u51c6\u5168\u7403\u4e8b\u52a1\u9886\u5bfc\u6743\uff0c\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u5c06\u9996\u6b21\u51fa\u5e2d\u8fbe\u6c83\u65af|last=Huang|first=Anwei|date=11 January 2017|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|trans-title=Aimed At Global Affairs, Xi Jinping Will Attend Davos Conference For First Time|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231034906/https://cn.nytimes.com/china/20170111/davos-china-xi-jinping-trump/|archive-date=31 December 2018|access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://en.people.cn/n3/2017/0111/c90000-9165250.html|title=Xi first top Chinese leader at Davos|last=Kou|first=Jie|date=11 January 2017|newspaper=[[People's Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617132421/http://en.people.cn/n3/2017/0111/c90000-9165250.html|archive-date=17 June 2019|access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref> Premier [[Li Keqiang]] attended the forum in 2015 and Vice-President [[Li Yuanchao]] did so in 2016. During the three-day [[state visit]] to the country in 2017 Xi also visited the [[World Health Organization]], the [[United Nations Office at Geneva|United Nations]] and the [[International Olympic Committee]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 20 June 2019, Xi Jinping visited [[Pyongyang]], becoming the first Chinese leader to visit North Korea since his predecessor Hu Jintao's visit in 2004.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/20/world/asia/xi-jinping-china-north-korea.html|title=Xi Jinping Arrives in North Korea, With Many Eyes on Trump|last=Perlez|first=Jane|date=20 June 2019|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=7 September 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905094512/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/20/world/asia/xi-jinping-china-north-korea.html|archive-date=5 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 27 June, he attended the [[2019 G20 Osaka summit|G20 summit in Osaka]], becoming the first Chinese leader to visit Japan since 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-06/27/c_138178312.htm|title=Chinese President Xi Jinping arrives in Osaka, Japan for G20 summit|last=Yinglun|first=Shi|date=27 June 2019|newspaper=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191018055659/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-06/27/c_138178312.htm|archive-date=18 October 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Belt and Road Initiative ====\n{{main|Belt and Road Initiative}}\n[[File:Belt and Road Initiative participant map.svg|thumb|300x300px|Countries which signed cooperation documents related to the Belt and Road Initiative]]\nThe [[Belt and Road Initiative]] (BRI) was unveiled by Xi in September and October 2013 during visits to [[Kazakhstan]] and [[Indonesia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.gov.cn/news/top_news/2015/04/20/content_281475092566326.htm|title=Chronology of China's Belt and Road Initiative|website=[[State Council of the People's Republic of China]]|language=en|access-date=23 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923085510/http://english.gov.cn/news/top_news/2015/04/20/content_281475092566326.htm|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and was thereafter promoted by [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier]] [[Li Keqiang]] during [[state visit]]s to [[Asia]] and [[Europe]]. Xi made the announcement for the initiative while in Astana, Kazakhstan, and called it a \"golden opportunity\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2013-09/08/content_16952304.htm|title=Xi proposes a 'new Silk Road' with Central Asia|last=Jiao|first=Wu|date=8 September 2013|work=[[China Daily]]|access-date=29 October 2018|display-authors=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029232425/http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2013-09/08/content_16952304.htm|archive-date=29 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> BRI has been called Xi's \"signature project\", involving numerous infrastructure development and investment projects throughout  [[Asia]], [[Europe]], [[Africa]], and the [[Americas]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://time.com/5578514/china-xi-jinping-belt-road-corruption-debt/|title=Xi Jinping Says China's Belt and Road Initiative Is Not Saddling Poor Countries With Debt|last=|first=|date=26 April 2019|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=10 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> BRI was added to the [[Constitution of the Communist Party of China|constitution of the CPC]] at the closing session of the [[19th National Congress of the Communist Party of China|19th Party Congress]] in 24 October 2017,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-10/24/c_136702025.htm|title=\"Belt and Road\" incorporated into CPC Constitution|last=|first=|date=24 October 2017|work=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|access-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> further elevating its importance.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/10/31/china-wrote-belt-and-road-initiative-into-the-party-constitution.html|title=China wrote Belt and Road Initiative into the party constitution. That makes it riskier than ever|last=Tan|first=Huileng|date=31 October 2017|work=[[CNBC]]|access-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Human rights policy===\n{{main|Human rights in China}}According to the [[Human Rights Watch]], Xi has \"started a broad and sustained offensive on human rights\" since he became leader in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2018/country-chapters/china-and-tibet|title=World Report 2018: Rights Trends in China|date=9 January 2018|website=[[Human Rights Watch]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828203028/https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2018/country-chapters/china-and-tibet|archive-date=28 August 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> The HRW also said that repression in China is \"at its worst level since the [[1989 Tiananmen Square protests|Tiananmen Square massacre]].\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/china-repression-freedom-police-censorship-tiananmen-square-human-rights-watch-a8732501.html|title=Repression in China at worst level since Tiananmen Square, HRW warns|last=Withnall|first=Adam|date=17 January 2019|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524133120/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/china-repression-freedom-police-censorship-tiananmen-square-human-rights-watch-a8732501.html|archive-date=24 May 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> Since taking power, Xi has intensified crackdown against dissent, with hundreds being detained.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/b4de464a-7242-11e9-bf5c-6eeb837566c5|title=China widens crackdown against grassroot activists|last=|first=|date=9 May 2019|work=[[Financial Times]]|access-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He presided over the [[709 crackdown]] in 9 July 2015, which saw more than 200 lawyers, legal assistants and human rights activists being detained.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-china-blog-39974953|title=Wang Quanzhang: The lawyer who simply vanished|last=Sudworth|first=John|date=22 May 2017|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Xi's term has resulted in a further suppression of dissent from civil society. His term has seen the arrest and imprisonment of activists such as [[Xu Zhiyong]], as well as numerous others who identified with the [[New Citizens' Movement]]. Prominent legal activist [[Pu Zhiqiang]] of the [[Weiquan movement]] was also arrested and detained.<ref name=\"afp2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/world/419842/chinese-dream-turns-sour-for-activists-under-xi-jinping|title=Chinese dream turns sour for activists under Xi Jinping|last=|first=|date=10 July 2014|newspaper=[[Bangkok Post]]|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the local government of the [[Jiangxi|Jiangxi province]] told [[Christianity in China|Christians]] to replace their pictures of [[Jesus]] with Xi Jinping as part of a general [[Antireligious campaigns in China|antireligious campaign]] in the country.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/policies-politics/article/2119699/praise-xi-jinping-not-jesus-escape-poverty-christian|title=Replace pictures of Jesus with Xi to escape poverty, Chinese villagers urged|last=Gan|first=Nectar|date=14 November 2017|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717174448/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/policies-politics/article/2119699/praise-xi-jinping-not-jesus-escape-poverty-christian|archive-date=17 July 2019|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/11/14/jesus-wont-save-you-president-xi-jinping-will-chinese-christians-told/|title=Jesus won't save you - President Xi Jinping will, Chinese Christians told|last=Denyer|first=Simon|date=14 November 2017|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531100111/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/11/14/jesus-wont-save-you-president-xi-jinping-will-chinese-christians-told/|archive-date=31 May 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/sep/28/we-are-scared-but-we-have-jesus-china-and-its-war-on-christianity|title='We are scared, but we have Jesus': China and its war on Christianity|last=Haas|first=Benjamin|date=28 September 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=7 September 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823155226/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/sep/28/we-are-scared-but-we-have-jesus-china-and-its-war-on-christianity|archive-date=23 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Associated Press|The Associated Press]] reported in 2018 that \"Xi is waging the most severe systematic [[Christianity in China#Restrictions and international interest|suppression of Christianity]] in the country since religious freedom was written into the Chinese constitution in 1982\", which has involved \"destroying crosses, burning bibles, shutting churches and ordering followers to sign papers renouncing their faith\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.apnews.com/c09b2ee4b71540c8a7fd6178820c5970|title=Group: Officials destroying crosses, burning bibles in China|last=Bodeen|first=Christopher|date=10 September 2018|work=[[Associated Press]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008144601/https://www.apnews.com/c09b2ee4b71540c8a7fd6178820c5970|archive-date=8 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing several terrorist attacks in [[Xinjiang]] in 2013 and 2014, Xi launched the \"[[Strike Hard Campaign Against Violent Terrorism|people's war on terror]]\" in 2014, which involved increasing surveillance and repression against ethnic [[Uyghurs]] there.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/48508182-d426-11e9-8367-807ebd53ab77|title=Fear and oppression in Xinjiang: China's war on Uighur culture|last=Shepherd|first=Christian|date=12 September 2019|work=[[Financial Times]]|access-date=19 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Xi made an inspection tour in Xinjiang between April 27 and April 30 in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.agri.gov.cn/news/dqnf/201405/t20140504_21806.htm|title=President Xi Jinping makes inspection tour in Xinjiang|date=4 May 2014|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=[[Ministry of Agriculture of the People's Republic of China]] (from [[Xinhua News Agency]])|quote=Xi made an inspection tour in Xinjiang from April 27 to 30.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2017-06/01/content_29570422_10.htm|title=Xi's Moments With Children|date=1 June 2017|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=[[China Daily]]|quote=President Xi Jinping poses for a group picture with students of a primary school in Tokkuzak town of Shufu county in Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur autonomous region, April 28, 2014.}}</ref> As of 2019, China is holding one million ethnic Uyghurs in [[Xinjiang re-education camps|internment camps in Xinjiang]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/01/opinion/xi-jinping-china.html|title=Opinion {{!}} What Xi Jinping Hasn't Learned From China's Emperors|last=Millward|first=James A.|date=2019-10-01|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-10-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015061213/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/01/opinion/xi-jinping-china.html|archive-date=15 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Various human rights groups and former inmates have described the camps as \u201cconcentration camps\u201d, where Uyghurs and other minorities have been forcibly assimilated into China's majority [[Han Chinese|ethnic Han]] society.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/11/more-than-20-ambassadors-condemn-chinas-treatment-of-uighurs-in-xinjiang|title=More than 20 ambassadors condemn China's treatment of Uighurs in Xinjiang|last=|first=|date=11 July 2019|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711031342/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/11/more-than-20-ambassadors-condemn-chinas-treatment-of-uighurs-in-xinjiang|archive-date=11 July 2019|accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref> [[Xinjiang papers|Internal Chinese government documents]] leaked to the press in November 2019 showed that Xi personally ordered a security crackdown in Xinjiang, saying that the party must show \u201cabsolutely no mercy\u201d and that officials use all the \u201cweapons of the [[people's democratic dictatorship]]\u201d to suppress Muslims \u201cinfected with the virus of extremism\u201d.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/16/world/asia/china-xinjiang-documents.html|title='Absolutely No Mercy': Leaked Files Expose How China Organized Mass Detentions of Muslims|last=Ramzy|first=Austin|last2=Buckley|first2=Chris|date=16 November 2019|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2020/01/19/huaweis-human-rights-record-needs-scrutiny-britain-signs-5g-contracts/|title=Huawei's human rights record needs scrutiny before Britain signs 5G contracts|last=Tugendhat|first=Tom|date=19 January 2020|newspaper=[[Hong Kong Free Press]]|access-date=19 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The documents also showed that Xi repeatedly discussed about [[Islamic extremism]] in his speeches, likening it to a \"virus\" or a \"drug\" which could be only addressed by \"a period of painful, interventionary treatment.\u201d<ref name=\":11\" /> However, he also warned against discriminating against Uyghurs and rejected proposals to eradicate [[Islam in China]] completely, calling that kind of viewpoint \"biased, even wrong\".<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n==Political positions==\n{{further|Ideology of the Communist Party of China}}\n\n[[Elizabeth Economy|Elizabeth C. Economy]] argued in 2018:\n:What makes Xi\u2019s revolution distinctive is the strategy he has pursued: the dramatic centralization of authority under his personal leadership; the intensified penetration of society by the state; the creation of a virtual wall of regulations and restrictions that more tightly control the flow of ideas, culture and capital into and out of the country; and the significant projection of Chinese power. It represents a reassertion of the state in Chinese political and economic life at home, and a more ambitious and expansive role for China abroad.{{sfn|Economy|p=10|2018}}\n\n=== Chinese Dream ===\n{{main|Chinese Dream}}\n[[File:Lujiazui 2016.jpg|thumb|According to the ''[[Qiushi]]'', the Chinese Dream is about Chinese prosperity, collective effort, socialism, and national glory.]]\nXi and Communist Party ideologues coined the phrase \"Chinese Dream\" to describe his overarching plans for China as its leader. Xi first used the phrase during a high-profile visit to the [[National Museum of China]] on 29 November 2012, where he and his Standing Committee colleagues were attending a \"national revival\" exhibition. Since then, the phrase has become the signature political slogan of the Xi era.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/2013/05/04/xi-jinping-and-the-chinese-dream|title=Xi Jinping and the Chinese dream|last=|first=|date=4 May 2013|work=[[The Economist]]|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510092423/http://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21577070-vision-chinas-new-president-should-serve-his-people-not-nationalist-state-xi-jinping|archive-date=10 May 2016|issn=0013-0613}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/9935609/Xi-Jinping-calls-for-a-Chinese-Dream.html|title=Xi Jinping calls for a Chinese dream|last1=Moore|first1=Malcolm|date=17 March 2013|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=20 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320072154/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/9935609/Xi-Jinping-calls-for-a-Chinese-Dream.html|archive-date=20 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Since 2013, the phrase has emerged as the distinctive quasi-official ideology of the party leadership under Xi, much as the \"[[Scientific Outlook on Development]]\" was for Hu Jintao and the \"[[Three Represents]]\" was for [[Jiang Zemin]]. The origin of the term \"Chinese Dream\" is unclear. While the phrase has been used before by journalists and scholars,<ref name=\"atlantic2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/china/archive/2013/05/todays-china-notes-dreams-obstacles/275544/|title=Today's China Notes: Dreams, Obstacles|last=Fallows|first=James|date=3 May 2013|work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712023142/https://www.theatlantic.com/china/archive/2013/05/todays-china-notes-dreams-obstacles/275544/|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> some publications have posited the term likely drew its inspiration from the concept of the [[American Dream]].<ref name=\"economist22\">{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/analects/2013/05/chinese-dream-0|title=The role of Thomas Friedman|last=M.|first=J.|date=6 May 2013|work=[[The Economist]]|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028145059/https://www.economist.com/blogs/analects/2013/05/chinese-dream-0|archive-date=28 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Economist]]'' noted the abstract and seemingly accessible nature of the concept with no specific overarching policy stipulations may be a deliberate departure from the jargon-heavy ideologies of his predecessors.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21577063-chinas-new-leader-has-been-quick-consolidate-his-power-what-does-he-now-want-his|title=Chasing the Chinese dream |date=4 May 2013|work=[[The Economist]]|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028080732/http://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21577063-chinas-new-leader-has-been-quick-consolidate-his-power-what-does-he-now-want-his|archive-date=28 October 2016|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> While the Chinese Dream was originally interpreted as an extension of the American Dream, which emphasises individual self-improvement and opportunity,<ref name=\":4\" /> the slogan's use in official settings since 2013 has taken on a noticeably more nationalistic character, with official pronouncements of the \"Dream\" being consistently linked with the phrase \"great revival of the Chinese nation\".{{NoteTag|{{zh|links=no|s=\u4e2d\u534e\u6c11\u65cf\u4f1f\u5927\u590d\u5174}}, which can also be translated as the \"Great Renaissance of the Chinese nation\" or the \"Great revival of the Chinese people\".}}\n\n===Cultural revival===\nAs [[communist ideology]] plays a less central role in the lives of the masses in the People's Republic of China, top political leaders of the [[Communist Party of China]] such as Xi continue the rehabilitation of ancient Chinese philosophical figures like [[Han Fei]] into the mainstream of Chinese thought alongside [[Confucianism]], both of which Xi sees as relevant. At a meeting with other officials in 2013, he quoted [[Confucius]], saying \"he who rules by virtue is like the Pole Star, it maintains its place, and the multitude of stars pay homage.\" While visiting [[Shandong]], the birthplace of Confucius, in November, he told scholars that the [[Western world]] was \"suffering a crisis of confidence\" and that the CPC has been \"the loyal inheritor and promoter of China's outstanding [[Traditional Chinese culture|traditional culture]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/12/world/leader-taps-into-chinese-classics-in-seeking-to-cement-power.html|title=Leader Taps into Chinese Classics in Seeking to Cement Power|last=Buckley|first=Chris|date=12 October 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912091736/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/12/world/leader-taps-into-chinese-classics-in-seeking-to-cement-power.html|archive-date=12 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nHan Fei gained new prominence with favourable citations. One sentence of Han Fei's that Xi quoted appeared thousands of times in official Chinese media at the local, provincial, and national levels.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/01/is-chinas-machiavelli-now-its-most-important-political-philosopher/|title=Is 'China's Machiavelli' Now Its Most Important Political Philosopher?|last=Mitchell|first=Ryan Mi|date=16 January 2015|newspaper=[[The Diplomat]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912091739/https://thediplomat.com/2015/01/is-chinas-machiavelli-now-its-most-important-political-philosopher/|archive-date=12 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nXi has also overseen a revival of traditional [[Chinese culture]], breaking apart from CPC's path which had often attacked it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2017/08/17/the-communist-party-is-redefining-what-it-means-to-be-chinese|title=The Communist Party is redefining what it means to be Chinese|last=|first=|date=17 August 2017|work=[[The Economist]]|access-date=23 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He has called traditional culture the \"soul\" of the nation and the \"foundation\" of the CPC's culture.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jamestown.org/program/xi-jinping-chinas-traditionalist-restoration/|title=Xi Jinping and China's Traditionalist Restoration|last=Zi|first=Yang|date=6 July 2016|work=[[The Jamestown Foundation]]|access-date=23 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Ancient Chinese clothing|Hanfu]], the traditional dress of [[Han Chinese]], has seen a revival under him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/life-and-luxury/fashion-and-style/why-its-hip-to-be-oldfashioned-in-china-20181129-h18hql|title=China's 'Hanfu' movement is making it hip to be old-fashioned. Here's why.|last=Buckley|first=Chris|date=30 November 2018|work=[[The Australian Financial Review]]|access-date=23 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Xi Jinping Thought===\n{{main|Xi Jinping Thought}}\n[[File:A political slogan on the wall in Longhua District, Shenzhen, Guangdong, China, picture1.jpg|thumb|A billboard advertising [[Xi Jinping Thought]] in [[Shenzhen]]]]\nIn September 2017, the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|Communist Party Central Committee]] decided that Xi's political philosophies, generally referred to as \"Xi Jinping Thought\", would become part of the Party Constitution.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/politics/2017-09/18/c_1121683516.htm|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u5171\u4e2d\u592e\u653f\u6cbb\u5c40\u53ec\u5f00\u4f1a\u8bae \u7814\u7a76\u62df\u63d0\u8bf7\u515a\u7684\u5341\u516b\u5c4a\u4e03\u4e2d\u5168\u4f1a\u8ba8\u8bba\u7684\u6587\u4ef6-\u65b0\u534e\u7f51|last=Liu|first=Xiaodong|last2=Chen|first2=Yu|date=18 September 2017|newspaper=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|language=zh-hans|trans-title=The Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee Convened to Study the Documents to be Submitted to the Seventh Plenary Session of the 18th CPC Central Committee|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011094706/http://news.xinhuanet.com/politics/2017-09/18/c_1121683516.htm|archive-date=11 October 2017|access-date=4 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://chinadigitaltimes.net/2017/09/party-constitution-amendment-signal-xis-power/|title=CCP Constitution Amendment May Signal Xi's Power - China Digital Times (CDT)|last=Rudolph|first=Josh|date=19 September 2017|work=[[China Digital Times]] (CDT)|access-date=4 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003234252/http://chinadigitaltimes.net/2017/09/party-constitution-amendment-signal-xis-power/|archive-date=3 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Xi first made mention of the \"Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New Era\" in his opening day speech delivered to the [[19th National Congress of the Communist Party of China|19th Party Congress]] in October 2017. His Politburo Standing Committee colleagues, in their own reviews of Xi's keynote address at the Congress, prepended the name \"Xi Jinping\" in front of \"Thought\".<ref name=\"xithought2\">{{cite news|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-10/19/c_136689808.htm|title=CPC creates Xi Jinping Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New Era|last1=Zhang|first1=Ling|date=18 October 2017|work=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|accessdate=19 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018195301/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-10/19/c_136689808.htm|archive-date=18 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 24 October 2017, at its closing session, the 19th Party Congress approved the incorporation of Xi Jinping Thought into the Constitution of the Communist Party of China.<ref name=\"PhillipsGuardian2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/19thcpcnationalcongress/2017-10/24/content_33644524.htm|title=Xi Jinping Thought approved for Party Constitution|last=An|first=Baijie|date=24 October 2017|newspaper=[[China Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014092252/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/19thcpcnationalcongress/2017-10/24/content_33644524.htm|archive-date=14 October 2019|access-date=12 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nXi himself has described the Thought as part of the broad framework created around [[Socialism with Chinese Characteristics]], a term coined by Deng Xiaoping that places China in the \"[[primary stage of socialism]]\". In official party documentation and pronouncements by Xi's colleagues, the Thought is said to be a continuation of [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]], [[Mao Zedong Thought]], Deng Xiaoping Theory, the \"Three Represents\", and the [[Scientific Outlook on Development|Scientific Development Perspective]], as part of a series of guiding ideologies that embody \"Marxism adopted to Chinese conditions\" and contemporary considerations.<ref name=\"xithought2\" />[[File:201901 Xi Jinping's books at Shanghai Library.jpg|left|thumb|''[[The Governance of China]]'' in different languages presented at [[Shanghai Library]]]]The concepts and context behind Xi Jinping Thought are elaborated in Xi's ''[[The Governance of China]]'' book series, published by the [[Foreign Languages Press]] for an international audience. Volume one was published in September 2014, followed by volume two in November 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-11/07/c_136733705.htm|title=Second volume of Xi's book on governance published|last=Yang|first=Yi|date=7 November 2017|newspaper=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206143920/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-11/07/c_136733705.htm|archive-date=6 December 2017|access-date=6 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn app for teaching \u201cXi Jinping Thought\u201d has become the most popular smartphone app in China, as the country's ruling Communist Party launched a new campaign that calls on its cadres to immerse themselves in the political doctrine every day. ''[[Xuexi Qiangguo]]'', which translates to \u201cStudy powerful country\u201d, is now the most downloaded item on Apple's domestic App Store, surpassing in demand social media apps such as [[WeChat]] and [[TikTok]] \u2013 known as Weixin and Douyin, respectively, in mainland China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/tech/apps-social/article/2186037/chinas-most-popular-app-propaganda-tool-teaching-xi-jinping-thought|title=China's most popular app is a propaganda tool teaching Xi Jinping Thought|last=Huang|first=Zheping|date=14 February 2019|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=7 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920105809/https://www.scmp.com/tech/apps-social/article/2186037/chinas-most-popular-app-propaganda-tool-teaching-xi-jinping-thought|archive-date=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Role of the Communist Party===\n{{See also|Eight-point Regulation}}In Xi's view, the Communist Party is the legitimate, constitutionally-sanctioned ruling party of China, and that the party derives this legitimacy through advancing the Mao-style \"[[mass line]] Campaign\"; that is the party represents the interests of the overwhelming majority of ordinary people. In this vein, Xi called for officials to practise mild [[self-criticism]] in order to appear less corrupt and more popular among the people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thediplomat.com/2013/09/chinas-mass-line-campaign-2/|title=China's 'Mass Line' Campaign|last1=Forde|first1=Brendan|date=9 September 2013|work=[[The Diplomat]]|accessdate=23 June 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624035650/https://thediplomat.com/2013/09/chinas-mass-line-campaign-2/|archive-date=24 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/21/world/asia/china-revives-mao-era-self-criticism-but-this-kind-bruises-few-egos.html|title=China Revives Mao-Era Self-Criticism, but This Kind Bruises Few Egos|last1=Levin|first1=Dan|date=20 December 2013|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=23 June 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624010400/https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/21/world/asia/china-revives-mao-era-self-criticism-but-this-kind-bruises-few-egos.html|archive-date=24 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://thediplomat.com/2013/12/the-mass-line-campaign-in-the-21st-century/|title=The Mass Line Campaign in the 21st Century|last1=Tiezzi|first1=Shannon|date=27 December 2013|work=[[The Diplomat]]|accessdate=23 June 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624010506/https://thediplomat.com/2013/12/the-mass-line-campaign-in-the-21st-century/|archive-date=24 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nXi's position has been described as preferring highly centralized political power as a means to direct large-scale economic restructuring.<ref name=\"afp2\" /> Xi believes that China should be \"following its own path\" and that a strong authoritarian government is an integral part of the \"China model\", operating on a \"core socialist value system\", which has been interpreted as China's alternative to Western values. However, Xi and his colleagues acknowledge the challenges to the legitimacy of Communist rule, particularly corruption by party officials. The answer, according to Xi's programme, is two-fold: strengthen the party from within, by streamlining strict party discipline and initiating a large anti-corruption campaign to remove unsavoury elements from within the party, and re-instituting the Mass Line Campaign externally to make party officials better understand and serve the needs of ordinary people. Xi believes that, just as the party must be at the apex of political control of the state, the party's central authorities (i.e., the Politburo, PSC, or himself as general secretary) must exercise full and direct political control of all party activities.<ref name=\"vegs2\">{{cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/08/chinas-political-spectrum-under-xi-jinping/|title=China's Political Spectrum under Xi Jinping|last1=Veg|first1=Sebastien|date=11 August 2014|work=[[The Diplomat]]|access-date=7 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624092950/https://thediplomat.com/2014/08/chinas-political-spectrum-under-xi-jinping/|archive-date=24 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Hong Kong and Taiwan ===\n[[File:2019-10-01 Demonstration Hong Kong 11.jpg|thumb|[[2019 Hong Kong protests|Hong Kong protesters]] throw eggs at Xi Jinping's portrait on [[National Day of the People's Republic of China|National Day]]]]\n\n==== Hong Kong ====\nXi has supported and pursued a greater economic integration of [[Hong Kong]] to mainland China through projects such as the [[Hong Kong\u2013Zhuhai\u2013Macau Bridge]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/fe5976d8-ab81-11e8-94bd-cba20d67390c|title=Greater Bay Area: Xi Jinping's other grand plan|last=Bland|first=Ben|date=2 September 2018|work=[[Financial Times]]|access-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He has pushed for the [[Guangdong-Hong Kong-Macau Greater Bay Area|Greater Bay Area]] project, which aims to integrate Hong Kong, Macau, and nine other cities in [[Guangdong]].<ref name=\":9\" /> Xi's push for greater integration has created fears of decreasing freedoms in Hong Kong.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/05/chinas-xi-jinping-expresses-high-degree-of-trust-in-hong-kongs-carrie-lam|title=China signals desire to bring Hong Kong under tighter control|last=Yu|first=Verna|date=5 November 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nXi has supported the [[Government of Hong Kong|Hong Kong Government]] and incumbent [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong|Chief Executive]] [[Carrie Lam]] against the protesters in the [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hongkong-protests/chinas-xi-vows-support-for-hong-kong-leader-during-most-difficult-time-idUSKBN1YK025|title=China's Xi vows support for Hong Kong leader during 'most difficult' time|last=Sin|first=Noah|date=16 December 2019|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Kwok|first2=Donny}}</ref> He has defended the [[Hong Kong Police Force|Hong Kong police's]] use of force, saying that \"We sternly support the Hong Kong police to take forceful actions in enforcing the law, and the Hong Kong judiciary to punish in accordance with the law those who have committed violent crimes.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/3037811/xi-jinping-again-backs-hong-kong-police-use-force-stopping|title=Xi Jinping again backs Hong Kong police use of force in stopping unrest|last=Zhou|first=Laura|date=14 November 2019|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> While visiting [[Macau]] in 20 December 2019 as part of the 20th anniversary of its return to China, Xi warned of \"foreign forces\" interfering in Hong Kong and Macau,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/en/chinas-xi-warns-of-foreign-forces-at-macao-anniversary/a-51747054|title=China's Xi warns of 'foreign forces' at Macao anniversary|last=|first=|date=20 December 2019|work=[[Deutsche Welle]]|access-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while also hinting that Macau could be a model for Hong Kong to follow.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3042846/macau-handover-anniversary-xi-jinping-tells-residents-make|title=Xi Jinping seen as indirectly lecturing Hong Kong as he tells Macau residents to make 'positive voices' heard and resolve problems with rationality|last=Siu|first=Phila|date=19 December 2019|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=11 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Cheung|first2=Gary}}</ref>\n\n==== Taiwan ====\n[[File:2015 Ma\u2013Xi Meeting 08.jpg|thumb|Xi Jinping met with Taiwanese president [[Ma Ying-jeou]] in November 2015 in their capacity as the leader of mainland China and Taiwan respectively.]]\nThe [[Ma\u2013Xi meeting|2015 meeting]] between Xi and Taiwanese President [[Ma Ying-jeou]] marked the first time the political leaders of both sides of the [[Taiwan Strait]] have met since the end of the [[Chinese Civil War]] in 1950.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/04/world/asia/leaders-of-china-and-taiwan-to-meet-for-first-time-since-1949.html|title=China, Taiwan and a Meeting After 66 Years|last1=Perlez|first1=Jane|date=4 November 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=1 November 2017|last2=Ramzy|first2=Austin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903072421/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/04/world/asia/leaders-of-china-and-taiwan-to-meet-for-first-time-since-1949.html|archive-date=3 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Xi said that China and Taiwan are \"one family\" that can't be pulled apart.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/one-minute-handshake-marks-historic-meeting-between-xi-jinping-and-ma-ying-jeou|title=One-minute handshake marks historic meeting between Xi Jinping and Ma Ying-jeou|last=|first=|date=7 November 2015|work=[[The Straits Times]]|access-date=5 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905182113/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/one-minute-handshake-marks-historic-meeting-between-xi-jinping-and-ma-ying-jeou|archive-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[19th National Congress of the Communist Party of China|19th Party Congress]] held in 2017, Xi reaffirmed six of the nine principles that had been affirmed continuously since the 16th Party Congress in 2002, with the notable exception of \"Placing hopes on the [[People of Taiwan|Taiwan people]] as a force to help bring about [[Chinese unification|unification]]\".<ref name=\"Brookings R.C. Bush2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/order-from-chaos/2017/10/19/what-xi-jinping-said-about-taiwan-at-the-19th-party-congress/|title=What Xi Jinping said about Taiwan at the 19th Party Congress|last=Bush|first=Richard C.|date=19 October 2017|work=[[Brookings Institution]]|access-date=8 July 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708013012/https://www.brookings.edu/blog/order-from-chaos/2017/10/19/what-xi-jinping-said-about-taiwan-at-the-19th-party-congress/|archive-date=8 July 2018}}</ref> According to the [[Brookings Institution]], Xi used stronger language on potential [[Taiwan independence movement|Taiwan independence]] than his predecessors towards previous [[Democratic Progressive Party|DPP]] governments in Taiwan.<ref name=\"Brookings R.C. Bush2\" /> In March 2018, Xi said that Taiwan would face the \"punishment of history\" for any attempts at separatism.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/news/politics/world/xi-jinping-warns-taiwan-it-will-face-punishment-of-history-for-separatism-20180320-h0xpx4|title=Xi Jinping warns Taiwan it will face 'punishment of history' for separatism|last1=Wen|first1=Philip|date=20 March 2018|work=[[The Australian Financial Review]]|access-date=8 July 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708192153/https://www.afr.com/news/politics/world/xi-jinping-warns-taiwan-it-will-face-punishment-of-history-for-separatism-20180320-h0xpx4|archive-date=8 July 2018|last2=Qiu|first2=Stella|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Xi Jinping called on Taiwan to reject its formal independence from China, saying: \"We make no promise to renounce the use of force and reserve the option of taking all necessary means.\" Those options, he said, could be used against \u201cexternal interference\u201d. Xi also said that they \"are willing to create broad space for peaceful reunification, but will leave no room for any form of separatist activities,\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jan/02/all-necessary-means-xi-jinping-reserves-right-to-use-force-against-taiwan|title='All necessary means': Xi Jinping reserves right to use force against Taiwan|last=Kuo|first=Lily|date=2 January 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=7 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822114526/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jan/02/all-necessary-means-xi-jinping-reserves-right-to-use-force-against-taiwan|archive-date=22 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/01/02/asia/xi-jinping-taiwan-tsai-intl/|title=Xi warns Taiwan independence is 'a dead end'|last=Griffiths|first=James|date=2 January 2019|newspaper=[[CNN]]|access-date=7 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003215248/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/01/02/asia/xi-jinping-taiwan-tsai-intl/|archive-date=3 October 2019}}</ref> [[Tsai Ing-Wen]] responded to the speech by saying Taiwan would not accept a [[one country, two systems]] arrangement with the mainland, while stressing for the need of all cross-strait negotiations to be on a government-to-government basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-taiwan-president/taiwan-president-defiant-after-china-calls-for-reunification-idUSKCN1OW0FN|title=Taiwan president defiant after China calls for reunification|last=Lee|first=Yimou|date=2 January 2019|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=7 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929044514/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-taiwan-president/taiwan-president-defiant-after-china-calls-for-reunification-idUSKCN1OW0FN|archive-date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n=== Family ===\n[[File:Peng Liyuan, Xi Jinping and Barack Obama in the Lincoln Bedroom.jpg|thumb|Xi Jinping, [[Peng Liyuan]] and U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] in the Lincoln Bedroom]]Xi married Ke Lingling, the daughter of [[Ke Hua]], China's ambassador to the United Kingdom in the early 1980s. They divorced within a few years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/11/07/world/asia/china-xi-jinping-profile/index.html|title=Xi Jinping: From 'sent-down youth' to China's top|last=Yuan|first=Elizabeth|date=8 November 2012|newspaper=[[CNN]]|accessdate=8 November 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108195546/http://edition.cnn.com/2012/11/07/world/asia/china-xi-jinping-profile/index.html|archive-date=8 November 2012}}</ref> The two were said to fight \"almost every day\", and after the divorce Ke moved to England.<ref name=\"newyorker2\" />\n\nXi married the prominent Chinese folk singer [[Peng Liyuan]] in 1987.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/oct/23/world/fg-chileaders23|title=China's 'fifth generation' of leaders reflects nation's shifts|last=Magnier|first=Mark|date=23 October 2007|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=21 December 2009|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823133224/http://articles.latimes.com/2007/oct/23/world/fg-chileaders23|archive-date=23 August 2011}}</ref> Xi and Peng were introduced by friends as many Chinese couples were in the 1980s. Xi was reputedly academic during their courtship, inquiring about singing techniques.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/chinarealtime/2012/02/13/peng-liyuan-meet-chinas-folk-song-singing-first-lady-in-waiting/|title=Meet China's Folk Star First Lady-in-Waiting|last=Page|first=Jeremy|date=12 February 2012|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=7 November 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511045002/http://blogs.wsj.com/chinarealtime/2012/02/13/peng-liyuan-meet-chinas-folk-song-singing-first-lady-in-waiting/|archive-date=11 May 2012}}</ref> Peng Liyuan, a [[Celebrity|household name]] in China, was better known to the public than Xi until his political elevation. The couple frequently lived apart due largely to their separate professional lives. Peng has played a much more visible role as China's \"first lady\" compared to her predecessors; for example, Peng hosted U.S. First Lady [[Michelle Obama]] on her high-profile visit to China in March 2014.<ref name=\"beech2\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/33164/michelle-obama-china-beijing-peng-liyuan/|title=Michelle Obama Tours Beijing With China's First Lady|last1=Beech|first1=Hannah|date=21 March 2014|newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=17 July 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626122108/http://time.com/33164/michelle-obama-china-beijing-peng-liyuan/|archive-date=26 June 2014}}</ref> Xi and Peng have a daughter named [[Xi Mingze]], who graduated from [[Harvard University]] in the spring of 2015. While at Harvard, she used a pseudonym and studied Psychology and English.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/what-did-chinas-first-daughter-find-in-america|title=What Did China's First Daughter Find in America?|last=Osnos|first=Evan|date=6 April 2015|work=[[The New Yorker]]|access-date=29 October 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030035420/https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/what-did-chinas-first-daughter-find-in-america|archive-date=30 October 2018}}</ref> Xi's family has a home in [[Jade Spring Hill]], a garden and residential area in north-western Beijing run by the [[Central Military Commission of the Communist Party of China|Central Military Commission]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/hundreds-02202015111702.html|title=Beijing Police Detain Hundreds For Trying to Visit Chinese Leaders Over New Year|last=Qiao|first=Long|date=20 February 2015|newspaper=[[Radio Free Asia]]|accessdate=1 March 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164338/https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/hundreds-02202015111702.html|archive-date=1 March 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, ''[[Bloomberg News]]'' reported that members of Xi's extended family have substantial business interests, although there was no evidence he had intervened to assist them.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-29/xi-jinping-millionaire-relations-reveal-fortunes-of-elite.html|title=Xi Jinping Millionaire Relations Reveal Fortunes of Elite|last=Bennett|first=Amanda|date=29 June 2012|work=[[Bloomberg News]]|access-date=11 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120704222305/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-29/xi-jinping-millionaire-relations-reveal-fortunes-of-elite.html|archive-date=4 July 2012|last2=Hirschberg|first2=Peter}}</ref> The ''Bloomberg'' website was blocked in [[mainland China]] in response to the article.<ref name=\"guardian296122\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jun/29/china-bloomberg-xi-jinping|title=China blocks Bloomberg for exposing financial affairs of Xi Jinping's family|last=Branigan|first=Tania|date=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=11 September 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131120041457/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jun/29/china-bloomberg-xi-jinping|archive-date=20 November 2013|location=}}</ref> Since Xi embarked on an anti-corruption campaign, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported members of his family were selling their corporate and real estate investments beginning in 2012.<ref name=\"nytimes3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/18/world/asia/chinas-president-xi-jinping-investments.html|title=As China's Leader Fights Graft, His Relatives Shed Assets|last1=Forsythe|first1=Michael|date=17 June 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=16 July 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716105611/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/18/world/asia/chinas-president-xi-jinping-investments.html|archive-date=16 July 2014|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nRelatives of highly placed Chinese officials, including seven current and former senior leaders of the Politburo of the Communist Party of China, have been named in the [[Panama Papers]], including [[Deng Jiagui]],<ref>\n{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/04/04/the-panama-papers-are-super-awkward-for-beijing/|title=The Panama Papers are super awkward for Beijing|last1=Rauhala|first1=Emily|date=4 April 2016|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=7 September 2019|url-status=live|url-access=limited|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421044242/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/04/04/the-panama-papers-are-super-awkward-for-beijing/|archive-date=21 April 2016}}</ref> Xi's brother-in-law. Deng had two [[Shell corporation|shell companies]] in the [[British Virgin Islands]] while Xi was a member of the Politburo Standing Committee, but they were dormant by the time Xi became general secretary of the Communist Party in November 2012.<ref name=\"MP2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.marketplace.org/2016/04/04/world/xi-jinpings-family-linked-panama-papers|title=Xi Jinping's family linked to Panama Papers|last=Schmitz|first=Rob|date=4 April 2016|newspaper=[[Marketplace (radio program)|Marketplace]]|accessdate=6 April 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407224017/http://www.marketplace.org/2016/04/04/world/xi-jinpings-family-linked-panama-papers|archive-date=7 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Personality ===\nPeng described Xi as hardworking and down-to-earth: \"When he comes home, I've never felt as if there's some leader in the house. In my eyes, he's just my husband.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/in_depth/china_politics/leadership/html/6.stm|title=China's Leaders|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=26 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130808233513/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/in_depth/china_politics/leadership/html/6.stm|archive-date=8 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Xi was described in a 2011 ''The Washington Post'' article by those who know him as \"pragmatic, serious, cautious, hard-working, down to earth and low-key\". He was described as a good hand at problem solving and \"seemingly uninterested in the trappings of high office\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/xi-jinping-likely-chinas-next-leader-called-pragmatic-low-key/2011/08/15/gIQA5W83GJ_story.html|title=Xi Jinping, likely China's next leader, called pragmatic, low-key|last=Richburg|first=Keith B.|date=15 August 2011|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=7 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029173940/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/xi-jinping-likely-chinas-next-leader-called-pragmatic-low-key/2011/08/15/gIQA5W83GJ_story.html|archive-date=29 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He is known to love U.S. films such as ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]'', ''[[The Departed]]'' and ''[[The Godfather]]''.<ref>Buckley, Chris, [https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/02/08/us-china-usa-xi-idUSTRE8170FZ20120208 \"China leader-in-waiting carries heavy political baggage to U.S.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930175418/https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/02/08/us-china-usa-xi-idUSTRE8170FZ20120208|date=30 September 2015}}, [[Reuters]], 8 February 2012. Retrieved 14 February 2012.</ref><ref>Buckley, Chris, [http://sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/11/15/xi-in-godfather-mold-looks-assertive-and-even-imperial \"Xi, in 'Godfather' Mold, Looks Assertive and Even Imperial\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328221642/http://sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/11/15/xi-in-godfather-mold-looks-assertive-and-even-imperial|date=28 March 2015}} ''[[The New York Times]]'', 15 November 2013. Retrieved 14 May 2012.</ref> He is also a fan of HBO television series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', watching a condensed version due to tight schedules.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/3007991/xi-jinping-shows-his-love-game-thrones-warns-reality-must-not|title=Xi Jinping shows his love of Game of Thrones but warns reality must not mirror fantasy|date=28 April 2019|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=5 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505041030/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/3007991/xi-jinping-shows-his-love-game-thrones-warns-reality-must-not|archive-date=5 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He also praised the independent film-maker [[Jia Zhangke]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/feb/13/xi-jinping-profile-china |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |title=The Guardian profile: Xi Jinping |last=Branigan |first=Tania |date=13 February 2012 |location=UK |access-date=14 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106055944/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/feb/13/xi-jinping-profile-china |archive-date=6 November 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> He also likes playing soccer, mountain climbing, walking, volleyball and swimming. He once said that he would swim one kilometre and walk every day as long as there was time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-politics-xi-idUSKBN1DH0GA|title=Glowing profile cracks door open on private life of China's Xi|last=Blachard|first=Ben|date=2017-11-17|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=2019-12-09|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.people.cn/n3/2017/0405/c90000-9198935.html|title=Chinese President Xi Jinping in Cartoons|last=Wu|first=Chenliang|date=5 April 2017|newspaper=[[People's Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Public image===\nXi Jinping is widely popular in China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/14/xi-jinping-crushes-dissent-but-making-china-great-again|title=Chairman Xi crushes dissent but poor believe he's making China great|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=14 October 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=26 August 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826122356/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/14/xi-jinping-crushes-dissent-but-making-china-great-again|archive-date=26 August 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-03-06/the-astonishing-rise-of-chinese-president-xi-jinping/10794486|title='No room for mercy in this system': Xi Jinping's rise from cave dweller to post-modern chairman|last=Zhou|first=Christina|last2=Mantesso|first2=Sean|date=6 March 2019|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|language=en-AU|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826051002/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-03-06/the-astonishing-rise-of-chinese-president-xi-jinping/10794486|archive-date=26 August 2019|url-status=live|access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> According to a 2014 poll co-sponsored by the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Harvard Kennedy School's]] [[Ash Center for Democratic Governance and Innovation]], Xi ranked 9 out of 10 in domestic approval ratings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thediplomat.com/2014/12/the-worlds-most-popular-leader-chinas-president-xi/|title=The World's Most Popular Leader: China's President Xi|last=Tiezzi|first=Shannon|date=20 December 2014|newspaper=[[The Diplomat]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191027062238/https://thediplomat.com/2014/12/the-worlds-most-popular-leader-chinas-president-xi/|archive-date=27 October 2019|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref> A [[YouGov]] poll released in July 2019 found that 22% of Chinese people list Xi as the person they admire the most.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://today.yougov.com/topics/international/articles-reports/2019/07/18/2019-worlds-most-admired|title=Michelle Obama is the world's most admired woman|last=Smith|first=Matthew|date=18 July 2019|website=[[YouGov]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729151150/https://today.yougov.com/topics/international/articles-reports/2019/07/18/2019-worlds-most-admired|archive-date=29 July 2019|access-date=17 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, ''[[The Economist]]'' named him the most powerful person in the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/2017/10/14/xi-jinping-has-more-clout-than-donald-trump-the-world-should-be-wary|title=Xi Jinping has more clout than Donald Trump. The world should be wary|last=|first=|date=14 October 2017|work=[[The Economist]]|access-date=11 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918133802/https://www.economist.com/leaders/2017/10/14/xi-jinping-has-more-clout-than-donald-trump-the-world-should-be-wary|archive-date=18 September 2019|issn=0013-0613|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 2018, ''[[Forbes]]'' ranked him as [[Forbes list of The World's Most Powerful People|the most powerful and influential person in the world]], replacing [[President of Russia|Russian President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] who had been so ranked for five consecutive years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidewalt/2018/05/08/the-worlds-most-powerful-people-2018/#7e7884216c47|title=The World's Most Powerful People 2018|last1=Ewalt|first1=David M.|date=31 May 2018|work=[[Forbes]]|access-date=7 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509222602/https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidewalt/2018/05/08/the-worlds-most-powerful-people-2018/#7e7884216c47|archive-date=9 May 2018|author-link=David McWalter}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n\n; Foreign Honours\n* {{IOC}}: [[Olympic Order|The Golden Olympic order]] (19 November 2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinaconsulatesf.org/eng/zgxw/t1101193.htm|title=Xi Jinping Meets with International Olympic Committee President Thomas Bach and Receives the Olympic Order in Gold|last=|first=|date=23 November 2013|website=Consulate-General of the People's Republic of China in San Francisco|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091315/http://www.chinaconsulatesf.org/eng/zgxw/t1101193.htm|archive-date=4 March 2016|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[File:Grand Crest Ordre de Leopold.png|85x85px]] {{flagu|Belgium}}: [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Grand Cordon of the Order of Leopold]] (30 March 2014)<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/3d516a4d3541544d/share_p.html|title=How many honors has President Xi Jinping received?|last=Wang|first=Mingyang|date=22 November 2016|newspaper=[[CGTN]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905185246/https://news.cgtn.com/news/3d516a4d3541544d/share_p.html|archive-date=5 September 2019|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[File:VEN Order of the Liberator - Grand Cordon BAR.png|85x85px]] {{flagu|Venezuela}}: [[Order of the Liberator|Grand Cordon of the Order of the Liberator]] (20 July 2014)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[File:Ribbon jose marti.png|85x85px]] {{flagu|Cuba}}: [[Order of Jos\u00e9 Mart\u00ed]] (22 July 2014)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[File:Order of Pakistan.png|85x85px]] {{flagu|Pakistan}}: [[Nishan-e-Pakistan]] (21 April 2015)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[File:Spange des K\u00f6nig-Abdulaziz-Ordens.png|85x85px]] {{flagu|Saudi Arabia}}: [[Order of Abdulaziz al Saud]] (19 January 2016)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[File:Orden Republike Srbije.gif|85x85px]] {{flagu|Serbia}}: [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Serbia|Order of the Republic of Serbia of the first order]] (18 June 2016)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics.php?yyyy=2016&mm=06&dd=18&nav_id=98363|title=Chinese president receives Order of Republic of Serbia|last=|first=|date=18 June 2016|newspaper=[[B92]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616192355/https://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics.php?yyyy=2016&mm=06&dd=18&nav_id=98363|archive-date=16 June 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n* {{flagu|Belarus}}: [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Belarus|Order for Promotion of Peace and Friendship]] (29 September 2016)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://eng.belta.by/president/view/lukashenko-awards-order-for-strengthening-peace-and-friendship-to-xi-jinping-94925-2016/|title=Lukashenko awards Order for Strengthening Peace and Friendship to Xi Jinping|last=|first=|date=9 September 2016|newspaper=[[Belarusian Telegraph Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612193511/http://eng.belta.by/president/view/lukashenko-awards-order-for-strengthening-peace-and-friendship-to-xi-jinping-94925-2016/|archive-date=12 June 2018|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n*[[File:Medalla de Honor del Congreso (Peru) - ribbon bar.png|frameless|85x85px]] {{flagu|Peru}}: Medal of Honor  (21 November 2016)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[File:Grand Collar of the Order of the State of Palestine ribbon.svg|85x85px]] {{flagu|Palestine}}: [[Grand Collar of the State of Palestine]] (18 July 2017)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/pm-modi-conferred-grand-