rto Rico Census Office|url=https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog|year=1900|publisher=Imprenta del gobierno|page=[https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog/page/n255 164]| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico}}\n* [[List of communities in Puerto Rico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|18.2300319|-66.997901900000002|display=title|format=dms}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{gnis|2415639}}\n\n[[Category:Barrios of Las Mar\u00edas, Puerto Rico]]\n\n\n{{PuertoRico-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "The Eloquent Peasant", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:unlink self", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maravilla_Sur"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Hastie (politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Andrew Hastie\n| honorific-suffix = [[Australian House of Representatives|MP]]\n| image            = Andrew Hastie Orignal.jpg\n| caption          = Hastie in 2018\n| constituency_MP  = [[Division of Canning|Canning]]\n| parliament       = Australian\n| majority         = \n| predecessor      = [[Don Randall]]\n| successor        = \n| term_start       = 19 September 2015\n| term_end         = \n| office1          = Chair of the [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]]\n| deputy1          = [[Anthony Byrne (politician)|Anthony Byrne]]\n| term_start1      = 15 February 2017\n| term_end1        = \n| predecessor1     = [[Michael Sukkar]]\n| successor1       = \n| birthname        = Andrew William Hastie\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1982|9|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[Wangaratta, Victoria]], Australia\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| nationality      = \n| spouse           = Ruth Hastie\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Australia]]\n| relations        = \n| children         = 2\n| residence        = [[Mandurah, Western Australia]]\n| alma_mater       = [[University of New South Wales|UNSW]], [[Australian Defence Force Academy|ADFA]], [[Royal Military College, Duntroon|Duntroon]], [[George Washington University|GWU]]\n| occupation       = \n| profession       = [[Member of Parliament]] (MP)\n| signature        = \n| website          = {{url|www.andrewhastie.com.au}}\n| footnotes        = \n| allegiance       = Australia\n| branch           = [[Australian Army]]\n| serviceyears     = 2001\u20132015\n| rank             = [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]]\n| unit             = [[2nd Cavalry Regiment (Australia)|2nd Cavalry Regiment]] (2007\u20132009)<br />[[Special Air Service Regiment]] (2010\u20132015)\n| battles          = [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br/>[[Military intervention against ISIL]]\n}}\n\n'''Andrew William Hastie''' (born 30 September 1982) is an Australian politician who serves as Chair of the [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]] and as the Federal MP for [[Division of Canning|Canning]], [[Western Australia|WA]] in the [[Australian House of Representatives]]. He was first elected in the [[2015 Canning by-election]] and re-elected in 2016 and 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Andrew Hastie MP|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=260805|website=www.aph.gov.au|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> A controversial figure, his public statements for Australia to \"preserve our sovereignty\"<ref name=\"Hastie\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=7 August 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> in defiance of an \"expansionist\"<ref name=\"Grattan\">{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/politics-with-michelle-grattan-andrew-hastie-on-foreign-influence-security-and-veteran-mental-health-128545|title=Politics with Michelle Grattan: Andrew Hastie on foreign influence, security and veteran mental health|last=Grattan|first=Michelle|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> [[Communist Party of China]] have been condemned as \"totally intemperate\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ferguson|first=Richard|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/kerry-stokes-says-andrew-hastie-did-more-harm-than-good-with-china-remarks/news-story/bc218d8b7cbffd3f1cc3ec6cb6db8ee8|title=Kerry Stokes says Andrew Hastie did more harm than good with China remarks|date=9 February 2020|work=The Australian|access-date=9 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"inflammatory\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watoday.com.au/politics/western-australia/wa-premier-slams-andrew-hastie-s-china-concerns-as-extreme-and-inflammatory-20190808-p52f7m.html|title=WA Premier slams Andrew Hastie's China concerns as 'extreme and inflammatory'|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=8 August 2019|website=WAtoday|language=en|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref> by Australian corporate leaders, then praised as a matter of \"strong public interest\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/radio/programs/pm/strong-public-interest-in-chinese-influence-claims/9792976|title=\"Strong public interest\" in Chinese influence claims|date=23 May 2018|website=ABC Radio|language=en-AU|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> and \"necessary, and important\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/news/politics/2019/08/17/how-the-china-question-split-australian-politics/15659640008614|title=How the China question split Australian politics|last=Seccombe|first=Mike|date=17 August 2019|website=The Saturday Paper|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> by security analysts [[Clive Hamilton|Professor Clive Hamilton]] and Professor Rory Medcalf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/in-defence-of-andrew-hastie-20190811-p52fyw|title=In defence of Andrew Hastie|date=11 August 2019|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> His stance led to the [[Government of China]] refusing him and his colleague [[James Paterson (Australian politician)|James Paterson]] from visiting China on a study tour, demanding that they \"repent\" from their views.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/outspoken-liberal-politicians-must-repent-and-redress-says-china|title='Outspoken' Liberal politicians must 'repent and redress', says China|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and family==\nHastie's mother Sue was a primary school teacher, particularly to children with special needs. [[File:Andrew Hastie with his father Peter Hastie back yard Wangaratta Victoria circa 1983.jpg|alt=Andrew Hastie, age 1, with his father Peter, around 1983|thumb|Andrew Hastie with his father Peter, in the backyard of their home in Wangaratta, Victoria, circa 1983]] Her mother Rose \u2014 to whom, Hastie says in his first speech, he was \"very close\"<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b1239e0c-7fca-43e4-aac5-25ac64e2bc96/0128%22|title=First Speech|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=13 October 2015|website=Australian Parliament House|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref>\u2014 was a nurse throughout her life, caring for Hastie's grandfather, Reginald a war veteran, through to his death.\n\nSimilarly, his paternal grandfather served as an officer with the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] and was severely wounded by gunfire when covering the air-sea rescue of two downed Australian airmen during the [[Pacific War]] for which he was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]].<ref name=\":8\" /> His son (Hastie's father) Peter has served as a pastor in church communities, early on in rural [[Wangaratta]], Victoria; and later in the inner urban suburb of [[Ashfield, New South Wales|Ashfield]], where he launched a Mandarin speaking congregation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-s-awakening-to-xi-s-bid-for-total-control-of-china-and-beyond-20190809-p52for.html|title=Hastie's awakening to Xi's bid for total control of China - and beyond|last=Hartcher|first=Peter|date=9 August 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nWhen the family moved to the inner west of Sydney, Hastie began his primary education at Ashbury Public School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=A Tale of Two Andrews|last=|first=|date=4 May 2019|website=Unforgiving 60|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> From year 5 he attended [[The Scots College]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=Summer 2015|title=Old Boy News|url=https://www.tsc.nsw.edu.au/hubfs/Lion_and_Lang_Syne_Summer_2015.pdf|journal=The Lion & Lang Syne|volume=26|pages=49|via=}}</ref> in [[Sydney]], completing his [[Higher School Certificate (New South Wales)|Higher School Certificate]] in 2000. Intending to become a journalist, Hastie began a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in History, Politics and Philosophy at the Kensington Campus of [[University of New South Wales]] in 2001, and also joined the [[University of New South Wales Regiment]] as a part-time reservist. At a tutorial near the end of first year, following [[September 11 attacks|11 September terror attacks]] Hastie says he listened to other students argue that the [[United States]] had \u201cdeserved\u201d the attack, which he says he found \u201cbizarre\",<ref name=\"thewest.com.au\">{{Cite web|url=https://thewest.com.au/news/australia/war-has-its-limits-hastie-tells-mps-ng-ya-130555|title=War has its limits, new MP Andrew Hastie tells Parliament|date=14 October 2015|website=The West Australian|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> the event would \"shape the next decade of my life.\"<ref name=\"Hastie\"/><blockquote>I was planning on being a foreign correspondent. 9/11 happened and the daughter of my year 2/3 teacher at Ashbury Public School, she died in one of the towers, I think she was 90 floors up. And so that event, apart from the obvious impact it had on Australia, it came very close to me and my life and I had a tradition of service in my family and thought, you know what, this is a big, historical shift, I want to be part of this.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=unforgiving60|website=unforgiving60|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Hastie with book.jpg|thumb|Lieutenant Andrew Hastie at the rear of his ASLAV Type 1, holding a copy of ''Empire'' by Scottish historian [[Niall Ferguson]].]]\nHastie decided to join the [[Australian Army]] full-time, but completed his second year at the Kensington Campus in 2002 before transferring to the [[University of New South Wales]] at [[Australian Defence Force Academy]] in Canberra in 2003. He completed his bachelor's degree in 2004 before being invited to do an honours year in 2005, his final thesis examined [[Charles Bean]]'s official history of the [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps]]. Hastie still regards himself as a student of history<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yourlocalexaminer.com.au/andrew-hastie-maiden-speech/|title=Hastie sworn in, vows to put Canning people first|last=Hastie|first=Hamish|date=14 October 2015|website=Your Local Examiner|language=en-US|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> and recently wrote the forward to ''Destined for War''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.scribd.com/book/350699416/Destined-for-War-can-America-and-China-escape-Thucydides-Trap|title=Destined for War by Graham Allison and Andrew Hastie - Book - Read Online|language=en}}</ref> an historical survey of global conflicts, beginning with the [[Peloponnesian War]] by [[Graham T. Allison]].\n\nHastie went on to officer training at [[Royal Military College, Duntroon]] in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=260805|title=Mr Andrew Hastie MP|website=www.aph.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> In 2007, Hastie completed the [[George Washington University]] [[Elliott School of International Affairs]]'s U.S. Foreign Policy Summer Program in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\n==Military service (2001\u20132015)==\nWhile at University, Hastie had planned on a part time career in the military, and began officer training with the [[Australian Army Reserve]] in 2001 through the University of New South Wales Regiment.<ref>{{cite web|title=September 11 Australian Stories|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426162732/http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2011/09/08/september-11-australian-stories|website=www.sbs.com.au|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> However, the events of [[9/11]] near the end of that year propelled him towards full-time army service, which he began as a Cadet in 2003. His officer training was completed at Duntroon in 2006, and he was presented with his Commission as Lieutenant from Governor General [[Michael Jeffery]] in December of that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://old.gg.gov.au/program/tuesday-12-december-2006-royal-military-college-australia-duntroon-canberra-their-ex|title=On Tuesday 12 December 2006 at the Royal Military College of Australia, Duntroon, Canberra, Their Ex...|last=Anonymous|date=27 March 2012|website=old.gg.gov.au|language=en|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> His first posting as a young officer was in 2007 with [[2nd Armoured Division (Australia)|2nd Cavalry Regiment]], the second most senior regiment in the [[Royal Australian Armoured Corps]], which he describes as \"the last of the old army.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=The Unforgiving 60 (2019) 3 May 2019, \u201cA Tale of Two Andrews\u201d Season 1, Episode 15a.|last=|first=|date=3 May 2019|website=The Unforgiving 60 (2019)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> At this time the regiment was based with 1st Brigade<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.defence.gov.au/media/media-releases/2nd-cavalry-regiment-arrives-townsville|title=2nd Cavalry Regiment arrives in Townsville|last=Defence|first=Department of|date=9 November 2016|website=news.defence.gov.au|language=en|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> in [[Palmerston, Northern Territory]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army.gov.au/our-people/units/forces-command/1st-brigade/2nd-cavalry-regiment|title=2nd Cavalry Regiment|website=www.army.gov.au|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>. Hastie took command of a cavalry troop in 2008, preparing for deployment in Afghanistan the following year. \n\n=== Afghanistan, 2009-2010 ===\n[[File:Charmestan valley afghanistan.jpg|thumb|MRTF-2 Commanding Officer's Tactical Party, on the edge of the Charmestan, Mirabad Valley, Urozgan Province, Afghanistan.]]\n[[File:Hastie overlooking Chora Valley.jpg|thumb|Andrew Hastie overlooking Chora from his Type I ASLAV.]]\n[[File:Bushmaster Counter IED Lane Tarin Kowt.JPG|thumb|[[Bushmaster Protected Mobility Vehicle]] damaged by [[Improvised explosive device]] attack in [[Tarinkot District|Tarinkot]] in December 2009. Its V-shaped undercarriage design and armour meant that no Australian soldier was wounded.]]\n\nHastie first deployed to Afghanistan with [[Mentoring Task Force One|Mentoring Task Force Two]], a 750-strong Australian combined arms battle group, all under the command of Colonel Peter Connolly. Hastie's role was to commanded a troop of [[ASLAV|Australian Light Armoured Vehicle]]s as it helped to provide \"cover when the Diggers go out on patrol\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/afghanistans-treeless-fields-provide-nowhere-to-hide-20110220-1b14u.html|title=Afghanistan's treeless fields provide nowhere to hide|last=Oakes|first=Dan|date=20 February 2011|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> by using \u201cclose combat to destroy the enemy with precision.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Connolly|first=Peter|title=Counterinsurgency in Uruzgan 2009|publisher=Land Warfare Studies Centre|year=2011|isbn=|location=Canberra|pages=}}</ref> The troop's armoured operations began at the very start of the fighting season in May 2009, concluding in February 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nautilus.org/publications/books/australian-forces-abroad/afghanistan/mentoring-task-force/|title=Mentoring Task Force|date=2011-12-19|website=Nautilus Institute for Security and Sustainability|language=en-US|accessdate=2019-12-18}}</ref> In an extensive report on the mission, known as Operation Falcon's Talon, Hastie's commander, Colonel Peter Connolly said the goal of the Australian forces was \"...to clear and dominate the valley.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Australian forces, including Hastie's, pushed east out of [[Tarinkot District]], up the Mirabad Valley from Charmestan to [[Khas Urozgan District|Khas Urozgan]], all in order to extend the influence of the government of [[Hamid Karzai]], who was seeking re-election in November of that year. The patrols were dangerous and at least four [[List of Australian Defence Force casualties in Afghanistan|Australian soldiers were killed in Afghanistan]] at this time, mostly from attacks by [[improvised explosive device]]s.  Hastie reported \"we had four strikes in my troop alone\u201d though no deaths or wounding, thanks to effective armour.<ref name=\"Development\">{{Cite web|url=https://unforgiving60.podbean.com/e/a-tale-of-two-andrews-%e2%80%93-two-federal-politicians-but-no-politics-andrew-hastie-mp-and-andrew-leigh-mp/|title=S1E15a- A Tale of Two Andrews \u2013 Two Federal Politicians / But No Politics! Andrew Hastie (MP) and Andrew Leigh (MP)|last=Development|first=PodBean|website=unforgiving60.podbean.com|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> Despite the attacks, the series of patrol bases were established through the valley system in [[Urozgan Province]] by December of that year, and the wider operation was considered, in official reports \u2014 at least at this point \u2014 to be a success.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.army.gov.au/Our-future/Publications/Australian-Army-Journal/Past-editions/~/media/Files/Our%20future/LWSC%20Publications/AAJ/2011Winter/02-CounterinsurgencyInUruz.pdf|title=Counterinsurgency in Uruzgan 2009|date=1 July 2010|publisher=The Australian Army|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923174042/http://www.army.gov.au/Our-future/Publications/Australian-Army-Journal/Past-editions/~/media/Files/Our%20future/LWSC%20Publications/AAJ/2011Winter/02-CounterinsurgencyInUruz.pdf|archivedate=23 September 2015|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref> Hastie himself understood the role he and his men performed was part of a wider attempt to reshape Afghanistan:<blockquote>Our job pretty much was the stick. The carrot was the mentoring piece, the aid that was delivered through DFAT, also there at the time and other NGOs. And we were the stick that kept the bad guys back.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|date=December 9, 2016|work=Herald Sun|access-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>\n=== Special Air Service Regiment, 2010-2012 ===\n[[File:Insigne du Special Air Service Regiment (SASR).svg|thumb|Insignia of the Special Air Service Regiment (SASR)]]Hastie successfully applied for entry to the [[Special Air Service Regiment]]\u00a0Selection Course (known simply as \"Selection\"). The process is designed to identify soldiers with diverse backgrounds and strong character as they are able to \u201cgenerate unconventional answers to strategic and tactical problems\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cios.org/EJCPUBLIC/010/1/01013.html|title=Article from ejc/rec|website=www.cios.org|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> as needed for a Tier 1 [[Special forces]] unit. His cohort featured in the SBS documentary ''The Search for Warriors''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/video/11757123841/SAS-The-Search-For-Warriors-S1-Ep1|title=SAS - The Search For Warriors S1 Ep1|website=SBS PopAsia|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> where Hastie has been identified as candidate 10. With the other candidates, Hastie was subjected to extreme exercises, a deliberate system in which, according to the Lieutenant Colonel who had oversight of Hastie's Selection, \u201cwe will break an individual down.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blackfootstudios.com/forums/index.php?/forums/topic/5012-australian-sas-selection-documentary/|title=Australian SAS Selection Documentary|website=BlackFoot Studios|language=en-US|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> Exercises included \u201cLucky Dip\u201d, five days working with teams to move heavy equipment by hand through the bush, with only one meal in that time; and a 150&nbsp;km five-day solo trek across mountainous terrain, which Hastie recalled in interview:<blockquote>\u201cI remember on Selection being up on one of the mountains in the Stirling ranges, being asked, \u201cWhy do you want to be here?\u201d I said, \u201cBecause last time I was in Afghanistan I was driving around getting blown up and I actually want to go after these guys.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=A Tale of Two Andrews|last=|first=|date=3 May 2019|website=Unforgiving 60|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> </blockquote>Hastie's Selection experience concluded with a three-day extreme interrogation session, involving constant sleep deprivation and starvation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/documentary-reveals-gruelling-sas-selection-process/news-story/4488a528d9e0bffd2bc98c43cc2a9350|title=SAS: We will break an individual down|date=6 December 2010|website=NewsComAu|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref>  Men in the group lost between 10 and 15 kilograms from exertion and malnutrition. From Hastie's initial cohort of 131, only 26 completed the course.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/national/2015/08/21/can-pass-sas-test/|title=The most gruelling tests of the SAS|date=21 August 2015|website=The New Daily|language=en-US|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> From there Hastie commenced the 18-month Reinforcement Cycle before receiving qualification with the Regiment, based at [[Campbell Barracks]]. He was issued his \u201csandy beret\u201d in May 2012 and was assigned to 1 SAS Squadron. His first overseas deployment was in Port Moresby to support the [[Papua New Guinea Defence Force]] as they provide security and stability for the General Election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/pm/content/2012/s3523650.htm|title=Australia provides help for PNG elections|date=12 June 2012|website=www.abc.net.au|language=en-AU|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Commanding special forces troop in Afghanistan, 2013  ===\n[[File:Australia\u2019s Special Operations Task Group mentors Provincial Response Company \u2013 Uruzgan 130427-A-FS372-213.jpg|thumb|Australia's Special Operations Task Group was partnered with the local Provincial Police Ready Reaction Auxiliary Force which involved training, support and some joint operations.]]\n\nIn January 2013, Hastie returned to Afghanistan as an SASR officer with Special Operations Task Group Rotation XIX. Hastie told journalist [[Chris Masters (writer)|Chris Masters]] his role was now, \"to protect the base and take the fight to the enemy.\" More widely, the mission was to provide force protection as the ADF mentored the nascent [[Afghan National Security Force]]. Hastie led his troop in operations against hostile [[Taliban]] leadership in southern Afghanistan, commanding B Troop:<blockquote>This meant targeting and taking out the Taliban leadership, helping to support the building of institutions such as schools, and trying to carve out some space for the new Afghan Government to govern.<ref name=\"Whinnett\">{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|date=December 9, 2016|work=Herald Sun|access-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>As part of Task Force 66 (Special Operations Task Groups IV-XX) Hastie's unit was awarded a [[Meritorious Unit Citation]] for \"outstanding service on operations against an unrelenting, cunning and ruthless enemy, in an unforgiving environment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/australia-day-honours-list-2015|title=Australia Day honours list 2015|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref>Little is known about Hastie's actual missions, as special forces exist to deliver \"clandestine, discreet, strategic effects.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/defence/sas-fighting-funds-to-be-increased-by-billions/news-story/b1e1e487970259d213c7c90075ef96e2|title=SAS fighting funds to be increased by billions|last=Packham|first=Ben|date=12 August 2019|website=The Australian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> However, as research by Chris Masters, [[Nick McKenzie]] and [[Ellen Whinnett]] has emerged, we know of five events, which show both the effectiveness of his unit, and the serious limitations of what he later called \"democracy at gunpoint.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|last=Whinnet|first=Whinnett|date=9 December 2016|website=Herald Sun|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==== 1. Joint operation with Wakunish ====\nLargely, SASR operations were about \"going after Taliban commanders and bomb makers\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/95142-big-boys-rules/|title=Big boys\u2019 rules|date=2 July 2018|website=The Mandarin|language=en-US|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>in partnership with local Afghan forces. \"Objective Multiple Spoons\"<ref name=\":3\" /> was the improbable name given to a high value leader who was on the \"Joint Prioritized Effects List.\" The enemy commander was tracked by Hastie's colleagues using an \"array of reconnaissance elements and intelligence platforms\"<ref name=\":3\" /> and was located to an exact position using thermal imaging systems. One SASR operator recalled \"We watched the heat dissipate from his shit in the cold of night.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> Hastie's men deployed to make the capture by Bushmasters, along with a Wakunish force element. These were special-forces-like soldiers from the North of Afghanistan, whom Hastie held in high regard. \"The Wakunish were disciplined. They were tactically proficient. They were sensitive to the populace...\" They encircled the target and attacked at first light, as per their rules of engagement for this context. The entire mission was observed by the commander of all Special Operations Forces for [[International Security Assistance Force]], Brigadeer Bill Dechow, who \"watched on as the Wakunish made entry and captured the senior objective without bloodshed.\" Hastie regarded it as exemplary of the kind of work special forces could achieve, \"surgical and sensitive to locals. We even returned the objective's motorbike to the family.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== 2. Deaths of Toor Jan and Odood ====\n\nIn February 2013, Hastie led a squad of men to support a remote outpost of [[Afghan National Police]] in the [[Deh Rahwod District]]<ref name=\":2\" /> planning to \"supply them with some water, some Red Bull\" and build trust with the local commander.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\" /> While there, the Electronic Warfare Operator received communication intercepts indicating two Taliban fighters, seen at a distance of 1,000 metres, were planning a rocket attack on the post.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\">{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|date=9 December 2016|work=Herald Sun|access-date=9 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Hastie had authority to neutralise the threat, communicated the coordinates for the combatants and called in a strike by a US Army Apache helicopter. However, the attack went badly wrong:<blockquote>I remember looking at the target, and then hearing the guns fire and then the rounds splashing 600m away and thinking, \u2018what the heck, that is not at all, that is not the target.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\"/></blockquote>Two boys, Toor Jan, age 7 and his brother Odood, who were collecting firewood had been mistakenly targeted for the two Taliban figures. An ADF inquiry later cleared Australian forces of any breakdown in procedure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theaustralian.com.au%2Fnation%2Fdefence%2Fandrew-hastie-in-clear-on-second-afghan-incident%2Fnews-story%2Fb91a2ab20fa8ccfe4fb7f1a546b5e7cd&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=9daa57764cfab982111b15402df38b47-1576880157|title=Andrew Hastie in clear on second afghan incident|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref> However, Hastie took responsibilities for the action and met with the grieving family. <blockquote>I said to them, \"I'm the commander; I was the guy who made the decision.\" And I said, \"I'm sorry, if I could take it back I would... and the uncle replied in Pashtun through the interpreter. He sort of nodded and gave me a warm sympathetic smile and said, \"I forgive you.\"<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\" /></blockquote>For Hastie, the death of the boys was both personally affecting and a turning point in his political outlook:<blockquote>I just felt sick... It was arrogant to think we could build a mirror image of ourselves in foreign lands. [The boys\u2019 deaths] underscored the gap between our aims and reality. The two boys who perished were bystanders in this larger struggle. I was humbled and chastened by this experience. War is a miserable enterprise. I remember saying to my boss: \u2018I didn\u2019t come here to kill kids\u2019.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\" /></blockquote>\n\n==== 3. Severed hands ====\nOn 28 April 2013, a major operation began against the senior insurgent commander, Abdul Hai.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Masters|first=Chris|title=No Front Line: Australian special forces at war in Afghanistan|publisher=Allen & Unwin|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=510}}</ref> The attacking force of 120 included \"one Commando and two Provincial Response Company platoons\"<ref name=\":2\" /> led by Hastie's SASR B Troop, which he helped direct from the air. Several combatants were killed in the ensuing battle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=11 July 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref> On searching the dead men, one corporal severed the right hands of two \"Enemy Killed in Action\" using a scalpel. On attempting to do the same to a third EKIA the soldier was stopped by a sergeant who said, \u201cWhat the f*** are you doing?\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=11 July 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref> On arriving at this part of battle environment, Hastie gave the order to cease the practice and the next day the incident was reported to the CO, triggering a major ADF inquiry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=11 July 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> The inquiry heard that there had recently been training on how to collect biometric samples, particularly in managing the aftermath of a suicide bomb event.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Masters|first=Chris|title=No Front Line|publisher=Allen & Unwin|year=2017|isbn=9781760111144|location=Australia|pages=505}}</ref> Hastie later commented that \u201cthe guy giving instructions conflated site exploitation of a suicide bomber with that of biometric testing.\" The SASR corporal who severed the hands later conceded he had made an error of judgement in not first checking with his patrol commander.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|website=mobile.abc.net.au|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> The inquiry made it clear that the practice, and the fact that some appeared to accept it at the time, \"demonstrated a drift in values, or at least a degree of desensitisation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=11 July 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== 4. Suicide bomber capture ====\nIntelligence gathering operations constantly scanned for \"chatter\" on plans for suicide bombings by the Taliban. To interdict these operations, Hastie was required to work with local forces, however by May 2013 the Wakunish were now working independently,<ref name=\":2\" /> so Australia's forces need to work with the Provincial Response Company<ref name=\":2\" /> with whom they had few shared values. One of the first missions with the PRC was to capture a suicide bomber in [[Urozgan Province|Urozgan]] before he had the opportunity to attack. The operation was conducted in darkness \"When they found the suicide bomber they were chasing, a barrel pressed against his temple was used to ease the man awake.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> Now the enemy was secure, along with his explosive vest, and rockets, the PRC commanders, and their own magistrate, had a stand off with Hastie \u2014 insisting that they should execute the captured man.<ref name=\":2\" /> The \"person under confinement\" was escorted to prison by Hastie and his team. \n\n==== 5. Truck bomb ====\nHastie's B Company received intelligence of a Taliban plan to use a truck to enter their own [[Forward operating base]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The order was given for all personnel to put on armour and helmets if they were moving outside of secure buildings. An airstrike was considered once the exact location of the bomber was found, however, it was decided to neutralise the threat using Hastie's unit, on the ground. The force element was flown in on two Australian [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk|Black Hawk]]<nowiki/>s<ref name=\":2\" /> the bomber located and killed, and the team extracted. From wheels down to wheels up had taken 22 minutes. There were no force injuries or casualties. For Hastie:<blockquote>It was the SOTG machine at its most efficient and precise. When we got back and the order was given to all on base that they could take off the body armour and helmets when outside there was a sigh of relief. There was no doubt about that mission. We were protecting the base from attack. We just thought of Aussie diggers, aid workers, [[Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (Australia)|DFAT]] and everyone else supporting us behind the wire. I went to the gym and later enjoyed a deep and peaceful sleep.<ref name=\":2\" /></blockquote>\n\n=== Jordan and Afghanistan, 2014-2015 ===\nHastie deployed in late-2014 and 2015 to an intelligence role<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/analysis-andrew-hastie-chau-chak-wing-complex-situation/9795766|title=Here's why Andrew Hastie named Chau Chak Wing in Parliament|last=Editor|first=Political|last2=Probyn|first2=rew|date=24 May 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> in the Middle East-based role countering [[ISIL]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-08-21/hastie-liberal-candidate-keogh-alp-canning-byelection/6713986|title=Andrew Hastie to run for Liberals, Matt Keogh for ALP in Canning by-election|date=20 August 2015|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref> as an Operations Officer for Operation Gallant Phoenix,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unforgiving60.podbean.com/e/a-tale-of-two-andrews-%e2%80%93-two-federal-politicians-but-no-politics-andrew-hastie-mp-and-andrew-leigh-mp/|title=S1E15a- A Tale of Two Andrews \u2013 Two Federal Politicians / But No Politics! Andrew Hastie (MP) and Andrew Leigh (MP)|last=Development|first=PodBean|website=unforgiving60.podbean.com|language=en|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref> a classified defence operation based in Jordan. The operation is said to be collecting intelligence \"from commando raids in Syria and Iraq and funnelling it to law enforcement agencies in Europe and Southeast Asia to help stop future attacks.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Schmitt|first=Eric|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/24/us/politics/us-isis-fight.html|title=Its Territory May Be Gone, but the U.S. Fight Against ISIS Is Far From Over|date=24 March 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=24 March 2020|last2=Gibbons-Neff|first2=Thomas|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Cooper|first3=Helene|last4=Rubin|first4=Alissa J.}}</ref> \n\nBy mid 2013, Hastie had returned home to Perth. With his time in the SASR he felt he had achieved \"the peak of soldiering\"<ref name=\":2\" /> but had been frustrated at \"the absence of strategy\"<ref name=\":2\" /> which could only come from government. \"We were hidebound by policy that compromised military principle. We were planning who we took out on the ground before we planned the mission.\u2019<ref name=\":2\" /> Hastie joined the [[Liberal Party of Australia]] shortly after his return. He resigned his commission from the ADF in August 2015 after announcing his candidature to run as the Member for Canning in the House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/andrew-hastie-liberal-byelection-candidate-led-troop-probed-for-chopping-hands-off-taliban-20150821-gj52lj.html|title=Andrew Hastie, Liberal byelection candidate, was in charge of troop probed for chopping hands off Taliban|date=22 August 2015|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Political career (2015\u2013present)==\n\n=== Election and first Turnbull Government ===\nThe seat of [[Division of Canning|Canning]] became vacant by the death in office of the Liberal member, [[Don Randall]], triggering the [[2015 Canning by-election]]. Hastie began a launched his campaign with strong support from [[Mathias Cormann]] and [[Julie Bishop]], however he was quickly inundated with media criticism about the \"severed hands\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2015/08/australia-election-dictate-pm-fate-150830103706951.html|title=Australia by-election could dictate PM's fate|last=Kurmelovs|first=Royce|website=www.aljazeera.com|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> incident and was further \"rattled\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/creationism-rattles-cannings-newchum-politician-20150911-gjk0o8.html|title=Creationism rattles Canning's new-chum politician|last=Murphy|first=Damien|date=11 September 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> by strong questioning of his family's religious beliefs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/creationism-rattles-cannings-newchum-politician-20150911-gjk0o8.html|title=Creationism rattles Canning's new-chum politician|last=Murphy|first=Damien|date=11 September 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> Within days Hastie would give a speech in which he strongly defended the soldiers under his command and his own military service:<blockquote>I have not lived my life behind a desk pushing paper and talking about the concepts of freedom and democracy. I have acted. I have put my life on the line for this country and for that freedom.<ref name=\":6\" /></blockquote>On Saturday 19 September 2015, after a four-week campaign that centred on solving the [[methamphetamine]] epidemic, Hastie won 55.26% of votes under the [[Two-party-preferred vote|two-party-preferred]] system, making him the 10th Federal Member for Canning, defeating Labor candidate [[Matt Keogh]]. He joined the government of [[Malcolm Turnbull]] who had himself become [[Prime Minister of Australia]] a week before the by-election. Hastie gave his first speech on 13 October 2015, which centred on his priorities for healthy democracy, stronger community institutions and for defending Australia's sovereignty, \"To safeguard our freedom I believe that the first duty of the Australian federal government is to secure our nation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b1239e0c-7fca-43e4-aac5-25ac64e2bc96/0128%22|title=ParlInfo - BUSINESS : Rearrangement|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> In the first months, when headlines were dominated by the [[2015 Parramatta shooting|Parramatta shooting]] and the [[November 2015 Paris attacks|Paris terror attack]] and the aftermath of the [[2014 Sydney hostage crisis|Sydney hostage crisis]], it seemed that Hastie's parliamentary career would be marked by his concern<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/asio-chief-called-just-two-coalition-mps-about-islam-debate-malcolm-turnbull-20151218-glr0js.html|title=ASIO chief called just two Coalition MPs about Islam debate: Malcolm Turnbull|last=Kenny|first=David Wroe and Mark|date=18 December 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> about \"radical islamist ideology\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Alberici|first=Emma|title=Interview: Andrew Hastie, Liberal MP|date=31 May 2017|url=https://www.abc.net.au/lateline/interview:-andrew-hastie,-liberal-mp/8577672|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|language=en-AU|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> arguing in interviews<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.2gb.com/podcast/alan-jones-andrew-hastie/|title=Alan Jones \u2013 Andrew Hastie|date=1 December 2015|website=2GB|language=en|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> and op eds that: <blockquote>I have read the Koran in its entirety. In my previous job with the Australian Defence Force, I studied Islamic State propaganda including many of its violent videos and images in an effort to understand their objectives, aims and rationale. I was disturbed by what I saw, but not cowed into inaction.... we should be free to question the roots of Islamic terrorism, especially the brand pushed by Islamic State. It is troubling that we have had young Australians sympathising with the theology and ideology of Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=AAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.adelaidenow.com.au%2Fnews%2Fopinion%2Fwe-should-be-free-to-question-the-roots-of-islamic-terrorism-especially-the-brand-pushed-by-islamic-state-writes-andrew-hastie%2Fnews-story%2F81bc06145842d58af1c980edb20d0b42&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=3290dea7434c4d3e6d98e6f90da327e0-1586142284|title=Adelaidenow.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to The Advertiser for exclusive stories|website=www.adelaidenow.com.au|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Re-election and second Turnbull Government ===\nHastie stood again for the division of Canning for the [[2016 Australian federal election]], on Saturday 2 July. He won 56.79% of the votes under the [[Two-party-preferred vote]] against Labor opposition candidate Barry Winmar, moving his seat from being \"marginal\" to \"fairly safe\" according to the [[Australian Electoral Commission]].{{cn|date=March 2020}} He was appointed to the [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]] [[File:Andrew Hastie MP, Chair of the Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security with Deputy Chair Anthony Byrne MP in February 2020 photo taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|Anthony Byrne, a Labor MP and Deputy Chair of the Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security with its Chair, Andrew Hastie MP. ]]in September 2016, and invited to chair the committee from February 2017.<ref>http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22chamber%2Fhansardr%2F9de5f081-9ccf-4f72-a05a-02462c1f3a0c%2F0136%22 Retrieved 15 June 2017</ref> It's known the committee receives briefings from [[Inspector-General of Intelligence and Security (Australia)]], [[Australian Signals Directorate]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/plans-to-boost-electronic-spy-agency-meet-with-extreme-caution-20190615-p51y1o.html|title=Plans to boost electronic spy agency meet with extreme caution|last=Ireland|first=David Wroe, Judith|date=15 June 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref> and [[Australian Security Intelligence Organisation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itnews.com.au/news/four-hour-top-secret-briefing-used-to-press-encryption-law-need-516084|title=Four hour 'top secret' briefing used to press encryption law need|website=iTnews|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref> As such, Hastie and fellow members of the [[bi-partisan]] committee are \"privy to a lot of information and intelligence briefings that other members of parliament aren't.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skynews.com.au/details/_6070077627001|title='We can't deny there are problems with China's behaviour': Dutton|website=Sky News Australia|language=|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref> Through his work with the PJCIS Hastie came to conclude that Australia is \"facing an unprecedented threat from espionage and foreign interference, and that current laws are not adequate to deal with this threat.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/foreign-interference-laws-needed-before-super-saturday-vote-christian-porter-says-20180607-h113o9|title=Foreign interference laws needed before super Saturday vote, Christian Porter says|date=7 June 2018|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> At this point the source of the foreign interference was unnamed. Following its deliberations, the committee reviewed and amended the [https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2018C00506 Espionage and Foreign Interference Act 2018]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defence.gov.au/dsvs/industry/DISP-foreign-espionage.asp|title=Foreign Espionage & Interference Act 2018 : Industry Security Program : Department of Defence|last=|website=www.defence.gov.au|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> and [https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2018A00029 Security of Critical Infrastructure Act 2018]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/about-us/our-portfolios/national-security/security-coordination/security-of-critical-infrastructure-act-2018|title=Security of Critical Infrastructure Act 2018|website=www.homeaffairs.gov.au|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== First Morrison Government ===\n[[File:Andrew Hastie and daughter (KN).jpg|thumb|In Parliamentary offices, Andrew Hastie plays with his daughter. ]]\nIn August 2018, Malcolm Turnbull called for two [[2018 Liberal Party of Australia leadership spills|leadership spills]], in which Hastie is known to have supported the call for a new leader.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-24/the-liberal-mps-that-sparked-the-spill/10161660|title=The 43 Liberal MPs that brought down Malcolm Turnbull|date=24 August 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref> [[Scott Morrison]] was elected leader of the Liberal Party, becoming [[Prime Minister of Australia]]. Hastie maintained his chairmanship of the PJCIS as it took an increasingly serious tone on foreign threats. The committee carried the Assistance and Access Bill 2018 through to legislation enabling security agencies to access otherwise encrypted communications by people who intend harm to Australians. Prompted by the sale of the Port of [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] to interests connected to the Communist Party of China, the Committee made recommendations for the Security of Critical Infrastructure Act 2018 (Cth) (Act)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://corrs.com.au/insights/critical-infrastructure-reporting-starts-now|title=Critical infrastructure: reporting starts now|website=Corrs Chambers Westgarth|language=en|access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref> \u2014 placing a national security test to any foreign investment into energy or water assets and, notably, ports. The committee also contributed amendments to the Foreign Influence Transparency Scheme Act 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ag.gov.au/Integrity/foreign-influence-transparency-scheme/Pages/default.aspx|title=Foreign Influence Transparency Scheme|last=Department|first=Attorney-Generals's|website=www.ag.gov.au|language=en-au|access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn his constituency work, Hastie surprised some by giving public support to striking [[Alcoa Australia]] workers, organised by the [[Australian Workers' Union]]. Hastie said, he supported the strikers because, \"energy production in Australia is too expensive and it is hurting industry, workers, seniors and families. We have to put Australians first. Otherwise, more jobs will go offshore to other countries. Our smelters and refineries will close down. Energy security is job security.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/opinion/andrew-hastie-utility-bills-are-crippling-workingclass-families/news-story/d2890e742284107f09917bfcbfd78a08|title=Utility bills are crippling working-class families|date=23 November 2018|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=9 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Re-election and second Morrison Government ===\n[[File:AH and PM at Mandurah War Memorial (KN).jpg|thumb|Prime Minister Scott Morrison and Andrew Hastie MP stand by ANZAC wreaths at a memorial in Mandurah.]]\nIn the [[2019 Australian federal election]], held on 18 May, Hastie ran for re-election and won 61.83% of the [[two-party-preferred vote]] against the Australian Labor Party's candidate Mellisa Teede. On entering the [[46th Parliament of Australia]] Hastie, in which [[Scott Morrison]] was returned as Prime Minister, Hastie become increasingly involved in lawmaking around matters of national security. He spoke in 45 debates in 2019, above average according to Open Australia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openaustralia.org.au/mp/andrew_hastie/canning|title=Andrew Hastie MP, Canning (OpenAustralia.org)|website=www.openaustralia.org.au|access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref> the bulk of them surrounding matters of security or sovereignty.  [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]] pushed forward the Temporary Exclusion Orders Bill designed to prevent dual-national terrorists from returning to Australia. [[File:Andrew Hastie MP with flag gifted to him by SASR operators January 2020 photo taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|Andrew Hastie in his electoral office in Mandurah, with an Australian flag given to him by a friend in the ADF, it had once flown at a army forward operating base]]However, the Identity-matching Services Bill 2019 and the Australian Passports Amendment (Identity-matching Services) Bill 2019 were reviewed by the committee and sent back for redrafting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/facial-recognition-bill-knocked-back-20191024-p533s6|title=Facial recognition bill knocked back|date=23 October 2019|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref> By 2020, Hastie was able to review the suite of legislative changes security as being all of one piece, to strengthen Australia's position in the region and the world:<blockquote>What we\u2019ve done in Australia over the last three or four years, I call it our pivot... taking action to preserve our digital sovereignty by excluding high-risk vendors from our future 5G network, passing the Espionage and Foreign Interference Laws, stopping the extradition treaty to China, those things were part of the pivot and ultimately, they\u2019re expressions of our sovereignty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/5792-insight-australia-s-relationship-with-china-andrew-hastie-mp|title=INSIGHT: Australia\u2019s relationship with China \u2013 Andrew Hastie MP|last=Levy|first=Tasha|last2=Levy|first2=Tasha|date=19 March 2020|website=www.defenceconnect.com.au|language=en|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\u00a0 </blockquote>\n\n==== \"We Must See China with Clear Eyes\" ====\n[[File:Joint media release Hastie Paterson November 15 2019.jpg|alt=A media release from Andrew Hastie MP and Senator James Paterson.|thumb|Hastie and James Paterson confirm they have been blocked from visiting China following their public comments about the [[Communist Party of China]]]]\nIn August 2019 Hastie wrote an [[Op-ed]] column, \"We Must See China with Clear Eyes\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=7 August 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> for ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' and ''[[The Age]]'' newspapers<ref name=\"Hastie\"/>, where he admitted that Communist China \u2014 rather than [[Islamic terrorism]], which he worked to defeat in his military career \u2014 would be the real security concern of the 21st Century. Moreover, a rising, revisionist, expansionist China would frame \"almost every strategic and economic question facing Australia in the coming decades.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=7 August 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>  What brought more attention was his strong criticism of Western democracies and their mistaken belief \"that economic liberalisation would naturally lead to democratisation in China\" much as the French had believed the [[Maginot Line]] would guard them against the German advance in 1940. Hastie wrote, \"Like the French, Australia has failed to see how mobile our authoritarian neighbour has become.\"<ref name=\":01\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last1=Hastie|first1=Andrew|date=8 August 2019|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> The piece caused \"a firestorm\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-s-awakening-to-xi-s-bid-for-total-control-of-china-and-beyond-20190809-p52for.html|title=Hastie's awakening to Xi's bid for total control of China - and beyond|last=Hartcher|first=Peter|date=9 August 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> with the [[Embassy of China, Canberra|Chinese Embassy in Australia]] denouncing the remarks as reflecting a \"[[Cold war (general term)|Cold War]] mentality\",<ref name=\":11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-08/chinese-officials-slam-andrew-hastie-nazi-beijing-china-comments/11395980|title=Liberal MP Andrew Hastie condemned by China after comparing Beijing's rise to threat from Nazi Germany|last1=Laschon|first1=Eliza|date=8 August 2019|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> while Western Australian Premier [[Mark McGowan]], whose state is heavily reliant on China for trade,<ref name=\"abcaunazi\">{{cite news|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-09/wa-particularly-vulnerable-in-a-china-us-trade-war/11395926|title=Western Australia's huge reliance on China leaves it particularly vulnerable in a trade war|last1=O'Flaherty|first1=Alisha|date=10 August 2019|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> accusing Hastie of \"threatening WA jobs with extreme and inflammatory language.\"<ref name=\"abcaunazi\" /> An academic at UWA opined that the Western Australian government's contemporaneous relationship with China may not be sustainable in the future, saying \"But there may come a time where this relationship is not possible to be run purely on commercial lines, and I have to say most of the reason for that is the changing behaviour of the Chinese Communist Party.\"<ref name=\"abcaunazi\" /> Conversely, Hastie received support from his colleagues [[Dave Sharma]]<ref name=\":21\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-wins-support-for-his-china-warning-from-former-diplomat-sharma-20190810-p52fup.html|title=Hastie wins support for his China warning from former diplomat Sharma|last1=Wright|first1=Shane|date=10 August 2019|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> and [[Peter Dutton]].<ref name=\":31\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/no-point-pretending-there-s-nothing-to-see-here-peter-dutton-warns-on-china-20190809-p52fgz.html|title='No point pretending there's nothing to see here': Peter Dutton warns on China|last1=Shields|first1=Bevan|date=9 August 2019|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> Hastie had been invited on a study trip with several colleagues to China with the independent think tank China Matters. However the Chinese embassy announced \u201cthat at this time Mr Hastie and Senator Paterson are not welcome\" unless they \"genuinely repent and redress their mistakes.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/nov/15/china-denies-entry-to-liberal-mps-andrew-hastie-and-james-paterson|title=China denies entry to Liberal MPs Andrew Hastie and James Paterson|last=editor|first=Katharine Murphy Political|date=15 November 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=18 December 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> This snub had the effect of making [[Communist Party of China]] attempts to control the behaviour and speech of people in sovereign nations an even bigger concern. Hastie's warnings about Chinese abuses of human rights and interference with sovereign nations appeared to be vindicated when newspapers released 400 pages of Chinese documents<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/16/world/asia/china-xinjiang-documents.html|title='Absolutely No Mercy': Leaked Files Expose How China Organized Mass Detentions of Muslims|last=Ramzy|first=Austin|date=16 November 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=18 December 2019|last2=Buckley|first2=Chris|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> on the workings of internment camps in [[Xinjiang]], shortly followed by the apparent defection of a young Chinese spy with information in connection with a Chinese Australian, Nick Zhao<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-25/chinese-spy-parliament-foreign-interference-in-hong-kong-taiwan/11735176|title=A man is dead. Another fears being killed. Here's a breakdown of the claims about Chinese espionage|last=Conifer|first=Dan|date=25 November 2019|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> who was funded by Chinese interests to run for parliament, and was later found dead in a hotel room. By raising concerns about foreign interference, the opinion piece has been seen as a \"threshold\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-s-awakening-to-xi-s-bid-for-total-control-of-china-and-beyond-20190809-p52for.html|title=Hastie's awakening to Xi's bid for total control of China - and beyond|last=Hartcher|first=Peter|date=9 August 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref>, with other commentators predicting that Hastie's concerns \"will dominate the political agenda\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/ellen-whinnett-china-crisis-looms-large-in-canberra/news-story/66c19d19acafcbaa2a914fabe17b23d5|title=China crisis looms large in Canberra|date=4 December 2019|work=Herald Sun|access-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>, having been discussed in the pages of global newspapers such as ''[[Haaretz]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/.premium-a-dead-spy-chinese-hackers-and-the-australian-commando-warning-israel-1.8223349|title=A Dead Spy, Chinese Hackers and the Australian Commando Warning Israel|last=Melman|first=Yossi|date=6 December 2019|website=haaretz.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref>  ''[[The Times]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/beijing-denies-australian-mps-right-to-visit-china-bldtfvl2j|title=Beijing denies Australian MPs right to visit China|last=Times|first=Bernard Lagan, Sydney {{!}} The|access-date=18 December 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> and ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/28/world/australia/china-spying-wang-liqiang-nick-zhao.html|title=Suddenly, the Chinese Threat to Australia Seems Very Real|last=Cave|first=Damien|date=28 November 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=18 December 2019|last2=Tarabay|first2=Jamie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nHastie has been described as a \"conservative\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/ruthless-hardline-and-focused-the-mp-who-stunned-parliament-20180525-p4zhgy.html|title='Ruthless, hardline and focused': The MP who stunned Parliament|last=Wright|first=Tony|date=25 May 2018|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>, a \"social conservative\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wahlquist|first=Calla|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/sep/08/canning-byelection-the-complete-and-completely-unofficial-guide-to-the-candidates|title=Canning byelection: the complete (and completely unofficial) guide to the candidates|date=7 September 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=31 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and, at least by the official Chinese government media as \"an arch-conservative\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/21/c_137406904.htm|title=News Analysis: Aussie gov't set for period of upheaval following leadership challenge to PM - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>. Critics see his foreign policy outlook as being \"jingoistic\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1161600.shtml|title=Australia need not follow US script on its relationship with China - Global Times|website=www.globaltimes.cn|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> and the MP himself as \"a notorious hawk.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/08/andrew-hasties-nazi-germany-warning-on-china-labelled-extreme-and-unwelcome|title=China denounces Liberal MP Andrew Hastie's Nazi Germany analogy|date=8 August 2019|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Hastie himself has said, \"I am not a libertarian, but I am a Liberal, which is to say that I am committed to freedom.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/blogs/andrew-bolt/andrew-hastie-shames-the-free-speech-quislings/news-story/1f81333ae068f76e98ca8b311effcc1d|title=Andrew Hastie Shames the Free Speech Quislings|last=Bolt|first=Andrew|date=3 March 2017|website=Herald Sun|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> This would appear to be confirmed by his decision to join the [[Atlantic Council]] \u2014 a [[Classical liberalism|Classical liberal]] bi-partisan think tank formed for \"defending democratic values.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/cbd-melbourne-hockey-ready-to-ride-post-virus-bondi-wave-20200325-p54dw1.html|title=CBD Melbourne: Hockey ready to ride post-virus Bondi wave|last=Loussikian|first=Samantha Hutchinson, Kylar|date=25 March 2020|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> The invitation<ref name=\":5\" /> came via US Congressman [[Mike Gallagher (American politician)|Mike Gallagher]], a conservative [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and [[Tom Tugendhat]], a British MP who describes himself as a \"community conservative.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smf.co.uk/tom-tugendhat-speech-2018/|title=Tom Tugendhat MP's speech for the SMF|date=8 November 2018|website=Social Market Foundation|language=en-CA|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> [[File:Soldiers cross a foot bridge in the Mirabad Valley.jpg|thumb|A footbridge in the Mirabad Valley, in [[Urozgan Province]], built by [[Australian Defence Force|ADF]] engineers, being patrolled by a member of the [[Afghan National Army]], followed by an Australian soldier from the [[Mentoring Task Force One|Mentoring Task Force]] in February 2010. ]] His outlook, unsurprisingly, has been shaped by his experience of war:<blockquote>I take my time in Afghanistan, especially in my first deployment, particularly my time with [[Mentoring Task Force One|MRTF2]] with the [[1st Battalion, Royal Australian Regiment|1RAR]] battle group, as being very formative for me, doing [[Nation Building - Afghanistan|Nation Building]] and realising the limitations of government to change people and their culture. We built bridges, we built a bazaar where we expected people to trade, we built schools and hospitals, we built all sorts of things, but fundamentally, we didn\u2019t change the way the Afghan people lived. Respecting people\u2019s sovereignty, and people\u2019s freedom to live as they choose is something that I learned over there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/5792-insight-australia-s-relationship-with-china-andrew-hastie-mp|title=INSIGHT: Australia\u2019s relationship with China \u2013 Andrew Hastie MP|last=Levy|first=Tasha|last2=Levy|first2=Tasha|date=19 March 2020|website=www.defenceconnect.com.au|language=en|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Hastie giving crayons to children op takht.jpg|thumb|Lieutenant Hastie distributing crayons to Afghan children in Oruzghan]]This experience seems to have made Hastie sceptical of [[Neoliberalism]], saying, \"I am now far more circumspect about the ability of military power to change people and societies, and far more aware of how resilient culture can be.\"<ref name=\"thewest.com.au\" /> By the same measure, Hastie is diffident towards [[Neoconservatism]], especially in its [[Laissez-faire]] tendencies, which he finds unacceptable because, \"despite the benefits of globalisation, there are always losers in the transfer of labour and capital offshore. Loss of identity through vocational irrelevance is a real anxiety in communities that prize skilled labour.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/opinion/political-class-ignored-the-people-and-paid-the-price/news-story/f1d35ad7c29f76daf08768182b316d55|title=Political Class Ignored the People and Paid the Price|date=23 November 2020|work=The Australian|access-date=30 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  Hastie's high view of  sovereignty and his desire to protect local people and their industries from global forces<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/may/26/andrew-hasties-contribution-to-our-china-effort-curious-and-curiouser|title=Andrew Hastie's contribution to our China effort? Curious and curiouser {{!}} Katharine Murphy|last=Murphy|first=Katharine|date=25 May 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=18 December 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> would places him in the tradition of [[National liberalism]]. Recently Ben Pronk and Tim Curtis (both former SAS officers, Pronk had been Hastie's commanding officer) asked Hastie for his vision for Australia. His off the cuff answer was: <blockquote>I hope to see a country where families are strong. Where we've incentivised families through the policies that we've legislated. I hope to see a strong defence force so that we can weather the challenges that will inevitably come. If you take history as a guide we will face inevitable security challenges. I hope that we are aware of our history, that we haven't cut the mooring that is our civilisation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=A Tale of Two Andrews|last=|first=|date=|website=Unforgiving 60|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref></blockquote>This statement contains three threads that are seen in almost all of Hastie's writing and remarks. First, a passion \"to defend the rule of law, democracy and the constituent freedoms\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Greg|first=Brown|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/rivals-unite-for-the-sake-of-democracy/news-story/455c76fe549eda7c318a6a496985b811|title=Rivals unite for the sake of democracy|date=13 July 2020|work=The Australian|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>. Second, a believe that \"Sovereignty, where compromised, must be recovered and protected.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/challenge-to-democracy-to-counter-russia-china-20191204-p53gzj.html|title=Challenge to democracy to counter Russia, China|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=9 December 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Third, that community or local institutions \"should define the character and activity of our nation from the ground up.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;db=CHAMBER;id=chamber/hansardr/e5ff85d2-b96e-4e0e-8227-2131e40beaf7/0200;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/e5ff85d2-b96e-4e0e-8227-2131e40beaf7/0049%22|title=ParlInfo - ADJOURNMENT : 45th Parliament|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Democracy ===\nOne [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC]] profile on Hastie found that \"the heart of his worldview is the belief that everyone is equal and has dignity\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382?pfmredir=sm&sf75079731=1&smid=Page:+ABC+News-Facebook_Organic&WT.tsrc=Facebook_Organic|title=Keeping the faith: Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|website=mobile.abc.net.au|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> and from here his convictions about democracy emanate. The belief in the inherent value of the individual means the individual must be free when it comes to \"thought, worship, speech, association and choice\" as Hastie said in his first speech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b1239e0c-7fca-43e4-aac5-25ac64e2bc96/0128%22|title=First Speech|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=13 October 2015|website=Parliament of Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> These freedoms allow our communities to naturally form and \"are the fullest expression of self-government.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/first_speech|title=First Speech|website=Andrew Hastie MP|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> Hastie recently collaborated with the [[Australian Labor Party]]'s [[Kimberley Kitching]] to form the \"Parliamentary Friends of Democracy.\" It comes out of a concern that democratic institutions are \"under increasing pressure around the globe.\" They believe, \"Australian parliamentarians have a duty to rise above party to defend the rule of law, democracy and the constituent freedoms that make Australia a special place to live.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theaustralian.com.au%2Fnation%2Fpolitics%2Frivals-unite-for-the-sake-of-democracy%2Fnews-story%2F455c76fe549eda7c318a6a496985b811&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=e77fa5e4fbb81da52eba770ee8c0a8a7-1576685699|title=Subscribe to The Australian {{!}} Newspaper home delivery, website, iPad, iPhone & Android apps|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> This view expands on concerns that Hastie has expressed elsewhere, that \"our greatest vulnerability lies not in our infrastructure, but in our thinking. That intellectual failure makes us institutionally weak. If we don't understand the challenge ahead for our civil society, in our parliaments, in our universities, in our private enterprises, in our charities \u2014 our little platoons \u2014 then choices will be made for us. Our sovereignty, our freedoms, will be diminished.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-08/chinese-officials-slam-andrew-hastie-nazi-beijing-china-comments/11395980|title=Embassy condemns MP Hastie for comparing China's rise to threat from Nazi Germany|last=Laschon|first=political reporter Eliza|date=8 August 2019|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> In February 2020 it was announced that Hastie had been invited to serve on a panel of western leaders who are concerned for the state of global democracy, the Commission on Advancing a Free World, in association with [[Atlantic Council|The Atlantic Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/news/press-releases/free-world-commission-of-legislators-from-leading-democracies-launched-at-munich-security-conference/|title=Free World Commission of legislators from leading democracies launched at Munich Security Conference|date=16 February 2020|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref> Their ''Declaration of Principles for Freedom, Prosperity, and Peace''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/declaration/|title=Declaration of Principles for Freedom, Prosperity, and Peace|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> articulates seven statements for protecting democracy across the world, beginning with \"the right of all people to live in free and just societies, where fundamental rights are protected under the rule of law.\"\n\n==== Freedom of thought - on marriage ====\nHastie saw the 2016 [[Same-sex marriage in Australia|Same-sex marriage debate in Australia]] as a conscience issue.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/opinion/marriage-is-peoples-institution-so-they-should-decide-its-future/news-story/a6ace55c388f0f5e3c7484f8738aefe6|title=Marriage is people's institution, so they should decide its future|date=20 September 2016|work=|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  He supported the postal survey because he believed that the institution of marriage, since it existed before the parliament, was an institution that \"belongs to the people\" so it was right for the people themselves to vote on it.<ref name=\":4\" /> When the \"yes vote\" was strongly returned, Hastie ensured passage of the bill, but could not vote for it himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-11-15/wa-politicians-to-ignore-same-sex-marriage-result/9154656|title=Prominent No campaigner to abstain from same-sex marriage vote|date=15 November 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> He explained, \"We went to the election with it, I was on television saying I would abstain, I've been in dialogue with constituents for the last 18 months and whenever I've talked to them about the issue, I've said I would abstain. My intention is to abstain because to vote yes would go against my conscience, but I want to uphold both the vote in Canning and the national result and abstention is the best way to do that.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/5058727/hastie-to-abstain-on-yes-vote/|title=Hastie to abstain on 'yes' vote|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=15 November 2017|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> Most of Hastie's statements through the public debate centred not on marriage, but on how to have the debate. When right wing commentators such as Larry Pickering used homophobic language towards [[LGBT]] persons, Hastie immediately condemned the statement, expressing his \"dismay\" at the degrading language, and pleaded for \"higher personal and civic standards\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/pickering-comments-despicable-hastie|title=Pickering comments despicable: Hastie|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of conscience - on military abuses ====\nRecent reports by Chris Masters and others of prisoner abuse, and even killings, by the Australian [[Special Air Service Regiment]] in Afghanistan have seen Hastie come forward as a strong advocate for transparency, though it may hurt the prestige of his former unit. He has \"emerged as a champion of the Brereton Inquiry.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/he-thought-i-was-going-to-shoot-him-how-david-s-little-voice-saved-him-in-war-20190913-p52qy6.html|title='He thought I was going to shoot him': How David's 'little voice' saved him in war|last=Masters|first=Nick McKenzie, Chris|date=20 September 2019|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> He strongly supports whistleblowers when it comes to abuse, telling ABC Radio the truth tellers should be respected: \"I don't want to go into any specific allegations, but they should be taken seriously and, as I said, we want a free media reporting on all issues.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/federal/secretive-and-elite-sas-soldiers-grilled-about-alleged-war-crimes-20180608-p4zkau.html|title=Secretive and elite SAS soldiers grilled about alleged war crimes|last=Wroe|first=Nick McKenzie, David|date=8 June 2018|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of expression ====\nIn one of Hastie's first electoral campaigns, he had a large outdoor poster vandalised. Rather than condemn the culprit, he wrote a Facebook message, \"Will Mandurah's Van Gogh please come forward<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/3985723/hasties-spray-mp-responds-to-graffiti-attack/|title=Hastie's spray: MP responds to graffiti attack|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=2016-06-22|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> then had a local graffiti artist add even more colour to the piece. However, when a campaign bus was torched, Hastie drew a firm line, calling them, \"cowards using Taliban tactics in the dead of night\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watoday.com.au/federal-election-2019/andrew-hastie-s-campaign-bus-survives-dead-of-night-arson-attack-20190420-p51fr4.html|title=Andrew Hastie's campaign bus survives 'dead of night' arson attack|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=19 April 2019|website=WAtoday|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> Hastie encourages debate and dissension, especially in classroom settings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/4488661/students-get-political-during-hastie-visit/|title=Students get political during Hastie visit|last=Cockerill|first=Jess|date=23 February 2017|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of press ====\nHastie is currently having difficulty balancing freedoms when it comes to the media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themonthly.com.au/today/paddy-manning/2019/23/2019/1563861108/joint-pain|title=Joint pain|last=paddym@schwartzmedia.com.au1516749970|date=23 July 2019|website=The Monthly|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> He has actively stood up for journalists at the ABC and [[Sydney morning Herald|Sydney Morning Herald]], using Parliamentary privilege to name Chau Chak Wing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-23/turnbull-did-not-know-hastie-would-make-chau-chak-wing-claims/9790476|title=Liberal MP says he did his duty in speaking up about political donor|last=Yaxley|first=political reporters Louise|last2=Gribbin|first2=Caitlyn|date=23 May 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=31 March 2020|last3=Conifer|first3=Dan}}</ref> as a man who co-conspired to bribe a UN official, a man who took the media outlets to court for defamation as they had published the accusations. Hastie explained his actions by saying \"...democracy works only if we have a free press that can publish information that serves the public interest.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-23/turnbull-did-not-know-hastie-would-make-chau-chak-wing-claims/9790476|title=Liberal MP says he did his duty in speaking up about political donor|last=Yaxley|first=political reporters Louise|last2=Gribbin|first2=Caitlyn|date=23 May 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=18 December 2019|last3=Conifer|first3=Dan}}</ref> However, current laws have allowed for the Australian Federal Police to raid journalists from the ABC and News Corp Australia for reasons of security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-07-15/abc-raids-australian-federal-police-press-freedom/11309810|title=AFP wanted fingerprints of journalists behind ABC special forces investigation|last=Lyons|first=the ABC's head of investigative journalism John|date=15 July 2019|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> This places a tension between freedom and sovereignty.\n\n==== Freedom of religion ====\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP with Huyghur delegates and Sen James Paterson 30 November 2019 photographed by D Birch.jpg|thumb|Delegates from Australia's Uyghur community, Sadam and Almas, meeting with Andrew Hastie MP (on left) and Senator James Paterson (right) at Parliament House, Canberra, in November 2019.]]\nWhile an observant Christian<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2 May 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Hastie holds to the view that if the law allows him to practice his faith, it must allow all to express their faith, or lack of it. That means, in Australia, that while he personally finds the burka \"repugnant\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2 May 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> as it \"defaces the personhood of women\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2 May 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> he would be very reluctant to have the state controlling it, as it's an expression of religious belief.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2 May 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> Hastie advocates strongly for freedom of religion as a basic human right across the globe, including the right of [[Uyghurs]] to practice their faith in China's Xingjian Province, saying \"it's our duty to stand up for them, and argue the point, and ask for their freedom.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-17/andrew-hastie-james-paterson-refuse-to-repent-china-criticism/11712160|title=Hastie and Paterson defiant in the face of China's calls for repentance|last=Dalzell|first=political reporter Stephanie|last2=Editor|first2=Political|date=17 November 2019|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=10 April 2020|last3=Probyn|first3=rew}}</ref> After [[The New York Times]] published the [[Xinjiang papers]] Hastie expressed deep empathy for those with personal ties to Uighurs facing \"systemic persecution and internment\".<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/liberal-mp-and-outspoken-china-critic-vows-uighur-loved-ones-will-not-be-forgotten|title=Liberal MP and outspoken China critic vows Uighur \u2018loved ones\u2019 will not be forgotten|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>  The documents showed how China views their the Muslim people of that region as being \"infected, as they say, with unhealthy thoughts\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-17/andrew-hastie-james-paterson-refuse-to-repent-china-criticism/11712160|title=Hastie and Paterson defiant in the face of China's calls for repentance|last=Dalzell|first=political reporter Stephanie|last2=Editor|first2=Political|date=17 November 2019|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=10 April 2020|last3=Probyn|first3=rew}}</ref> forcing millions into the communist government's [[Xinjiang re-education camps|Xinjiang re-education program]]. Hastie urged Uyghur people in Australia, and in China, not to give up hope.<ref name=\":7\" /> \n\n=== Sovereignty ===\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP with Mayor Rhys Williams at March 2020 Citizenship Ceremony in Mandurah photo taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|The Mayor of Mandurah, Rhys Williams, with Andrew Hastie MP, hosting an Australian Citizenship ceremony in March 2020]]\nHastie argues that Australia's representatives must be the ones making decisions that affect Australia's future, and so \"upholding our political system is the first thing that we must do because that at least preserves our political leadership and their ability to make decisions, un-influence by greater powers.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/5792-insight-australia-s-relationship-with-china-andrew-hastie-mp|title=INSIGHT: Australia\u2019s relationship with China \u2013 Andrew Hastie MP|last=Levy|first=Tasha|last2=Levy|first2=Tasha|date=19 March 2020|website=www.defenceconnect.com.au|language=en|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> As such he strongly resists foreign influence on the working of the Australian economy, culture or political system. \"My bottom line is Australian sovereignty \u2013 I want to protect our way of life, our freedom of action and our political institutions. That's my job as a member of the Commonwealth Parliament. I make no apologies for it.\"<ref name=\"Haaretz\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-a-dead-spy-chinese-hackers-and-the-australian-commando-warning-israel-1.8223349|title=A Dead Spy, Chinese Hackers and the Australian Commando Warning Israel|date=6 December 2019|work=Haaretz|access-date=18 December 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Economic sovereignty ====\nInterestingly, Hastie locates the energy debates as sovereignty issue, and in 2018 said, \"I have a problem legislating the Paris target because it undermines Australia's 'economic sovereignty'\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kelly|first=Joe|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/andrew-hastie-confirms-we-cannot-support-neg-in-current-form/news-story/48af53948ad288198550fdb68617f947|title=Andrew Hastie confirms he cannot support NEG in current form|date=16 August 2018|work=The Australian|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which meant he could not support the [[National Energy Guarantee]] (sometimes called \"the NEG\"). The next month he made a speech in the Federation Chamber, saying, \"Australian industry and Australian workers must come first. When it comes to energy, we must put the Australian people before Paris.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;db=CHAMBER;id=chamber/hansardr/b8101fb1-edde-4753-a50e-1709934db485/0350;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b8101fb1-edde-4753-a50e-1709934db485/0329%22|title=ParlInfo - Federation Chamber : PRIVATE MEMBERS' BUSINESS : Alcoa|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Sovereignty and political warfare ====\nThis has been the main legislative focus for Hastie in recent times. In an interview with the Israeli newspaper ''Haaretz'', Hastie explained that, \"Democratic countries must take domestic measures to protect against these threats. Australia has led the way in this regard. Authoritarian states use all instruments of state power to pursue their strategic objectives. Seemingly innocent activities like diplomacy, foreign-investment flows into strategic industries and infrastructure acquisitions like the purchase of ports are not so innocuous. Democracies who don't pay attention to these activities \u2013 and take measures to guard against them \u2013 risk becoming tethered to hyper-modern authoritarian states and losing their sovereignty in the process.\"<ref name=\"Haaretz\"/>\n\n==== Digital sovereignty ====\nHastie frames questions to do with the provision of information networks as a matter of sovereignty, which must be defended. Given that companies such as Huawei would be legally required to pass on information carried on their networks to the Chinese government,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/05/huawei-would-have-to-give-data-to-china-government-if-asked-experts.html|title=Huawei says it would never hand data to China's government. Experts say it wouldn't have a choice|last=Kharpal|first=Arjun|date=5 March 2019|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Hastie was a strong supporter of the Turnbull Government's decision to prevent that company from providing 5G services in Australia. Along with other parliamentarians from the Liberal Party, including [[Tim Wilson (Australian politician)|Tim Wilson]] and [[James Paterson (Australian politician)|James Paterson]] and [[Australian Labor Party|Labor's]] [[Kimberley Kitching]] and [[Anthony Byrne (politician)|Anthony Byrne]], he has been active in applying pressure to Australia's partners in the [[Five Eyes]] security alliance to do the same. In a public statement he explained how important that security arrangement is, \"In a time of growing strategic uncertainty, Australia values that membership more than ever.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/four-australian-mps-urge-britain-to-ban-huawei-20200124-p53u9x.html|title=Four Australian MPs urge Britain to ban Huawei|last=Bourke|first=Latika|date=23 January 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> In private settings, it is known that he has supported Byrne, the Deputy Chair of the committee Hastie leads, who used forceful language with the UK leadership, asking \u201cHow would you feel if the Russians laid down infrastructure in your own networks? That\u2019s how we feel about Huawei.\u201d Hastie is quoted as supporting frank conversation about data sovereignty with western allies, saying \"We save our toughest talk for our closest mates. I back my deputy chair.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=Lucy Fisher, Defence Editor {{!}} Caroline Wheeler, The Sunday|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/huawei-decision-may-threaten-trade-deal-with-us-says-mike-pence-vlg9d6ggs|title=Mike Pence and Tory MPs attack Boris Johnson over Huawei decision|access-date=12 February 2020|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n==== Enemies, allies and sovereignty ====\nIn May 2018, Hastie took the \"dramatic\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/andrew-hastie-senate-estimates/9797718|title=ASIO boss says Hastie's allegations have had no impact on intelligence allies|last=Gribbin|first=political reporter Caitlyn|date=24 May 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> step of using parliamentary privilege to name a Chinese-Australian property developer as being a corrupt person acting in the interests of a foreign power, saying, \"It is now my duty to inform the House and the Australian people that CC-3 is Chau Chak Wing, the same man who co-conspired to bribe the president of the United Nations General Assembly, John Ashe, the same man with extensive contacts in the Chinese Communist Party, including the United Front.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baumgaertner|first=Emily|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/world/australia/bribery-un-china-chau-chak-wing.html|title=In Australia, Fears of Chinese Meddling Rise on U.N. Bribery Case Revelation|date=22 May 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=22 March 2020|last2=Williams|first2=Jacqueline|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The information had been given to the MP during meetings in the United States earlier that year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baumgaertner|first=Emily|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/world/australia/bribery-un-china-chau-chak-wing.html|title=In Australia, Fears of Chinese Meddling Rise on U.N. Bribery Case Revelation|date=22 May 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=22 March 2020|last2=Williams|first2=Jacqueline|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The move was criticised as \"causing trouble\" both to the government to Australia's relationship with China.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/analysis-andrew-hastie-chau-chak-wing-complex-situation/9795766|title=Here's why Andrew Hastie named Chau Chak Wing in Parliament|last=Editor|first=Political|last2=Probyn|first2=rew|date=24 May 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Hastie himself believed he was compelled to speak as, \"My duty, first and foremost, is to the Australian people and the preservation of the ideals and democratic traditions of our Commonwealth.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/why-andrew-hastie-australias-uberpatriot-mp-risked-chinas-wrath-20180524-h10ie6|title=Why Andrew Hastie, Australia's uber-patriot MP, risked China's wrath|date=24 May 2018|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:AH and Gen Mattis.jpg|thumb|Hastie with General Jim Mattis outside the Pentagon on 4 May 2018]]\nWhile the incident gave another example of the parliamentarian's determination to protect Australian institutions from the influence of the Chinese Communist Party<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/political-donor-chau-chak-wing-behind-un-bribe-scandal-parliament-told-20180522-p4zgs5.html|title=Political donor Chau Chak Wing behind UN bribe scandal, Parliament told|last=Baker|first=Nick McKenzie, Richard|date=22 May 2018|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> his acting in consort with American defence forces and intelligence agencies such as the Department of Justice<ref>{{Cite news|last=Karp|first=Paul|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/may/24/andrew-hasties-use-of-us-intelligence-over-bribery-allegation-a-concern-dreyfus-says|title=Andrew Hastie's use of US intelligence over bribery allegation 'a concern', Dreyfus says|date=24 May 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=22 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> also provided more proof of his commitment to the [[U.S.-Australia alliance]]. At the high level, Hastie believes that this alliance is essential to Australia maintaining its sovereignty saying, \u201cNational leaders must affirm and articulate the values that define Western democracies, especially as we seek to build a coalition of like-minded partners to resist authoritarian political warfare.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/challenge-to-democracy-to-counter-russia-china-20191204-p53gzj.html|title=Challenge to democracy to counter Russia, China|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=9 December 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> He led a parliamentary delegation to the United States in early 2017 and afterwards indicated that, for him, the defence alliance holds personal importance<blockquote>\u201cWhen we met with House and Senate leaders, and members of the [US] House Intelligence Committee, those committee members really emphasised the importance of the relationship... I was sitting there in front of the Senate Intelligence and Security Committee and the committee minority leader is a senator from Virginia and I said to him, \u2018I wouldn't be sitting here if it wasn\u2019t for a medic from Virginia who saved my grandfather\u2019s life on the 31st of March 1945\u2019.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/4466943/hastie-promoted-to-key-national-security-role/|title=Hastie promoted to key national security role|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=14 February 2017|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Community ===\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP Age Care Community Visit.jpg|thumb|Andrew Hastie MP visiting Amana Living Meadow Springs Village, an Anglican age care community in Mandurah.]]Hastie's experiences in Afghanistan, especially in seeing how limited the military is in reshaping people's lives, seems to have given him an even higher view of community, culture and local institutions. In an interview about his wartime experiences, he said:<blockquote> For me, it proved that culture and geography (are) decisive in the formation of societies and political institutions. Building lasting, trusted institutions takes time, generations of stewardship and public virtue.<ref name=\"Whinnett\"/></blockquote>\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP with son Jonathan at the 2018 ANZAC Day March in Mandurah WA taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|His son Jonathan holding his hand, Andrew Hastie marches with veterans on [[Anzac Day]] in Mandurah. ]]\n\n Looking at Australia, Hastie believes that it is local institutions that provide civic foundations of \"accountability, freedom and democracy.\"<ref name=\"First Speech\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/first_speech|title=First Speech|website=Andrew Hastie MP|language=en|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref> He argued in his first speech that the first of these institutions is the family, which \"is central to a healthy society\"<ref name=\"First Speech\"/> but also extends to sporting clubs, service clubs, churches and local businesses.<ref name=\"First Speech\"/> In one op-ed, Hastie went even further, suggesting that community groups, or \"pre-political institutions\" are finally more important than governments:<blockquote> \"More powerful than the political levers of government are grassroots volunteer movements and pre-political institutions... Pre-political institutions are the best place for securing our freedoms and so we should take encouragement that democratic governments cannot control them, and are sent packing when they attempt to do so.\"<ref name=\"theaustralian.com.au\">{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/opinion/political-class-ignored-the-people-and-paid-the-price/news-story/f1d35ad7c29f76daf08768182b316d55|title=Political class ignored the people and paid the price|date=November 23, 2016|work=The Australian|access-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==== The power of community and PTSD ====\nHastie reflected on how his grandfather recovered from the trauma of [[World War II]] thanks, in part to the power of community, and laments that we may not have that power available to us now, \"Just thinking of my grandfather's own experience, he was shot up quite badly in the second world war where civil society was still very strong, community was still very strong, a lot of local clubs and organisations, I think he struggled with [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|PTSD]] but I think his PTSD was mitigated by those little platoons that we talk about, he was very close to his comrades from the second war, and I'm just not sure if we have in today's society that same sort of cushioning and community support as we had 70 years ago.\"<ref name=\"Grattan\"/>\n\n==== Community and environment ====\nWhile environmental concern is often seen as a progressive cause, Hastie sets the environment between two concerns - that, as per the [[Edmund Burke|Burkean]] contract - the good things inherited should be passed on to the next generation. And that the environment serves the community, which means they need to make the decisions about it. In a recent controversy about a proposed dredging of an estuary, Hastie said: <blockquote>\"I believe in the sovereignty of local communities to make decisions about how they conserve and develop their environment. The Bindjareb people, the First Australians in my constituency, have long been custodians of the waterways\u2014for many generations back to the present. The Murray Mandurah community also shares this responsibility, and together we are all stewards of the beautiful Peel-Harvey Estuary, a body of water larger than Sydney Harbour, teeming with marine life and brimming with natural beauty. We, therefore, through our local governments, have sovereignty over this natural asset and should have a say about how development takes place. We're not antiprogress, but we are rightly cautious about development, as we are the ones most affected by it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openaustralia.org.au/debates/?id=2019-09-11.151.1&s=speaker:10843#g151.2|title=Peel-Harvey Estuary: 11 Sep 2019: House debates (OpenAustralia.org)|website=www.openaustralia.org.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:AH with family (KN).jpg|thumb|Ruth and Andrew Hastie with their children in Mandurah, October 2018]]\nHastie met his wife Ruth in the summer of 2007 while he was studying at [[George Washington University]]. Their first date was \"watching then President George W. Bush walk from the Oval Office across the lawns of the White House to be whisked away in the Marine One helicopter.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/from-fighting-taliban-to-federal-politics-andrew-hastie-was-born-to-serve/news-story/af994f98fccf82ea9385ae465c00bc7c|title=From fighting Taliban to Federal politics|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|date=5 December 2015|website=Herald Sun|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Some months later, Hastie proposed to Ruth on the steps of the [[Sydney Opera House]]. The two were married in 2008 at [[Capitol Hill Baptist Church]]. Their children were born in Perth in June 2015 and August 2017. The family of four now lives in the [[City of Mandurah]] in the [[Peel (Western Australia)|Peel]] region of [[Western Australia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=For God and country|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/weekend-australian-magazine/sas-commander-liberal-party-rising-star-how-far-can-andrew-hastie-go/news-story/327a82373c4e90755402c1388506a502|accessdate=18 April 2018|agency=The Australian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Andrew|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/about_andrew|website=www.andrewhastie.com|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe credits his family for giving him a love for reading, especially \"biographies, Shakespeare, psalms\"<ref name=\"Development\"/> along with history. Favourite historians include [[Geoffrey Blainey]], [[H. W. Brands]], [[Niall Ferguson]], [[Andrew Roberts (historian)|Andrew Roberts]] and [[Ronald C. White]]. He also enjoys 20th century novelists such as [[Graham Greene]], [[Cormac McCarthy]] and [[P. G. Wodehouse]].\n\nFellow parliamentarians recognise Hastie as \u201ca man of deep faith\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openaustralia.org.au/debates/?id=2018-10-24.163.2&s=speaker:10843#g180.1|title=National Apology to Victims and...: 24 Oct 2018: House debates (OpenAustralia.org)|website=www.openaustralia.org.au|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> which he shares with his parents and siblings. Whilst he is frequently ridiculed as being \u201cfundamentalist\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themonthly.com.au/blog/mungo-maccallum/2018/28/2018/1527472468/hastie-judgement|title=Hastie judgement|last=kateg@themonthly.com.au1515708219|date=28 May 2018|website=The Monthly|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> he has been active across several reformed, evangelical and Protestant church communities with historic understandings of the Christian faith, including [[Capitol Hill Baptist Church]] in Washington DC, Shenton Park [[Anglican Church of Australia|Anglican Church]] in the North of Perth<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wahlquist|first=Calla|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/sep/03/canning-byelection-andrew-hastie-deems-questions-on-family-and-religion-unacceptable|title=Canning byelection: Andrew Hastie deems questions on family and religion 'unacceptable'|date=3 September 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=24 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and Crossroads Church in Canberra (an independent Evangelical Church) Hastie actually identifies with the Scottish Presbyterian faith in which he was raised<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/analysis-andrew-hastie-chau-chak-wing-complex-situation/9795766|title=Here's why Andrew Hastie named Chau Chak Wing in Parliament|last=Editor|first=Political|last2=Probyn|first2=rew|date=24 May 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> and his family church in Mandurah today is part of the [[Presbyterian Church of Australia]]. Having rejected Christian belief in his teens for several years, Hastie has spoken of how only a theistic understanding of the world makes any sense of the death and suffering he has personally witnessed, that if he were \"a closed universe atheist, how bleak and senseless those deaths would be\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sheridan|first=Greg|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/inquirer/politicians-reveal-what-religion-means-to-them/news-story/ad54c5d1948393ae00cf20b9445372d1|title=In defence of Christianity|date=23 July 2018|work=The Australian|accessdate=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n<center>\n\n[[File:Australian Active Service Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n\n[[File:Afghanistan Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Australian Service Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Australian Defence Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar v2.svg|100px]]\n\n[[File:AUS Meritorious Unit Citation with Federation Star.png|100px]]\n\n</center>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|[[File:Australian Active Service Medal ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the AASM]] || [[Australian Active Service Medal]] || with clasp for [[Australian Active Service Medal#ICAT|ICAT]]\n|-\n|[[File:Afghanistan Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the Afghanistan Medal for Australia]] || [[Afghanistan Medal (Australia)|Afghanistan Medal]] || Operation SLIPPER\n|-\n|[[File:Australian Service Medal ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the Australian Service Medal]] || [[Australian Service Medal]] || with clasp for CT/SR (Counter Terrorism / Special Recovery)<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://defence-honours-tribunal.gov.au/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/SASR-Final-Report-Public-Release.pdf|title = INQUIRY INTO RECOGNITION OF AUSTRALIAN DEFENCE FORCE SERVICE FOR SPECIAL AIR SERVICE COUNTER TERRORIST AND SPECIAL RECOVERY DUTIES|date = 22 December 2009|accessdate = 20 September 2015|website = Defence Honours Tribunal|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Australian Defence Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the ADM]] || [[Australian Defence Medal]] ||\n|-\n|[[File:NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar v2.svg|50px]] || [[NATO Medal#Non-Article 5 Medal|NATO Medal for the Non-Article 5 ISAF Operation in Afghanistan]] || with clasp ''ISAF''\n|-\n|[[File:AUS Meritorious Unit Citation with Federation Star.png|50px|Meritorious Unit Citation]] || [[Meritorious Unit Citation]] with [[Federation Star]] || Awarded to Task Force 66 in the [[2015 Australia Day Honours]]\n|-\n||| [[Infantry Combat Badge]] ||\n|-\n||| [[Army Combat Badge]] ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n* {{cite book |last = Masters |first = Chris |year = 2019 |title = No Front Line: Australian special forces at war in Afghanistan |location = Sydney |publisher = [[Allen & Unwin]] |isbn = 9781760111144}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=260805 Parliamentary biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Don Randall]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Division of Canning|Canning]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Western Australia Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hastie, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Australian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Australian military personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Australian Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian monarchists]]\n[[Category:Elliott School of International Affairs alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives for Canning]]\n[[Category:People educated at The Scots College]]\n[[Category:People from Wangaratta]]\n[[Category:Royal Military College, Duntroon graduates]]\n[[Category:University of New South Wales alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Andrew Hastie\n| honorific-suffix = [[Australian House of Representatives|MP]]\n| image            = Andrew Hastie Orignal.jpg\n| caption          = Hastie in 2018\n| constituency_MP  = [[Division of Canning|Canning]]\n| parliament       = Australian\n| majority         = \n| predecessor      = [[Don Randall]]\n| successor        = \n| term_start       = 19 September 2015\n| term_end         = \n| office1          = Chair of the [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]]\n| deputy1          = [[Anthony Byrne (politician)|Anthony Byrne]]\n| term_start1      = 15 February 2017\n| term_end1        = \n| predecessor1     = [[Michael Sukkar]]\n| successor1       = \n| birthname        = Andrew William Hastie\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1982|9|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[Wangaratta, Victoria]], Australia\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| nationality      = \n| spouse           = Ruth Hastie\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Australia]]\n| relations        = \n| children         = 2\n| residence        = [[Mandurah, Western Australia]]\n| alma_mater       = [[University of New South Wales|UNSW]], [[Australian Defence Force Academy|ADFA]], [[Royal Military College, Duntroon|Duntroon]], [[George Washington University|GWU]]\n| occupation       = \n| profession       = [[Member of Parliament]] (MP)\n| signature        = \n| website          = {{url|www.andrewhastie.com.au}}\n| footnotes        = \n| allegiance       = Australia\n| branch           = [[Australian Army]]\n| serviceyears     = 2001\u20132015\n| rank             = [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]]\n| unit             = [[2nd Cavalry Regiment (Australia)|2nd Cavalry Regiment]] (2007\u20132009)<br />[[Special Air Service Regiment]] (2010\u20132015)\n| battles          = [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br/>[[Military intervention against ISIL]]\n}}\n\n'''Andrew William Hastie''' (born 30 September 1982) is an Australian politician who serves as Chair of the [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]] and as the Federal MP for [[Division of Canning|Canning]], [[Western Australia|WA]] in the [[Australian House of Representatives]]. He was first elected in the [[2015 Canning by-election]] and re-elected in 2016 and 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Andrew Hastie MP|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=260805|website=www.aph.gov.au|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> A controversial figure, his public statements for Australia to \"preserve our sovereignty\"<ref name=\"Hastie\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=7 August 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> in defiance of an \"expansionist\"<ref name=\"Grattan\">{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/politics-with-michelle-grattan-andrew-hastie-on-foreign-influence-security-and-veteran-mental-health-128545|title=Politics with Michelle Grattan: Andrew Hastie on foreign influence, security and veteran mental health|last=Grattan|first=Michelle|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> [[Communist Party of China]] have been condemned as \"totally intemperate\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ferguson|first=Richard|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/kerry-stokes-says-andrew-hastie-did-more-harm-than-good-with-china-remarks/news-story/bc218d8b7cbffd3f1cc3ec6cb6db8ee8|title=Kerry Stokes says Andrew Hastie did more harm than good with China remarks|date=9 February 2020|work=The Australian|access-date=9 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"inflammatory\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watoday.com.au/politics/western-australia/wa-premier-slams-andrew-hastie-s-china-concerns-as-extreme-and-inflammatory-20190808-p52f7m.html|title=WA Premier slams Andrew Hastie's China concerns as 'extreme and inflammatory'|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=8 August 2019|website=WAtoday|language=en|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref> by Australian corporate leaders, then praised as a matter of \"strong public interest\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/radio/programs/pm/strong-public-interest-in-chinese-influence-claims/9792976|title=\"Strong public interest\" in Chinese influence claims|date=23 May 2018|website=ABC Radio|language=en-AU|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> and \"necessary, and important\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/news/politics/2019/08/17/how-the-china-question-split-australian-politics/15659640008614|title=How the China question split Australian politics|last=Seccombe|first=Mike|date=17 August 2019|website=The Saturday Paper|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> by security analysts [[Clive Hamilton|Professor Clive Hamilton]] and Professor Rory Medcalf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/in-defence-of-andrew-hastie-20190811-p52fyw|title=In defence of Andrew Hastie|date=11 August 2019|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> His stance led to the [[Government of China]] refusing him and his colleague [[James Paterson (Australian politician)|James Paterson]] from visiting China on a study tour, demanding that they \"repent\" from their views.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/outspoken-liberal-politicians-must-repent-and-redress-says-china|title='Outspoken' Liberal politicians must 'repent and redress', says China|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and family==\nHastie's mother Sue was a primary school teacher, particularly to children with special needs. [[File:Andrew Hastie with his father Peter Hastie back yard Wangaratta Victoria circa 1983.jpg|alt=Andrew Hastie, age 1, with his father Peter, around 1983|thumb|Andrew Hastie with his father Peter, in the backyard of their home in Wangaratta, Victoria, circa 1983]] Her mother Rose \u2014 to whom, Hastie says in his first speech, he was \"very close\"<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b1239e0c-7fca-43e4-aac5-25ac64e2bc96/0128%22|title=First Speech|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=13 October 2015|website=Australian Parliament House|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref>\u2014 was a nurse throughout her life, caring for Hastie's grandfather, Reginald a war veteran, through to his death.\n\nSimilarly, his paternal grandfather served as an officer with the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] and was severely wounded by gunfire when covering the air-sea rescue of two downed Australian airmen during the [[Pacific War]] for which he was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]].<ref name=\":8\" /> His son (Hastie's father) Peter has served as a pastor in church communities, early on in rural [[Wangaratta]], Victoria; and later in the inner urban suburb of [[Ashfield, New South Wales|Ashfield]], where he launched a Mandarin speaking congregation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-s-awakening-to-xi-s-bid-for-total-control-of-china-and-beyond-20190809-p52for.html|title=Hastie's awakening to Xi's bid for total control of China - and beyond|last=Hartcher|first=Peter|date=9 August 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nWhen the family moved to the inner west of Sydney, Hastie began his primary education at Ashbury Public School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=A Tale of Two Andrews|last=|first=|date=4 May 2019|website=Unforgiving 60|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> From year 5 he attended [[The Scots College]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=Summer 2015|title=Old Boy News|url=https://www.tsc.nsw.edu.au/hubfs/Lion_and_Lang_Syne_Summer_2015.pdf|journal=The Lion & Lang Syne|volume=26|pages=49|via=}}</ref> in [[Sydney]], completing his [[Higher School Certificate (New South Wales)|Higher School Certificate]] in 2000. Intending to become a journalist, Hastie began a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in History, Politics and Philosophy at the Kensington Campus of [[University of New South Wales]] in 2001, and also joined the [[University of New South Wales Regiment]] as a part-time reservist. At a tutorial near the end of first year, following [[September 11 attacks|11 September terror attacks]] Hastie says he listened to other students argue that the [[United States]] had \u201cdeserved\u201d the attack, which he says he found \u201cbizarre\",<ref name=\"thewest.com.au\">{{Cite web|url=https://thewest.com.au/news/australia/war-has-its-limits-hastie-tells-mps-ng-ya-130555|title=War has its limits, new MP Andrew Hastie tells Parliament|date=14 October 2015|website=The West Australian|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> the event would \"shape the next decade of my life.\"<ref name=\"Hastie\"/><blockquote>I was planning on being a foreign correspondent. 9/11 happened and the daughter of my year 2/3 teacher at Ashbury Public School, she died in one of the towers, I think she was 90 floors up. And so that event, apart from the obvious impact it had on Australia, it came very close to me and my life and I had a tradition of service in my family and thought, you know what, this is a big, historical shift, I want to be part of this.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=unforgiving60|website=unforgiving60|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Hastie with book.jpg|thumb|Lieutenant Andrew Hastie at the rear of his ASLAV Type 1, holding a copy of ''Empire'' by Scottish historian [[Niall Ferguson]].]]\nHastie decided to join the [[Australian Army]] full-time, but completed his second year at the Kensington Campus in 2002 before transferring to the [[University of New South Wales]] at [[Australian Defence Force Academy]] in Canberra in 2003. He completed his bachelor's degree in 2004 before being invited to do an honours year in 2005, his final thesis examined [[Charles Bean]]'s official history of the [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps]]. Hastie still regards himself as a student of history<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yourlocalexaminer.com.au/andrew-hastie-maiden-speech/|title=Hastie sworn in, vows to put Canning people first|last=Hastie|first=Hamish|date=14 October 2015|website=Your Local Examiner|language=en-US|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> and recently wrote the forward to ''Destined for War''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.scribd.com/book/350699416/Destined-for-War-can-America-and-China-escape-Thucydides-Trap|title=Destined for War by Graham Allison and Andrew Hastie - Book - Read Online|language=en}}</ref> an historical survey of global conflicts, beginning with the [[Peloponnesian War]] by [[Graham T. Allison]].\n\nHastie went on to officer training at [[Royal Military College, Duntroon]] in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=260805|title=Mr Andrew Hastie MP|website=www.aph.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> In 2007, Hastie completed the [[George Washington University]] [[Elliott School of International Affairs]]'s U.S. Foreign Policy Summer Program in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\n==Military service (2001\u20132015)==\nWhile at University, Hastie had planned on a part time career in the military, and began officer training with the [[Australian Army Reserve]] in 2001 through the University of New South Wales Regiment.<ref>{{cite web|title=September 11 Australian Stories|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426162732/http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2011/09/08/september-11-australian-stories|website=www.sbs.com.au|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> However, the events of [[9/11]] near the end of that year propelled him towards full-time army service, which he began as a Cadet in 2003. His officer training was completed at Duntroon in 2006, and he was presented with his Commission as Lieutenant from Governor General [[Michael Jeffery]] in December of that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://old.gg.gov.au/program/tuesday-12-december-2006-royal-military-college-australia-duntroon-canberra-their-ex|title=On Tuesday 12 December 2006 at the Royal Military College of Australia, Duntroon, Canberra, Their Ex...|last=Anonymous|date=27 March 2012|website=old.gg.gov.au|language=en|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> His first posting as a young officer was in 2007 with [[2nd Armoured Division (Australia)|2nd Cavalry Regiment]], the second most senior regiment in the [[Royal Australian Armoured Corps]], which he describes as \"the last of the old army.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=The Unforgiving 60 (2019) 3 May 2019, \u201cA Tale of Two Andrews\u201d Season 1, Episode 15a.|last=|first=|date=3 May 2019|website=The Unforgiving 60 (2019)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> At this time the regiment was based with 1st Brigade<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.defence.gov.au/media/media-releases/2nd-cavalry-regiment-arrives-townsville|title=2nd Cavalry Regiment arrives in Townsville|last=Defence|first=Department of|date=9 November 2016|website=news.defence.gov.au|language=en|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> in [[Palmerston, Northern Territory]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army.gov.au/our-people/units/forces-command/1st-brigade/2nd-cavalry-regiment|title=2nd Cavalry Regiment|website=www.army.gov.au|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>. Hastie took command of a cavalry troop in 2008, preparing for deployment in Afghanistan the following year. \n\n=== Afghanistan, 2009-2010 ===\n[[File:Charmestan valley afghanistan.jpg|thumb|MRTF-2 Commanding Officer's Tactical Party, on the edge of the Charmestan, Mirabad Valley, Urozgan Province, Afghanistan.]]\n[[File:Hastie overlooking Chora Valley.jpg|thumb|Andrew Hastie overlooking Chora from his Type I ASLAV.]]\n[[File:Bushmaster Counter IED Lane Tarin Kowt.JPG|thumb|[[Bushmaster Protected Mobility Vehicle]] damaged by [[Improvised explosive device]] attack in [[Tarinkot District|Tarinkot]] in December 2009. Its V-shaped undercarriage design and armour meant that no Australian soldier was wounded.]]\n\nHastie first deployed to Afghanistan with [[Mentoring Task Force One|Mentoring Task Force Two]], a 750-strong Australian combined arms battle group, all under the command of Colonel Peter Connolly. Hastie's role was to commanded a troop of [[ASLAV|Australian Light Armoured Vehicle]]s as it helped to provide \"cover when the Diggers go out on patrol\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/afghanistans-treeless-fields-provide-nowhere-to-hide-20110220-1b14u.html|title=Afghanistan's treeless fields provide nowhere to hide|last=Oakes|first=Dan|date=20 February 2011|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> by using \u201cclose combat to destroy the enemy with precision.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Connolly|first=Peter|title=Counterinsurgency in Uruzgan 2009|publisher=Land Warfare Studies Centre|year=2011|isbn=|location=Canberra|pages=}}</ref> The troop's armoured operations began at the very start of the fighting season in May 2009, concluding in February 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nautilus.org/publications/books/australian-forces-abroad/afghanistan/mentoring-task-force/|title=Mentoring Task Force|date=2011-12-19|website=Nautilus Institute for Security and Sustainability|language=en-US|accessdate=2019-12-18}}</ref> In an extensive report on the mission, known as Operation Falcon's Talon, Hastie's commander, Colonel Peter Connolly said the goal of the Australian forces was \"...to clear and dominate the valley.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Australian forces, including Hastie's, pushed east out of [[Tarinkot District]], up the Mirabad Valley from Charmestan to [[Khas Urozgan District|Khas Urozgan]], all in order to extend the influence of the government of [[Hamid Karzai]], who was seeking re-election in November of that year. The patrols were dangerous and at least four [[List of Australian Defence Force casualties in Afghanistan|Australian soldiers were killed in Afghanistan]] at this time, mostly from attacks by [[improvised explosive device]]s.  Hastie reported \"we had four strikes in my troop alone\u201d though no deaths or wounding, thanks to effective armour.<ref name=\"Development\">{{Cite web|url=https://unforgiving60.podbean.com/e/a-tale-of-two-andrews-%e2%80%93-two-federal-politicians-but-no-politics-andrew-hastie-mp-and-andrew-leigh-mp/|title=S1E15a- A Tale of Two Andrews \u2013 Two Federal Politicians / But No Politics! Andrew Hastie (MP) and Andrew Leigh (MP)|last=Development|first=PodBean|website=unforgiving60.podbean.com|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> Despite the attacks, the series of patrol bases were established through the valley system in [[Urozgan Province]] by December of that year, and the wider operation was considered, in official reports \u2014 at least at this point \u2014 to be a success.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.army.gov.au/Our-future/Publications/Australian-Army-Journal/Past-editions/~/media/Files/Our%20future/LWSC%20Publications/AAJ/2011Winter/02-CounterinsurgencyInUruz.pdf|title=Counterinsurgency in Uruzgan 2009|date=1 July 2010|publisher=The Australian Army|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923174042/http://www.army.gov.au/Our-future/Publications/Australian-Army-Journal/Past-editions/~/media/Files/Our%20future/LWSC%20Publications/AAJ/2011Winter/02-CounterinsurgencyInUruz.pdf|archivedate=23 September 2015|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref> Hastie himself understood the role he and his men performed was part of a wider attempt to reshape Afghanistan:<blockquote>Our job pretty much was the stick. The carrot was the mentoring piece, the aid that was delivered through DFAT, also there at the time and other NGOs. And we were the stick that kept the bad guys back.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|date=December 9, 2016|work=Herald Sun|access-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>\n=== Special Air Service Regiment, 2010-2012 ===\n[[File:Insigne du Special Air Service Regiment (SASR).svg|thumb|Insignia of the Special Air Service Regiment (SASR)]]Hastie successfully applied for entry to the [[Special Air Service Regiment]]\u00a0Selection Course (known simply as \"Selection\"). The process is designed to identify soldiers with diverse backgrounds and strong character as they are able to \u201cgenerate unconventional answers to strategic and tactical problems\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cios.org/EJCPUBLIC/010/1/01013.html|title=Article from ejc/rec|website=www.cios.org|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> as needed for a Tier 1 [[Special forces]] unit. His cohort featured in the SBS documentary ''The Search for Warriors''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/video/11757123841/SAS-The-Search-For-Warriors-S1-Ep1|title=SAS - The Search For Warriors S1 Ep1|website=SBS PopAsia|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> where Hastie has been identified as candidate 10. With the other candidates, Hastie was subjected to extreme exercises, a deliberate system in which, according to the Lieutenant Colonel who had oversight of Hastie's Selection, \u201cwe will break an individual down.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blackfootstudios.com/forums/index.php?/forums/topic/5012-australian-sas-selection-documentary/|title=Australian SAS Selection Documentary|website=BlackFoot Studios|language=en-US|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> Exercises included \u201cLucky Dip\u201d, five days working with teams to move heavy equipment by hand through the bush, with only one meal in that time; and a 150&nbsp;km five-day solo trek across mountainous terrain, which Hastie recalled in interview:<blockquote>\u201cI remember on Selection being up on one of the mountains in the Stirling ranges, being asked, \u201cWhy do you want to be here?\u201d I said, \u201cBecause last time I was in Afghanistan I was driving around getting blown up and I actually want to go after these guys.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=A Tale of Two Andrews|last=|first=|date=3 May 2019|website=Unforgiving 60|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> </blockquote>Hastie's Selection experience concluded with a three-day extreme interrogation session, involving constant sleep deprivation and starvation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/documentary-reveals-gruelling-sas-selection-process/news-story/4488a528d9e0bffd2bc98c43cc2a9350|title=SAS: We will break an individual down|date=6 December 2010|website=NewsComAu|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref>  Men in the group lost between 10 and 15 kilograms from exertion and malnutrition. From Hastie's initial cohort of 131, only 26 completed the course.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/national/2015/08/21/can-pass-sas-test/|title=The most gruelling tests of the SAS|date=21 August 2015|website=The New Daily|language=en-US|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> From there Hastie commenced the 18-month Reinforcement Cycle before receiving qualification with the Regiment, based at [[Campbell Barracks]]. He was issued his \u201csandy beret\u201d in May 2012 and was assigned to 1 SAS Squadron. His first overseas deployment was in Port Moresby to support the [[Papua New Guinea Defence Force]] as they provide security and stability for the General Election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/pm/content/2012/s3523650.htm|title=Australia provides help for PNG elections|date=12 June 2012|website=www.abc.net.au|language=en-AU|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Commanding special forces troop in Afghanistan, 2013  ===\n[[File:Australia\u2019s Special Operations Task Group mentors Provincial Response Company \u2013 Uruzgan 130427-A-FS372-213.jpg|thumb|Australia's Special Operations Task Group was partnered with the local Provincial Police Ready Reaction Auxiliary Force which involved training, support and some joint operations.]]\n\nIn January 2013, Hastie returned to Afghanistan as an SASR officer with Special Operations Task Group Rotation XIX. Hastie told journalist [[Chris Masters (writer)|Chris Masters]] his role was now, \"to protect the base and take the fight to the enemy.\" More widely, the mission was to provide force protection as the ADF mentored the nascent [[Afghan National Security Force]]. Hastie led his troop in operations against hostile [[Taliban]] leadership in southern Afghanistan, commanding B Troop:<blockquote>This meant targeting and taking out the Taliban leadership, helping to support the building of institutions such as schools, and trying to carve out some space for the new Afghan Government to govern.<ref name=\"Whinnett\">{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|date=December 9, 2016|work=Herald Sun|access-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>As part of Task Force 66 (Special Operations Task Groups IV-XX) Hastie's unit was awarded a [[Meritorious Unit Citation]] for \"outstanding service on operations against an unrelenting, cunning and ruthless enemy, in an unforgiving environment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/australia-day-honours-list-2015|title=Australia Day honours list 2015|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref>Little is known about Hastie's actual missions, as special forces exist to deliver \"clandestine, discreet, strategic effects.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/defence/sas-fighting-funds-to-be-increased-by-billions/news-story/b1e1e487970259d213c7c90075ef96e2|title=SAS fighting funds to be increased by billions|last=Packham|first=Ben|date=12 August 2019|website=The Australian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> However, as research by Chris Masters, [[Nick McKenzie]] and [[Ellen Whinnett]] has emerged, we know of five events, which show both the effectiveness of his unit, and the serious limitations of what he later called \"democracy at gunpoint.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|last=Whinnet|first=Whinnett|date=9 December 2016|website=Herald Sun|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==== 1. Joint operation with Wakunish ====\nLargely, SASR operations were about \"going after Taliban commanders and bomb makers\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/95142-big-boys-rules/|title=Big boys\u2019 rules|date=2 July 2018|website=The Mandarin|language=en-US|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>in partnership with local Afghan forces. \"Objective Multiple Spoons\"<ref name=\":3\" /> was the improbable name given to a high value leader who was on the \"Joint Prioritized Effects List.\" The enemy commander was tracked by Hastie's colleagues using an \"array of reconnaissance elements and intelligence platforms\"<ref name=\":3\" /> and was located to an exact position using thermal imaging systems. One SASR operator recalled \"We watched the heat dissipate from his shit in the cold of night.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> Hastie's men deployed to make the capture by Bushmasters, along with a Wakunish force element. These were special-forces-like soldiers from the North of Afghanistan, whom Hastie held in high regard. \"The Wakunish were disciplined. They were tactically proficient. They were sensitive to the populace...\" They encircled the target and attacked at first light, as per their rules of engagement for this context. The entire mission was observed by the commander of all Special Operations Forces for [[International Security Assistance Force]], Brigadeer Bill Dechow, who \"watched on as the Wakunish made entry and captured the senior objective without bloodshed.\" Hastie regarded it as exemplary of the kind of work special forces could achieve, \"surgical and sensitive to locals. We even returned the objective's motorbike to the family.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== 2. Deaths of Toor Jan and Odood ====\n\nIn February 2013, Hastie led a squad of men to support a remote outpost of [[Afghan National Police]] in the [[Deh Rahwod District]]<ref name=\":2\" /> planning to \"supply them with some water, some Red Bull\" and build trust with the local commander.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\" /> While there, the Electronic Warfare Operator received communication intercepts indicating two Taliban fighters, seen at a distance of 1,000 metres, were planning a rocket attack on the post.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\">{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|date=9 December 2016|work=Herald Sun|access-date=9 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Hastie had authority to neutralise the threat, communicated the coordinates for the combatants and called in a strike by a US Army Apache helicopter. However, the attack went badly wrong:<blockquote>I remember looking at the target, and then hearing the guns fire and then the rounds splashing 600m away and thinking, \u2018what the heck, that is not at all, that is not the target.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\"/></blockquote>Two boys, Toor Jan, age 7 and his brother Odood, who were collecting firewood had been mistakenly targeted for the two Taliban figures. An ADF inquiry later cleared Australian forces of any breakdown in procedure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theaustralian.com.au%2Fnation%2Fdefence%2Fandrew-hastie-in-clear-on-second-afghan-incident%2Fnews-story%2Fb91a2ab20fa8ccfe4fb7f1a546b5e7cd&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=9daa57764cfab982111b15402df38b47-1576880157|title=Andrew Hastie in clear on second afghan incident|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref> However, Hastie took responsibilities for the action and met with the grieving family. <blockquote>I said to them, \"I'm the commander; I was the guy who made the decision.\" And I said, \"I'm sorry, if I could take it back I would... and the uncle replied in Pashtun through the interpreter. He sort of nodded and gave me a warm sympathetic smile and said, \"I forgive you.\"<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\" /></blockquote>For Hastie, the death of the boys was both personally affecting and a turning point in his political outlook:<blockquote>I just felt sick... It was arrogant to think we could build a mirror image of ourselves in foreign lands. [The boys\u2019 deaths] underscored the gap between our aims and reality. The two boys who perished were bystanders in this larger struggle. I was humbled and chastened by this experience. War is a miserable enterprise. I remember saying to my boss: \u2018I didn\u2019t come here to kill kids\u2019.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\" /></blockquote>\n\n==== 3. Severed hands ====\nOn 28 April 2013, a major operation began against the senior insurgent commander, Abdul Hai.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Masters|first=Chris|title=No Front Line: Australian special forces at war in Afghanistan|publisher=Allen & Unwin|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=510}}</ref> The attacking force of 120 included \"one Commando and two Provincial Response Company platoons\"<ref name=\":2\" /> led by Hastie's SASR B Troop, which he helped direct from the air. Several combatants were killed in the ensuing battle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=11 July 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref> On searching the dead men, one corporal severed the right hands of two \"Enemy Killed in Action\" using a scalpel. On attempting to do the same to a third EKIA the soldier was stopped by a sergeant who said, \u201cWhat the f*** are you doing?\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=11 July 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref> On arriving at this part of battle environment, Hastie gave the order to cease the practice and the next day the incident was reported to the CO, triggering a major ADF inquiry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=11 July 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> The inquiry heard that there had recently been training on how to collect biometric samples, particularly in managing the aftermath of a suicide bomb event.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Masters|first=Chris|title=No Front Line|publisher=Allen & Unwin|year=2017|isbn=9781760111144|location=Australia|pages=505}}</ref> Hastie later commented that \u201cthe guy giving instructions conflated site exploitation of a suicide bomber with that of biometric testing.\" The SASR corporal who severed the hands later conceded he had made an error of judgement in not first checking with his patrol commander.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|website=mobile.abc.net.au|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> The inquiry made it clear that the practice, and the fact that some appeared to accept it at the time, \"demonstrated a drift in values, or at least a degree of desensitisation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=11 July 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== 4. Suicide bomber capture ====\nIntelligence gathering operations constantly scanned for \"chatter\" on plans for suicide bombings by the Taliban. To interdict these operations, Hastie was required to work with local forces, however by May 2013 the Wakunish were now working independently,<ref name=\":2\" /> so Australia's forces need to work with the Provincial Response Company<ref name=\":2\" /> with whom they had few shared values. One of the first missions with the PRC was to capture a suicide bomber in [[Urozgan Province|Urozgan]] before he had the opportunity to attack. The operation was conducted in darkness \"When they found the suicide bomber they were chasing, a barrel pressed against his temple was used to ease the man awake.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> Now the enemy was secure, along with his explosive vest, and rockets, the PRC commanders, and their own magistrate, had a stand off with Hastie \u2014 insisting that they should execute the captured man.<ref name=\":2\" /> The \"person under confinement\" was escorted to prison by Hastie and his team. \n\n==== 5. Truck bomb ====\nHastie's B Company received intelligence of a Taliban plan to use a truck to enter their own [[Forward operating base]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The order was given for all personnel to put on armour and helmets if they were moving outside of secure buildings. An airstrike was considered once the exact location of the bomber was found, however, it was decided to neutralise the threat using Hastie's unit, on the ground. The force element was flown in on two Australian [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk|Black Hawk]]<nowiki/>s<ref name=\":2\" /> the bomber located and killed, and the team extracted. From wheels down to wheels up had taken 22 minutes. There were no force injuries or casualties. For Hastie:<blockquote>It was the SOTG machine at its most efficient and precise. When we got back and the order was given to all on base that they could take off the body armour and helmets when outside there was a sigh of relief. There was no doubt about that mission. We were protecting the base from attack. We just thought of Aussie diggers, aid workers, [[Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (Australia)|DFAT]] and everyone else supporting us behind the wire. I went to the gym and later enjoyed a deep and peaceful sleep.<ref name=\":2\" /></blockquote>\n\n=== Jordan and Afghanistan, 2014-2015 ===\nHastie deployed in late-2014 and 2015 to an intelligence role<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/analysis-andrew-hastie-chau-chak-wing-complex-situation/9795766|title=Here's why Andrew Hastie named Chau Chak Wing in Parliament|last=Editor|first=Political|last2=Probyn|first2=rew|date=24 May 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> in the Middle East-based role countering [[ISIL]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-08-21/hastie-liberal-candidate-keogh-alp-canning-byelection/6713986|title=Andrew Hastie to run for Liberals, Matt Keogh for ALP in Canning by-election|date=20 August 2015|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref> as an Operations Officer for Operation Gallant Phoenix,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unforgiving60.podbean.com/e/a-tale-of-two-andrews-%e2%80%93-two-federal-politicians-but-no-politics-andrew-hastie-mp-and-andrew-leigh-mp/|title=S1E15a- A Tale of Two Andrews \u2013 Two Federal Politicians / But No Politics! Andrew Hastie (MP) and Andrew Leigh (MP)|last=Development|first=PodBean|website=unforgiving60.podbean.com|language=en|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref> a classified defence operation based in Jordan. The operation is said to be collecting intelligence \"from commando raids in Syria and Iraq and funnelling it to law enforcement agencies in Europe and Southeast Asia to help stop future attacks.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Schmitt|first=Eric|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/24/us/politics/us-isis-fight.html|title=Its Territory May Be Gone, but the U.S. Fight Against ISIS Is Far From Over|date=24 March 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=24 March 2020|last2=Gibbons-Neff|first2=Thomas|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Cooper|first3=Helene|last4=Rubin|first4=Alissa J.}}</ref> \n\nBy mid 2013, Hastie had returned home to Perth. With his time in the SASR he felt he had achieved \"the peak of soldiering\"<ref name=\":2\" /> but had been frustrated at \"the absence of strategy\"<ref name=\":2\" /> which could only come from government. \"We were hidebound by policy that compromised military principle. We were planning who we took out on the ground before we planned the mission.\u2019<ref name=\":2\" /> Hastie joined the [[Liberal Party of Australia]] shortly after his return. He resigned his commission from the ADF in August 2015 after announcing his candidature to run as the Member for Canning in the House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/andrew-hastie-liberal-byelection-candidate-led-troop-probed-for-chopping-hands-off-taliban-20150821-gj52lj.html|title=Andrew Hastie, Liberal byelection candidate, was in charge of troop probed for chopping hands off Taliban|date=22 August 2015|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Political career (2015\u2013present)==\n\n=== Election and first Turnbull Government ===\nThe seat of [[Division of Canning|Canning]] became vacant by the death in office of the Liberal member, [[Don Randall]], triggering the [[2015 Canning by-election]]. Hastie began a launched his campaign with strong support from [[Mathias Cormann]] and [[Julie Bishop]], however he was quickly inundated with media criticism about the \"severed hands\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2015/08/australia-election-dictate-pm-fate-150830103706951.html|title=Australia by-election could dictate PM's fate|last=Kurmelovs|first=Royce|website=www.aljazeera.com|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> incident and was further \"rattled\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/creationism-rattles-cannings-newchum-politician-20150911-gjk0o8.html|title=Creationism rattles Canning's new-chum politician|last=Murphy|first=Damien|date=11 September 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> by strong questioning of his family's religious beliefs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/creationism-rattles-cannings-newchum-politician-20150911-gjk0o8.html|title=Creationism rattles Canning's new-chum politician|last=Murphy|first=Damien|date=11 September 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> Within days Hastie would give a speech in which he strongly defended the soldiers under his command and his own military service:<blockquote>I have not lived my life behind a desk pushing paper and talking about the concepts of freedom and democracy. I have acted. I have put my life on the line for this country and for that freedom.<ref name=\":6\" /></blockquote>On Saturday 19 September 2015, after a four-week campaign that centred on solving the [[methamphetamine]] epidemic, Hastie won 55.26% of votes under the [[Two-party-preferred vote|two-party-preferred]] system, making him the 10th Federal Member for Canning, defeating Labor candidate [[Matt Keogh]]. He joined the government of [[Malcolm Turnbull]] who had himself become [[Prime Minister of Australia]] a week before the by-election. Hastie gave his first speech on 13 October 2015, which centred on his priorities for healthy democracy, stronger community institutions and for defending Australia's sovereignty, \"To safeguard our freedom I believe that the first duty of the Australian federal government is to secure our nation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b1239e0c-7fca-43e4-aac5-25ac64e2bc96/0128%22|title=ParlInfo - BUSINESS : Rearrangement|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> In the first months, when headlines were dominated by the [[2015 Parramatta shooting|Parramatta shooting]] and the [[November 2015 Paris attacks|Paris terror attack]] and the aftermath of the [[2014 Sydney hostage crisis|Sydney hostage crisis]], it seemed that Hastie's parliamentary career would be marked by his concern<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/asio-chief-called-just-two-coalition-mps-about-islam-debate-malcolm-turnbull-20151218-glr0js.html|title=ASIO chief called just two Coalition MPs about Islam debate: Malcolm Turnbull|last=Kenny|first=David Wroe and Mark|date=18 December 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> about \"radical islamist ideology\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Alberici|first=Emma|title=Interview: Andrew Hastie, Liberal MP|date=31 May 2017|url=https://www.abc.net.au/lateline/interview:-andrew-hastie,-liberal-mp/8577672|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|language=en-AU|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> arguing in interviews<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.2gb.com/podcast/alan-jones-andrew-hastie/|title=Alan Jones \u2013 Andrew Hastie|date=1 December 2015|website=2GB|language=en|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> and op eds that: <blockquote>I have read the Koran in its entirety. In my previous job with the Australian Defence Force, I studied Islamic State propaganda including many of its violent videos and images in an effort to understand their objectives, aims and rationale. I was disturbed by what I saw, but not cowed into inaction.... we should be free to question the roots of Islamic terrorism, especially the brand pushed by Islamic State. It is troubling that we have had young Australians sympathising with the theology and ideology of Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=AAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.adelaidenow.com.au%2Fnews%2Fopinion%2Fwe-should-be-free-to-question-the-roots-of-islamic-terrorism-especially-the-brand-pushed-by-islamic-state-writes-andrew-hastie%2Fnews-story%2F81bc06145842d58af1c980edb20d0b42&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=3290dea7434c4d3e6d98e6f90da327e0-1586142284|title=Adelaidenow.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to The Advertiser for exclusive stories|website=www.adelaidenow.com.au|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Re-election and second Turnbull Government ===\nHastie stood again for the division of Canning<ref> name=\"foo\" /ref> for the [[2016 Australian federal election]], on Saturday 2 July. He won 56.79% of the votes under the [[Two-party-preferred vote]] against Labor opposition candidate Barry Winmar, moving his seat from being \"marginal\" to \"fairly safe\" according to the [[Australian Electoral Commission]].{{cn|date=March 2020}} He was appointed to the [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]] [[File:Andrew Hastie MP, Chair of the Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security with Deputy Chair Anthony Byrne MP in February 2020 photo taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|Anthony Byrne, a Labor MP and Deputy Chair of the Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security with its Chair, Andrew Hastie MP. ]]in September 2016, and invited to chair the committee from February 2017.<ref>http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22chamber%2Fhansardr%2F9de5f081-9ccf-4f72-a05a-02462c1f3a0c%2F0136%22 Retrieved 15 June 2017</ref> It's known the committee receives briefings from [[Inspector-General of Intelligence and Security (Australia)]], [[Australian Signals Directorate]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/plans-to-boost-electronic-spy-agency-meet-with-extreme-caution-20190615-p51y1o.html|title=Plans to boost electronic spy agency meet with extreme caution|last=Ireland|first=David Wroe, Judith|date=15 June 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref> and [[Australian Security Intelligence Organisation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itnews.com.au/news/four-hour-top-secret-briefing-used-to-press-encryption-law-need-516084|title=Four hour 'top secret' briefing used to press encryption law need|website=iTnews|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref> As such, Hastie and fellow members of the [[bi-partisan]] committee are \"privy to a lot of information and intelligence briefings that other members of parliament aren't.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skynews.com.au/details/_6070077627001|title='We can't deny there are problems with China's behaviour': Dutton|website=Sky News Australia|language=|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref> Through his work with the PJCIS Hastie came to conclude that Australia is \"facing an unprecedented threat from espionage and foreign interference, and that current laws are not adequate to deal with this threat.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/foreign-interference-laws-needed-before-super-saturday-vote-christian-porter-says-20180607-h113o9|title=Foreign interference laws needed before super Saturday vote, Christian Porter says|date=7 June 2018|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> At this point the source of the foreign interference was unnamed. Following its deliberations, the committee reviewed and amended the [https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2018C00506 Espionage and Foreign Interference Act 2018]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defence.gov.au/dsvs/industry/DISP-foreign-espionage.asp|title=Foreign Espionage & Interference Act 2018 : Industry Security Program : Department of Defence|last=|website=www.defence.gov.au|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> and [https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2018A00029 Security of Critical Infrastructure Act 2018]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/about-us/our-portfolios/national-security/security-coordination/security-of-critical-infrastructure-act-2018|title=Security of Critical Infrastructure Act 2018|website=www.homeaffairs.gov.au|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== First Morrison Government ===\n[[File:Andrew Hastie and daughter (KN).jpg|thumb|In Parliamentary offices, Andrew Hastie plays with his daughter. ]]\nIn August 2018, Malcolm Turnbull called for two [[2018 Liberal Party of Australia leadership spills|leadership spills]], in which Hastie is known to have supported the call for a new leader.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-24/the-liberal-mps-that-sparked-the-spill/10161660|title=The 43 Liberal MPs that brought down Malcolm Turnbull|date=24 August 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref> [[Scott Morrison]] was elected leader of the Liberal Party, becoming [[Prime Minister of Australia]]. Hastie maintained his chairmanship of the PJCIS as it took an increasingly serious tone on foreign threats. The committee carried the Assistance and Access Bill 2018 through to legislation enabling security agencies to access otherwise encrypted communications by people who intend harm to Australians. Prompted by the sale of the Port of [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] to interests connected to the Communist Party of China, the Committee made recommendations for the Security of Critical Infrastructure Act 2018 (Cth) (Act)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://corrs.com.au/insights/critical-infrastructure-reporting-starts-now|title=Critical infrastructure: reporting starts now|website=Corrs Chambers Westgarth|language=en|access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref> \u2014 placing a national security test to any foreign investment into energy or water assets and, notably, ports. The committee also contributed amendments to the Foreign Influence Transparency Scheme Act 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ag.gov.au/Integrity/foreign-influence-transparency-scheme/Pages/default.aspx|title=Foreign Influence Transparency Scheme|last=Department|first=Attorney-Generals's|website=www.ag.gov.au|language=en-au|access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn his constituency work, Hastie surprised some by giving public support to striking [[Alcoa Australia]] workers, organised by the [[Australian Workers' Union]]. Hastie said, he supported the strikers because, \"energy production in Australia is too expensive and it is hurting industry, workers, seniors and families. We have to put Australians first. Otherwise, more jobs will go offshore to other countries. Our smelters and refineries will close down. Energy security is job security.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/opinion/andrew-hastie-utility-bills-are-crippling-workingclass-families/news-story/d2890e742284107f09917bfcbfd78a08|title=Utility bills are crippling working-class families|date=23 November 2018|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=9 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Re-election and second Morrison Government ===\n[[File:AH and PM at Mandurah War Memorial (KN).jpg|thumb|Prime Minister Scott Morrison and Andrew Hastie MP stand by ANZAC wreaths at a memorial in Mandurah.]]\nIn the [[2019 Australian federal election]], held on 18 May, Hastie ran for re-election and won 61.83% of the [[two-party-preferred vote]] against the Australian Labor Party's candidate Mellisa Teede. On entering the [[46th Parliament of Australia]] Hastie, in which [[Scott Morrison]] was returned as Prime Minister, Hastie become increasingly involved in lawmaking around matters of national security. He spoke in 45 debates in 2019, above average according to Open Australia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openaustralia.org.au/mp/andrew_hastie/canning|title=Andrew Hastie MP, Canning (OpenAustralia.org)|website=www.openaustralia.org.au|access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref> the bulk of them surrounding matters of security or sovereignty.  [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]] pushed forward the Temporary Exclusion Orders Bill designed to prevent dual-national terrorists from returning to Australia. [[File:Andrew Hastie MP with flag gifted to him by SASR operators January 2020 photo taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|Andrew Hastie in his electoral office in Mandurah, with an Australian flag given to him by a friend in the ADF, it had once flown at a army forward operating base]]However, the Identity-matching Services Bill 2019 and the Australian Passports Amendment (Identity-matching Services) Bill 2019 were reviewed by the committee and sent back for redrafting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/facial-recognition-bill-knocked-back-20191024-p533s6|title=Facial recognition bill knocked back|date=23 October 2019|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref> By 2020, Hastie was able to review the suite of legislative changes security as being all of one piece, to strengthen Australia's position in the region and the world:<blockquote>What we\u2019ve done in Australia over the last three or four years, I call it our pivot... taking action to preserve our digital sovereignty by excluding high-risk vendors from our future 5G network, passing the Espionage and Foreign Interference Laws, stopping the extradition treaty to China, those things were part of the pivot and ultimately, they\u2019re expressions of our sovereignty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/5792-insight-australia-s-relationship-with-china-andrew-hastie-mp|title=INSIGHT: Australia\u2019s relationship with China \u2013 Andrew Hastie MP|last=Levy|first=Tasha|last2=Levy|first2=Tasha|date=19 March 2020|website=www.defenceconnect.com.au|language=en|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\u00a0 </blockquote>\n\n==== \"We Must See China with Clear Eyes\" ====\n[[File:Joint media release Hastie Paterson November 15 2019.jpg|alt=A media release from Andrew Hastie MP and Senator James Paterson.|thumb|Hastie and James Paterson confirm they have been blocked from visiting China following their public comments about the [[Communist Party of China]]]]\nIn August 2019 Hastie wrote an [[Op-ed]] column, \"We Must See China with Clear Eyes\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=7 August 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> for ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' and ''[[The Age]]'' newspapers<ref name=\"Hastie\"/>, where he admitted that Communist China \u2014 rather than [[Islamic terrorism]], which he worked to defeat in his military career \u2014 would be the real security concern of the 21st Century. Moreover, a rising, revisionist, expansionist China would frame \"almost every strategic and economic question facing Australia in the coming decades.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=7 August 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>  What brought more attention was his strong criticism of Western democracies and their mistaken belief \"that economic liberalisation would naturally lead to democratisation in China\" much as the French had believed the [[Maginot Line]] would guard them against the German advance in 1940. Hastie wrote, \"Like the French, Australia has failed to see how mobile our authoritarian neighbour has become.\"<ref name=\":01\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last1=Hastie|first1=Andrew|date=8 August 2019|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> The piece caused \"a firestorm\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-s-awakening-to-xi-s-bid-for-total-control-of-china-and-beyond-20190809-p52for.html|title=Hastie's awakening to Xi's bid for total control of China - and beyond|last=Hartcher|first=Peter|date=9 August 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> with the [[Embassy of China, Canberra|Chinese Embassy in Australia]] denouncing the remarks as reflecting a \"[[Cold war (general term)|Cold War]] mentality\",<ref name=\":11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-08/chinese-officials-slam-andrew-hastie-nazi-beijing-china-comments/11395980|title=Liberal MP Andrew Hastie condemned by China after comparing Beijing's rise to threat from Nazi Germany|last1=Laschon|first1=Eliza|date=8 August 2019|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> while Western Australian Premier [[Mark McGowan]], whose state is heavily reliant on China for trade,<ref name=\"abcaunazi\">{{cite news|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-09/wa-particularly-vulnerable-in-a-china-us-trade-war/11395926|title=Western Australia's huge reliance on China leaves it particularly vulnerable in a trade war|last1=O'Flaherty|first1=Alisha|date=10 August 2019|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> accusing Hastie of \"threatening WA jobs with extreme and inflammatory language.\"<ref name=\"abcaunazi\" /> An academic at UWA opined that the Western Australian government's contemporaneous relationship with China may not be sustainable in the future, saying \"But there may come a time where this relationship is not possible to be run purely on commercial lines, and I have to say most of the reason for that is the changing behaviour of the Chinese Communist Party.\"<ref name=\"abcaunazi\" /> Conversely, Hastie received support from his colleagues [[Dave Sharma]]<ref name=\":21\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-wins-support-for-his-china-warning-from-former-diplomat-sharma-20190810-p52fup.html|title=Hastie wins support for his China warning from former diplomat Sharma|last1=Wright|first1=Shane|date=10 August 2019|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> and [[Peter Dutton]].<ref name=\":31\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/no-point-pretending-there-s-nothing-to-see-here-peter-dutton-warns-on-china-20190809-p52fgz.html|title='No point pretending there's nothing to see here': Peter Dutton warns on China|last1=Shields|first1=Bevan|date=9 August 2019|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> Hastie had been invited on a study trip with several colleagues to China with the independent think tank China Matters. However the Chinese embassy announced \u201cthat at this time Mr Hastie and Senator Paterson are not welcome\" unless they \"genuinely repent and redress their mistakes.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/nov/15/china-denies-entry-to-liberal-mps-andrew-hastie-and-james-paterson|title=China denies entry to Liberal MPs Andrew Hastie and James Paterson|last=editor|first=Katharine Murphy Political|date=15 November 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=18 December 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> This snub had the effect of making [[Communist Party of China]] attempts to control the behaviour and speech of people in sovereign nations an even bigger concern. Hastie's warnings about Chinese abuses of human rights and interference with sovereign nations appeared to be vindicated when newspapers released 400 pages of Chinese documents<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/16/world/asia/china-xinjiang-documents.html|title='Absolutely No Mercy': Leaked Files Expose How China Organized Mass Detentions of Muslims|last=Ramzy|first=Austin|date=16 November 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=18 December 2019|last2=Buckley|first2=Chris|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> on the workings of internment camps in [[Xinjiang]], shortly followed by the apparent defection of a young Chinese spy with information in connection with a Chinese Australian, Nick Zhao<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-25/chinese-spy-parliament-foreign-interference-in-hong-kong-taiwan/11735176|title=A man is dead. Another fears being killed. Here's a breakdown of the claims about Chinese espionage|last=Conifer|first=Dan|date=25 November 2019|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> who was funded by Chinese interests to run for parliament, and was later found dead in a hotel room. By raising concerns about foreign interference, the opinion piece has been seen as a \"threshold\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-s-awakening-to-xi-s-bid-for-total-control-of-china-and-beyond-20190809-p52for.html|title=Hastie's awakening to Xi's bid for total control of China - and beyond|last=Hartcher|first=Peter|date=9 August 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref>, with other commentators predicting that Hastie's concerns \"will dominate the political agenda\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/ellen-whinnett-china-crisis-looms-large-in-canberra/news-story/66c19d19acafcbaa2a914fabe17b23d5|title=China crisis looms large in Canberra|date=4 December 2019|work=Herald Sun|access-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>, having been discussed in the pages of global newspapers such as ''[[Haaretz]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/.premium-a-dead-spy-chinese-hackers-and-the-australian-commando-warning-israel-1.8223349|title=A Dead Spy, Chinese Hackers and the Australian Commando Warning Israel|last=Melman|first=Yossi|date=6 December 2019|website=haaretz.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref>  ''[[The Times]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/beijing-denies-australian-mps-right-to-visit-china-bldtfvl2j|title=Beijing denies Australian MPs right to visit China|last=Times|first=Bernard Lagan, Sydney {{!}} The|access-date=18 December 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> and ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/28/world/australia/china-spying-wang-liqiang-nick-zhao.html|title=Suddenly, the Chinese Threat to Australia Seems Very Real|last=Cave|first=Damien|date=28 November 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=18 December 2019|last2=Tarabay|first2=Jamie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nHastie has been described as a \"conservative\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/ruthless-hardline-and-focused-the-mp-who-stunned-parliament-20180525-p4zhgy.html|title='Ruthless, hardline and focused': The MP who stunned Parliament|last=Wright|first=Tony|date=25 May 2018|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>, a \"social conservative\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wahlquist|first=Calla|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/sep/08/canning-byelection-the-complete-and-completely-unofficial-guide-to-the-candidates|title=Canning byelection: the complete (and completely unofficial) guide to the candidates|date=7 September 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=31 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and, at least by the official Chinese government media as \"an arch-conservative\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/21/c_137406904.htm|title=News Analysis: Aussie gov't set for period of upheaval following leadership challenge to PM - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>. Critics see his foreign policy outlook as being \"jingoistic\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1161600.shtml|title=Australia need not follow US script on its relationship with China - Global Times|website=www.globaltimes.cn|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> and the MP himself as \"a notorious hawk.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/08/andrew-hasties-nazi-germany-warning-on-china-labelled-extreme-and-unwelcome|title=China denounces Liberal MP Andrew Hastie's Nazi Germany analogy|date=8 August 2019|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Hastie himself has said, \"I am not a libertarian, but I am a Liberal, which is to say that I am committed to freedom.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/blogs/andrew-bolt/andrew-hastie-shames-the-free-speech-quislings/news-story/1f81333ae068f76e98ca8b311effcc1d|title=Andrew Hastie Shames the Free Speech Quislings|last=Bolt|first=Andrew|date=3 March 2017|website=Herald Sun|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> This would appear to be confirmed by his decision to join the [[Atlantic Council]] \u2014 a [[Classical liberalism|Classical liberal]] bi-partisan think tank formed for \"defending democratic values.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/cbd-melbourne-hockey-ready-to-ride-post-virus-bondi-wave-20200325-p54dw1.html|title=CBD Melbourne: Hockey ready to ride post-virus Bondi wave|last=Loussikian|first=Samantha Hutchinson, Kylar|date=25 March 2020|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> The invitation<ref name=\":5\" /> came via US Congressman [[Mike Gallagher (American politician)|Mike Gallagher]], a conservative [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and [[Tom Tugendhat]], a British MP who describes himself as a \"community conservative.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smf.co.uk/tom-tugendhat-speech-2018/|title=Tom Tugendhat MP's speech for the SMF|date=8 November 2018|website=Social Market Foundation|language=en-CA|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> [[File:Soldiers cross a foot bridge in the Mirabad Valley.jpg|thumb|A footbridge in the Mirabad Valley, in [[Urozgan Province]], built by [[Australian Defence Force|ADF]] engineers, being patrolled by a member of the [[Afghan National Army]], followed by an Australian soldier from the [[Mentoring Task Force One|Mentoring Task Force]] in February 2010. ]] His outlook, unsurprisingly, has been shaped by his experience of war:<blockquote>I take my time in Afghanistan, especially in my first deployment, particularly my time with [[Mentoring Task Force One|MRTF2]] with the [[1st Battalion, Royal Australian Regiment|1RAR]] battle group, as being very formative for me, doing [[Nation Building - Afghanistan|Nation Building]] and realising the limitations of government to change people and their culture. We built bridges, we built a bazaar where we expected people to trade, we built schools and hospitals, we built all sorts of things, but fundamentally, we didn\u2019t change the way the Afghan people lived. Respecting people\u2019s sovereignty, and people\u2019s freedom to live as they choose is something that I learned over there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/5792-insight-australia-s-relationship-with-china-andrew-hastie-mp|title=INSIGHT: Australia\u2019s relationship with China \u2013 Andrew Hastie MP|last=Levy|first=Tasha|last2=Levy|first2=Tasha|date=19 March 2020|website=www.defenceconnect.com.au|language=en|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Hastie giving crayons to children op takht.jpg|thumb|Lieutenant Hastie distributing crayons to Afghan children in Oruzghan]]This experience seems to have made Hastie sceptical of [[Neoliberalism]], saying, \"I am now far more circumspect about the ability of military power to change people and societies, and far more aware of how resilient culture can be.\"<ref name=\"thewest.com.au\" /> By the same measure, Hastie is diffident towards [[Neoconservatism]], especially in its [[Laissez-faire]] tendencies, which he finds unacceptable because, \"despite the benefits of globalisation, there are always losers in the transfer of labour and capital offshore. Loss of identity through vocational irrelevance is a real anxiety in communities that prize skilled labour.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/opinion/political-class-ignored-the-people-and-paid-the-price/news-story/f1d35ad7c29f76daf08768182b316d55|title=Political Class Ignored the People and Paid the Price|date=23 November 2020|work=The Australian|access-date=30 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  Hastie's high view of  sovereignty and his desire to protect local people and their industries from global forces<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/may/26/andrew-hasties-contribution-to-our-china-effort-curious-and-curiouser|title=Andrew Hastie's contribution to our China effort? Curious and curiouser {{!}} Katharine Murphy|last=Murphy|first=Katharine|date=25 May 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=18 December 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> would places him in the tradition of [[National liberalism]]. Recently Ben Pronk and Tim Curtis (both former SAS officers, Pronk had been Hastie's commanding officer) asked Hastie for his vision for Australia. His off the cuff answer was: <blockquote>I hope to see a country where families are strong. Where we've incentivised families through the policies that we've legislated. I hope to see a strong defence force so that we can weather the challenges that will inevitably come. If you take history as a guide we will face inevitable security challenges. I hope that we are aware of our history, that we haven't cut the mooring that is our civilisation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=A Tale of Two Andrews|last=|first=|date=|website=Unforgiving 60|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref></blockquote>This statement contains three threads that are seen in almost all of Hastie's writing and remarks. First, a passion \"to defend the rule of law, democracy and the constituent freedoms\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Greg|first=Brown|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/rivals-unite-for-the-sake-of-democracy/news-story/455c76fe549eda7c318a6a496985b811|title=Rivals unite for the sake of democracy|date=13 July 2020|work=The Australian|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>. Second, a believe that \"Sovereignty, where compromised, must be recovered and protected.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/challenge-to-democracy-to-counter-russia-china-20191204-p53gzj.html|title=Challenge to democracy to counter Russia, China|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=9 December 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Third, that community or local institutions \"should define the character and activity of our nation from the ground up.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;db=CHAMBER;id=chamber/hansardr/e5ff85d2-b96e-4e0e-8227-2131e40beaf7/0200;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/e5ff85d2-b96e-4e0e-8227-2131e40beaf7/0049%22|title=ParlInfo - ADJOURNMENT : 45th Parliament|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Democracy ===\nOne [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC]] profile on Hastie found that \"the heart of his worldview is the belief that everyone is equal and has dignity\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382?pfmredir=sm&sf75079731=1&smid=Page:+ABC+News-Facebook_Organic&WT.tsrc=Facebook_Organic|title=Keeping the faith: Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|website=mobile.abc.net.au|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> and from here his convictions about democracy emanate. The belief in the inherent value of the individual means the individual must be free when it comes to \"thought, worship, speech, association and choice\" as Hastie said in his first speech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b1239e0c-7fca-43e4-aac5-25ac64e2bc96/0128%22|title=First Speech|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=13 October 2015|website=Parliament of Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> These freedoms allow our communities to naturally form and \"are the fullest expression of self-government.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/first_speech|title=First Speech|website=Andrew Hastie MP|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> Hastie recently collaborated with the [[Australian Labor Party]]'s [[Kimberley Kitching]] to form the \"Parliamentary Friends of Democracy.\" It comes out of a concern that democratic institutions are \"under increasing pressure around the globe.\" They believe, \"Australian parliamentarians have a duty to rise above party to defend the rule of law, democracy and the constituent freedoms that make Australia a special place to live.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theaustralian.com.au%2Fnation%2Fpolitics%2Frivals-unite-for-the-sake-of-democracy%2Fnews-story%2F455c76fe549eda7c318a6a496985b811&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=e77fa5e4fbb81da52eba770ee8c0a8a7-1576685699|title=Subscribe to The Australian {{!}} Newspaper home delivery, website, iPad, iPhone & Android apps|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> This view expands on concerns that Hastie has expressed elsewhere, that \"our greatest vulnerability lies not in our infrastructure, but in our thinking. That intellectual failure makes us institutionally weak. If we don't understand the challenge ahead for our civil society, in our parliaments, in our universities, in our private enterprises, in our charities \u2014 our little platoons \u2014 then choices will be made for us. Our sovereignty, our freedoms, will be diminished.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-08/chinese-officials-slam-andrew-hastie-nazi-beijing-china-comments/11395980|title=Embassy condemns MP Hastie for comparing China's rise to threat from Nazi Germany|last=Laschon|first=political reporter Eliza|date=8 August 2019|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> In February 2020 it was announced that Hastie had been invited to serve on a panel of western leaders who are concerned for the state of global democracy, the Commission on Advancing a Free World, in association with [[Atlantic Council|The Atlantic Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/news/press-releases/free-world-commission-of-legislators-from-leading-democracies-launched-at-munich-security-conference/|title=Free World Commission of legislators from leading democracies launched at Munich Security Conference|date=16 February 2020|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref> Their ''Declaration of Principles for Freedom, Prosperity, and Peace''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/declaration/|title=Declaration of Principles for Freedom, Prosperity, and Peace|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> articulates seven statements for protecting democracy across the world, beginning with \"the right of all people to live in free and just societies, where fundamental rights are protected under the rule of law.\"\n\n==== Freedom of thought - on marriage ====\nHastie saw the 2016 [[Same-sex marriage in Australia|Same-sex marriage debate in Australia]] as a conscience issue.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/opinion/marriage-is-peoples-institution-so-they-should-decide-its-future/news-story/a6ace55c388f0f5e3c7484f8738aefe6|title=Marriage is people's institution, so they should decide its future|date=20 September 2016|work=|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  He supported the postal survey because he believed that the institution of marriage, since it existed before the parliament, was an institution that \"belongs to the people\" so it was right for the people themselves to vote on it.<ref name=\":4\" /> When the \"yes vote\" was strongly returned, Hastie ensured passage of the bill, but could not vote for it himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-11-15/wa-politicians-to-ignore-same-sex-marriage-result/9154656|title=Prominent No campaigner to abstain from same-sex marriage vote|date=15 November 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> He explained, \"We went to the election with it, I was on television saying I would abstain, I've been in dialogue with constituents for the last 18 months and whenever I've talked to them about the issue, I've said I would abstain. My intention is to abstain because to vote yes would go against my conscience, but I want to uphold both the vote in Canning and the national result and abstention is the best way to do that.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/5058727/hastie-to-abstain-on-yes-vote/|title=Hastie to abstain on 'yes' vote|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=15 November 2017|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> Most of Hastie's statements through the public debate centred not on marriage, but on how to have the debate. When right wing commentators such as Larry Pickering used homophobic language towards [[LGBT]] persons, Hastie immediately condemned the statement, expressing his \"dismay\" at the degrading language, and pleaded for \"higher personal and civic standards\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/pickering-comments-despicable-hastie|title=Pickering comments despicable: Hastie|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of conscience - on military abuses ====\nRecent reports by Chris Masters and others of prisoner abuse, and even killings, by the Australian [[Special Air Service Regiment]] in Afghanistan have seen Hastie come forward as a strong advocate for transparency, though it may hurt the prestige of his former unit. He has \"emerged as a champion of the Brereton Inquiry.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/he-thought-i-was-going-to-shoot-him-how-david-s-little-voice-saved-him-in-war-20190913-p52qy6.html|title='He thought I was going to shoot him': How David's 'little voice' saved him in war|last=Masters|first=Nick McKenzie, Chris|date=20 September 2019|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> He strongly supports whistleblowers when it comes to abuse, telling ABC Radio the truth tellers should be respected: \"I don't want to go into any specific allegations, but they should be taken seriously and, as I said, we want a free media reporting on all issues.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/federal/secretive-and-elite-sas-soldiers-grilled-about-alleged-war-crimes-20180608-p4zkau.html|title=Secretive and elite SAS soldiers grilled about alleged war crimes|last=Wroe|first=Nick McKenzie, David|date=8 June 2018|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of expression ====\nIn one of Hastie's first electoral campaigns, he had a large outdoor poster vandalised. Rather than condemn the culprit, he wrote a Facebook message, \"Will Mandurah's Van Gogh please come forward<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/3985723/hasties-spray-mp-responds-to-graffiti-attack/|title=Hastie's spray: MP responds to graffiti attack|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=2016-06-22|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> then had a local graffiti artist add even more colour to the piece. However, when a campaign bus was torched, Hastie drew a firm line, calling them, \"cowards using Taliban tactics in the dead of night\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watoday.com.au/federal-election-2019/andrew-hastie-s-campaign-bus-survives-dead-of-night-arson-attack-20190420-p51fr4.html|title=Andrew Hastie's campaign bus survives 'dead of night' arson attack|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=19 April 2019|website=WAtoday|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> Hastie encourages debate and dissension, especially in classroom settings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/4488661/students-get-political-during-hastie-visit/|title=Students get political during Hastie visit|last=Cockerill|first=Jess|date=23 February 2017|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of press ====\nHastie is currently having difficulty balancing freedoms when it comes to the media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themonthly.com.au/today/paddy-manning/2019/23/2019/1563861108/joint-pain|title=Joint pain|last=paddym@schwartzmedia.com.au1516749970|date=23 July 2019|website=The Monthly|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> He has actively stood up for journalists at the ABC and [[Sydney morning Herald|Sydney Morning Herald]], using Parliamentary privilege to name Chau Chak Wing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-23/turnbull-did-not-know-hastie-would-make-chau-chak-wing-claims/9790476|title=Liberal MP says he did his duty in speaking up about political donor|last=Yaxley|first=political reporters Louise|last2=Gribbin|first2=Caitlyn|date=23 May 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=31 March 2020|last3=Conifer|first3=Dan}}</ref> as a man who co-conspired to bribe a UN official, a man who took the media outlets to court for defamation as they had published the accusations. Hastie explained his actions by saying \"...democracy works only if we have a free press that can publish information that serves the public interest.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-23/turnbull-did-not-know-hastie-would-make-chau-chak-wing-claims/9790476|title=Liberal MP says he did his duty in speaking up about political donor|last=Yaxley|first=political reporters Louise|last2=Gribbin|first2=Caitlyn|date=23 May 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=18 December 2019|last3=Conifer|first3=Dan}}</ref> However, current laws have allowed for the Australian Federal Police to raid journalists from the ABC and News Corp Australia for reasons of security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-07-15/abc-raids-australian-federal-police-press-freedom/11309810|title=AFP wanted fingerprints of journalists behind ABC special forces investigation|last=Lyons|first=the ABC's head of investigative journalism John|date=15 July 2019|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> This places a tension between freedom and sovereignty.\n\n==== Freedom of religion ====\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP with Huyghur delegates and Sen James Paterson 30 November 2019 photographed by D Birch.jpg|thumb|Delegates from Australia's Uyghur community, Sadam and Almas, meeting with Andrew Hastie MP (on left) and Senator James Paterson (right) at Parliament House, Canberra, in November 2019.]]\nWhile an observant Christian<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2 May 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Hastie holds to the view that if the law allows him to practice his faith, it must allow all to express their faith, or lack of it. That means, in Australia, that while he personally finds the burka \"repugnant\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2 May 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> as it \"defaces the personhood of women\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2 May 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> he would be very reluctant to have the state controlling it, as it's an expression of religious belief.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2 May 2017|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> Hastie advocates strongly for freedom of religion as a basic human right across the globe, including the right of [[Uyghurs]] to practice their faith in China's Xingjian Province, saying \"it's our duty to stand up for them, and argue the point, and ask for their freedom.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-17/andrew-hastie-james-paterson-refuse-to-repent-china-criticism/11712160|title=Hastie and Paterson defiant in the face of China's calls for repentance|last=Dalzell|first=political reporter Stephanie|last2=Editor|first2=Political|date=17 November 2019|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=10 April 2020|last3=Probyn|first3=rew}}</ref> After [[The New York Times]] published the [[Xinjiang papers]] Hastie expressed deep empathy for those with personal ties to Uighurs facing \"systemic persecution and internment\".<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/liberal-mp-and-outspoken-china-critic-vows-uighur-loved-ones-will-not-be-forgotten|title=Liberal MP and outspoken China critic vows Uighur \u2018loved ones\u2019 will not be forgotten|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>  The documents showed how China views their the Muslim people of that region as being \"infected, as they say, with unhealthy thoughts\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-17/andrew-hastie-james-paterson-refuse-to-repent-china-criticism/11712160|title=Hastie and Paterson defiant in the face of China's calls for repentance|last=Dalzell|first=political reporter Stephanie|last2=Editor|first2=Political|date=17 November 2019|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=10 April 2020|last3=Probyn|first3=rew}}</ref> forcing millions into the communist government's [[Xinjiang re-education camps|Xinjiang re-education program]]. Hastie urged Uyghur people in Australia, and in China, not to give up hope.<ref name=\":7\" /> \n\n=== Sovereignty ===\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP with Mayor Rhys Williams at March 2020 Citizenship Ceremony in Mandurah photo taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|The Mayor of Mandurah, Rhys Williams, with Andrew Hastie MP, hosting an Australian Citizenship ceremony in March 2020]]\nHastie argues that Australia's representatives must be the ones making decisions that affect Australia's future, and so \"upholding our political system is the first thing that we must do because that at least preserves our political leadership and their ability to make decisions, un-influence by greater powers.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/5792-insight-australia-s-relationship-with-china-andrew-hastie-mp|title=INSIGHT: Australia\u2019s relationship with China \u2013 Andrew Hastie MP|last=Levy|first=Tasha|last2=Levy|first2=Tasha|date=19 March 2020|website=www.defenceconnect.com.au|language=en|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> As such he strongly resists foreign influence on the working of the Australian economy, culture or political system. \"My bottom line is Australian sovereignty \u2013 I want to protect our way of life, our freedom of action and our political institutions. That's my job as a member of the Commonwealth Parliament. I make no apologies for it.\"<ref name=\"Haaretz\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-a-dead-spy-chinese-hackers-and-the-australian-commando-warning-israel-1.8223349|title=A Dead Spy, Chinese Hackers and the Australian Commando Warning Israel|date=6 December 2019|work=Haaretz|access-date=18 December 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Economic sovereignty ====\nInterestingly, Hastie locates the energy debates as sovereignty issue, and in 2018 said, \"I have a problem legislating the Paris target because it undermines Australia's 'economic sovereignty'\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kelly|first=Joe|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/andrew-hastie-confirms-we-cannot-support-neg-in-current-form/news-story/48af53948ad288198550fdb68617f947|title=Andrew Hastie confirms he cannot support NEG in current form|date=16 August 2018|work=The Australian|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which meant he could not support the [[National Energy Guarantee]] (sometimes called \"the NEG\"). The next month he made a speech in the Federation Chamber, saying, \"Australian industry and Australian workers must come first. When it comes to energy, we must put the Australian people before Paris.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;db=CHAMBER;id=chamber/hansardr/b8101fb1-edde-4753-a50e-1709934db485/0350;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b8101fb1-edde-4753-a50e-1709934db485/0329%22|title=ParlInfo - Federation Chamber : PRIVATE MEMBERS' BUSINESS : Alcoa|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Sovereignty and political warfare ====\nThis has been the main legislative focus for Hastie in recent times. In an interview with the Israeli newspaper ''Haaretz'', Hastie explained that, \"Democratic countries must take domestic measures to protect against these threats. Australia has led the way in this regard. Authoritarian states use all instruments of state power to pursue their strategic objectives. Seemingly innocent activities like diplomacy, foreign-investment flows into strategic industries and infrastructure acquisitions like the purchase of ports are not so innocuous. Democracies who don't pay attention to these activities \u2013 and take measures to guard against them \u2013 risk becoming tethered to hyper-modern authoritarian states and losing their sovereignty in the process.\"<ref name=\"Haaretz\"/>\n\n==== Digital sovereignty ====\nHastie frames questions to do with the provision of information networks as a matter of sovereignty, which must be defended. Given that companies such as Huawei would be legally required to pass on information carried on their networks to the Chinese government,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/05/huawei-would-have-to-give-data-to-china-government-if-asked-experts.html|title=Huawei says it would never hand data to China's government. Experts say it wouldn't have a choice|last=Kharpal|first=Arjun|date=5 March 2019|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Hastie was a strong supporter of the Turnbull Government's decision to prevent that company from providing 5G services in Australia. Along with other parliamentarians from the Liberal Party, including [[Tim Wilson (Australian politician)|Tim Wilson]] and [[James Paterson (Australian politician)|James Paterson]] and [[Australian Labor Party|Labor's]] [[Kimberley Kitching]] and [[Anthony Byrne (politician)|Anthony Byrne]], he has been active in applying pressure to Australia's partners in the [[Five Eyes]] security alliance to do the same. In a public statement he explained how important that security arrangement is, \"In a time of growing strategic uncertainty, Australia values that membership more than ever.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/four-australian-mps-urge-britain-to-ban-huawei-20200124-p53u9x.html|title=Four Australian MPs urge Britain to ban Huawei|last=Bourke|first=Latika|date=23 January 2020|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> In private settings, it is known that he has supported Byrne, the Deputy Chair of the committee Hastie leads, who used forceful language with the UK leadership, asking \u201cHow would you feel if the Russians laid down infrastructure in your own networks? That\u2019s how we feel about Huawei.\u201d Hastie is quoted as supporting frank conversation about data sovereignty with western allies, saying \"We save our toughest talk for our closest mates. I back my deputy chair.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=Lucy Fisher, Defence Editor {{!}} Caroline Wheeler, The Sunday|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/huawei-decision-may-threaten-trade-deal-with-us-says-mike-pence-vlg9d6ggs|title=Mike Pence and Tory MPs attack Boris Johnson over Huawei decision|access-date=12 February 2020|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n==== Enemies, allies and sovereignty ====\nIn May 2018, Hastie took the \"dramatic\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/andrew-hastie-senate-estimates/9797718|title=ASIO boss says Hastie's allegations have had no impact on intelligence allies|last=Gribbin|first=political reporter Caitlyn|date=24 May 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> step of using parliamentary privilege to name a Chinese-Australian property developer as being a corrupt person acting in the interests of a foreign power, saying, \"It is now my duty to inform the House and the Australian people that CC-3 is Chau Chak Wing, the same man who co-conspired to bribe the president of the United Nations General Assembly, John Ashe, the same man with extensive contacts in the Chinese Communist Party, including the United Front.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baumgaertner|first=Emily|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/world/australia/bribery-un-china-chau-chak-wing.html|title=In Australia, Fears of Chinese Meddling Rise on U.N. Bribery Case Revelation|date=22 May 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=22 March 2020|last2=Williams|first2=Jacqueline|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The information had been given to the MP during meetings in the United States earlier that year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baumgaertner|first=Emily|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/world/australia/bribery-un-china-chau-chak-wing.html|title=In Australia, Fears of Chinese Meddling Rise on U.N. Bribery Case Revelation|date=22 May 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=22 March 2020|last2=Williams|first2=Jacqueline|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The move was criticised as \"causing trouble\" both to the government to Australia's relationship with China.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/analysis-andrew-hastie-chau-chak-wing-complex-situation/9795766|title=Here's why Andrew Hastie named Chau Chak Wing in Parliament|last=Editor|first=Political|last2=Probyn|first2=rew|date=24 May 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Hastie himself believed he was compelled to speak as, \"My duty, first and foremost, is to the Australian people and the preservation of the ideals and democratic traditions of our Commonwealth.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/why-andrew-hastie-australias-uberpatriot-mp-risked-chinas-wrath-20180524-h10ie6|title=Why Andrew Hastie, Australia's uber-patriot MP, risked China's wrath|date=24 May 2018|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:AH and Gen Mattis.jpg|thumb|Hastie with General Jim Mattis outside the Pentagon on 4 May 2018]]\nWhile the incident gave another example of the parliamentarian's determination to protect Australian institutions from the influence of the Chinese Communist Party<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/political-donor-chau-chak-wing-behind-un-bribe-scandal-parliament-told-20180522-p4zgs5.html|title=Political donor Chau Chak Wing behind UN bribe scandal, Parliament told|last=Baker|first=Nick McKenzie, Richard|date=22 May 2018|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> his acting in consort with American defence forces and intelligence agencies such as the Department of Justice<ref>{{Cite news|last=Karp|first=Paul|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/may/24/andrew-hasties-use-of-us-intelligence-over-bribery-allegation-a-concern-dreyfus-says|title=Andrew Hastie's use of US intelligence over bribery allegation 'a concern', Dreyfus says|date=24 May 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=22 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> also provided more proof of his commitment to the [[U.S.-Australia alliance]]. At the high level, Hastie believes that this alliance is essential to Australia maintaining its sovereignty saying, \u201cNational leaders must affirm and articulate the values that define Western democracies, especially as we seek to build a coalition of like-minded partners to resist authoritarian political warfare.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/challenge-to-democracy-to-counter-russia-china-20191204-p53gzj.html|title=Challenge to democracy to counter Russia, China|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=9 December 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> He led a parliamentary delegation to the United States in early 2017 and afterwards indicated that, for him, the defence alliance holds personal importance<blockquote>\u201cWhen we met with House and Senate leaders, and members of the [US] House Intelligence Committee, those committee members really emphasised the importance of the relationship... I was sitting there in front of the Senate Intelligence and Security Committee and the committee minority leader is a senator from Virginia and I said to him, \u2018I wouldn't be sitting here if it wasn\u2019t for a medic from Virginia who saved my grandfather\u2019s life on the 31st of March 1945\u2019.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/4466943/hastie-promoted-to-key-national-security-role/|title=Hastie promoted to key national security role|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=14 February 2017|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Community ===\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP Age Care Community Visit.jpg|thumb|Andrew Hastie MP visiting Amana Living Meadow Springs Village, an Anglican age care community in Mandurah.]]Hastie's experiences in Afghanistan, especially in seeing how limited the military is in reshaping people's lives, seems to have given him an even higher view of community, culture and local institutions. In an interview about his wartime experiences, he said:<blockquote> For me, it proved that culture and geography (are) decisive in the formation of societies and political institutions. Building lasting, trusted institutions takes time, generations of stewardship and public virtue.<ref name=\"Whinnett\"/></blockquote>\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP with son Jonathan at the 2018 ANZAC Day March in Mandurah WA taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|His son Jonathan holding his hand, Andrew Hastie marches with veterans on [[Anzac Day]] in Mandurah. ]]\n\n Looking at Australia, Hastie believes that it is local institutions that provide civic foundations of \"accountability, freedom and democracy.\"<ref name=\"First Speech\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/first_speech|title=First Speech|website=Andrew Hastie MP|language=en|access-date=20 December 2019}}</ref> He argued in his first speech that the first of these institutions is the family, which \"is central to a healthy society\"<ref name=\"First Speech\"/> but also extends to sporting clubs, service clubs, churches and local businesses.<ref name=\"First Speech\"/> In one op-ed, Hastie went even further, suggesting that community groups, or \"pre-political institutions\" are finally more important than governments:<blockquote> \"More powerful than the political levers of government are grassroots volunteer movements and pre-political institutions... Pre-political institutions are the best place for securing our freedoms and so we should take encouragement that democratic governments cannot control them, and are sent packing when they attempt to do so.\"<ref name=\"theaustralian.com.au\">{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/opinion/political-class-ignored-the-people-and-paid-the-price/news-story/f1d35ad7c29f76daf08768182b316d55|title=Political class ignored the people and paid the price|date=November 23, 2016|work=The Australian|access-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==== The power of community and PTSD ====\nHastie reflected on how his grandfather recovered from the trauma of [[World War II]] thanks, in part to the power of community, and laments that we may not have that power available to us now, \"Just thinking of my grandfather's own experience, he was shot up quite badly in the second world war where civil society was still very strong, community was still very strong, a lot of local clubs and organisations, I think he struggled with [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|PTSD]] but I think his PTSD was mitigated by those little platoons that we talk about, he was very close to his comrades from the second war, and I'm just not sure if we have in today's society that same sort of cushioning and community support as we had 70 years ago.\"<ref name=\"Grattan\"/>\n\n==== Community and environment ====\nWhile environmental concern is often seen as a progressive cause, Hastie sets the environment between two concerns - that, as per the [[Edmund Burke|Burkean]] contract - the good things inherited should be passed on to the next generation. And that the environment serves the community, which means they need to make the decisions about it. In a recent controversy about a proposed dredging of an estuary, Hastie said: <blockquote>\"I believe in the sovereignty of local communities to make decisions about how they conserve and develop their environment. The Bindjareb people, the First Australians in my constituency, have long been custodians of the waterways\u2014for many generations back to the present. The Murray Mandurah community also shares this responsibility, and together we are all stewards of the beautiful Peel-Harvey Estuary, a body of water larger than Sydney Harbour, teeming with marine life and brimming with natural beauty. We, therefore, through our local governments, have sovereignty over this natural asset and should have a say about how development takes place. We're not antiprogress, but we are rightly cautious about development, as we are the ones most affected by it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openaustralia.org.au/debates/?id=2019-09-11.151.1&s=speaker:10843#g151.2|title=Peel-Harvey Estuary: 11 Sep 2019: House debates (OpenAustralia.org)|website=www.openaustralia.org.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:AH with family (KN).jpg|thumb|Ruth and Andrew Hastie with their children in Mandurah, October 2018]]\nHastie met his wife Ruth in the summer of 2007 while he was studying at [[George Washington University]]. Their first date was \"watching then President George W. Bush walk from the Oval Office across the lawns of the White House to be whisked away in the Marine One helicopter.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/from-fighting-taliban-to-federal-politics-andrew-hastie-was-born-to-serve/news-story/af994f98fccf82ea9385ae465c00bc7c|title=From fighting Taliban to Federal politics|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|date=5 December 2015|website=Herald Sun|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Some months later, Hastie proposed to Ruth on the steps of the [[Sydney Opera House]]. The two were married in 2008 at [[Capitol Hill Baptist Church]]. Their children were born in Perth in June 2015 and August 2017. The family of four now lives in the [[City of Mandurah]] in the [[Peel (Western Australia)|Peel]] region of [[Western Australia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=For God and country|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/weekend-australian-magazine/sas-commander-liberal-party-rising-star-how-far-can-andrew-hastie-go/news-story/327a82373c4e90755402c1388506a502|accessdate=18 April 2018|agency=The Australian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Andrew|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/about_andrew|website=www.andrewhastie.com|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe credits his family for giving him a love for reading, especially \"biographies, Shakespeare, psalms\"<ref name=\"Development\"/> along with history. Favourite historians include [[Geoffrey Blainey]], [[H. W. Brands]], [[Niall Ferguson]], [[Andrew Roberts (historian)|Andrew Roberts]] and [[Ronald C. White]]. He also enjoys 20th century novelists such as [[Graham Greene]], [[Cormac McCarthy]] and [[P. G. Wodehouse]].\n\nFellow parliamentarians recognise Hastie as \u201ca man of deep faith\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openaustralia.org.au/debates/?id=2018-10-24.163.2&s=speaker:10843#g180.1|title=National Apology to Victims and...: 24 Oct 2018: House debates (OpenAustralia.org)|website=www.openaustralia.org.au|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> which he shares with his parents and siblings. Whilst he is frequently ridiculed as being \u201cfundamentalist\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themonthly.com.au/blog/mungo-maccallum/2018/28/2018/1527472468/hastie-judgement|title=Hastie judgement|last=kateg@themonthly.com.au1515708219|date=28 May 2018|website=The Monthly|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> he has been active across several reformed, evangelical and Protestant church communities with historic understandings of the Christian faith, including [[Capitol Hill Baptist Church]] in Washington DC, Shenton Park [[Anglican Church of Australia|Anglican Church]] in the North of Perth<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wahlquist|first=Calla|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/sep/03/canning-byelection-andrew-hastie-deems-questions-on-family-and-religion-unacceptable|title=Canning byelection: Andrew Hastie deems questions on family and religion 'unacceptable'|date=3 September 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=24 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and Crossroads Church in Canberra (an independent Evangelical Church) Hastie actually identifies with the Scottish Presbyterian faith in which he was raised<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/analysis-andrew-hastie-chau-chak-wing-complex-situation/9795766|title=Here's why Andrew Hastie named Chau Chak Wing in Parliament|last=Editor|first=Political|last2=Probyn|first2=rew|date=24 May 2018|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> and his family church in Mandurah today is part of the [[Presbyterian Church of Australia]]. Having rejected Christian belief in his teens for several years, Hastie has spoken of how only a theistic understanding of the world makes any sense of the death and suffering he has personally witnessed, that if he were \"a closed universe atheist, how bleak and senseless those deaths would be\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sheridan|first=Greg|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/inquirer/politicians-reveal-what-religion-means-to-them/news-story/ad54c5d1948393ae00cf20b9445372d1|title=In defence of Christianity|date=23 July 2018|work=The Australian|accessdate=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n<center>\n\n[[File:Australian Active Service Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n\n[[File:Afghanistan Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Australian Service Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Australian Defence Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar v2.svg|100px]]\n\n[[File:AUS Meritorious Unit Citation with Federation Star.png|100px]]\n\n</center>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|[[File:Australian Active Service Medal ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the AASM]] || [[Australian Active Service Medal]] || with clasp for [[Australian Active Service Medal#ICAT|ICAT]]\n|-\n|[[File:Afghanistan Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the Afghanistan Medal for Australia]] || [[Afghanistan Medal (Australia)|Afghanistan Medal]] || Operation SLIPPER\n|-\n|[[File:Australian Service Medal ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the Australian Service Medal]] || [[Australian Service Medal]] || with clasp for CT/SR (Counter Terrorism / Special Recovery)<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://defence-honours-tribunal.gov.au/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/SASR-Final-Report-Public-Release.pdf|title = INQUIRY INTO RECOGNITION OF AUSTRALIAN DEFENCE FORCE SERVICE FOR SPECIAL AIR SERVICE COUNTER TERRORIST AND SPECIAL RECOVERY DUTIES|date = 22 December 2009|accessdate = 20 September 2015|website = Defence Honours Tribunal|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Australian Defence Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the ADM]] || [[Australian Defence Medal]] ||\n|-\n|[[File:NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar v2.svg|50px]] || [[NATO Medal#Non-Article 5 Medal|NATO Medal for the Non-Article 5 ISAF Operation in Afghanistan]] || with clasp ''ISAF''\n|-\n|[[File:AUS Meritorious U